[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Foreword"]
[Black "A few words from IM Mikel Huerga"]
[Result "*"]

{ Several months ago, Josu  (aka Jestfer)  came to me with the idea of working together on a project. He asked me to endorse a book on the Grünfeld that he had in mind.  I have been Josu's coach for a few years, and, at first, even though I know well how capable and thorough he is in everything he does, I thought he was taking on a very difficult project.  The Grünfeld is undoubtedly one of the best defenses against the Queen’s Pawn opening. But wouldn’t it be too ambitious? Nevertheless, after a couple of talks with Josu he convinced me. He knows the amount of theory that comes with the Grünfeld, but he also understands the ideas behind the different variations, and he had recently worked on that! All these reasons combined made him a perfect candidate to offer many ideas in the Grünfeld.  The Grünfeld has been a part of my personal repertoire for 10 years so I decided to work with Josu and to share some interesting ideas of my own.  It has been months of hard work, choosing variations, solving problems  (especially with tricky transpositions!)  , but also of finding a good way out of positions that were not completely satisfactory.  Now, after seeing this course finished, I think we have enough reasons to feel satisfied. Throughout the whole course, the student can expect a very fresh, up-to-date touch on the Grünfeld. The course strikes a perfect balance between engine contributions and the human approach to chess. There are plenty of novelties and, again, a good balance between super main lines, interesting and strong sidelines and, finally, surprise weapons.  We believe we are offering a great tool against Queen’s Pawn players. A tool that can benefit casual and advanced players alike, and also expert players ranging from FMs to GMs.  IM Mikel Huerga Leache }
