[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction and Appetizers"]
[Black "The GrÃ¼nfeld Revisited - Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ This move defines the Grunfeld Defense. This is a hypermodern defense for Black which temporarily allows White to expand on the centre, taking over it and all that just to launch a strong counterattack !  The typical pawn breaks in the Grunfeld will be, from more common to less: ... c5, ...e5 and, finally, ...f5, which is a resource that we may need to use when both ...c5 and ...e5 are not possible. }
4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7
{ The dark-squared bishop will be one of our reference pieces on the board. In some variations it becomes really strong and is a constant annoyance for White ! }
7. Bc4
{ This is the old, classical Exchange Variation.  Now, how should we proceed ? It is all about timing ! ...O-O may be too slow   actually it is not in this variation, but it is a slow move against the modern Exchange Variation, which starts with  7.Nf3  c5 !  This is something you should get a feeling of when playing the Grunfeld. There is not enough pressure in White's centre and White could just consolidate his position, we must therefore play: }
7... c5
{ If there is something you should learn from this Introduction lesson is the following: 'Remember that, in the Grunfeld, we give White the centre temporarily in order to make it crumble to dust later on !' }
8. Ne2
{ But why ...Ne2 instead of ...Nf3 ? Well, against the Grunfeld, the knight on f3 and the bishop on c4 do not work very well together. Also, Nf3 allows ... Bg4 ! A thematic idea in the Grunfeld to pin the knight and apply even more pressure against White's center ! }
8... Nc6 { Putting more pressure on White's centre ! } 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O
{ This is a well-known tabiya in the Grunfeld within the classical Exchange Variation.  There are many options available for both sides and many of them are really interesting ! If you feel curious about the appetizers, check the games out ! Otherwise, start with the Course Chapters whenever you are ready ! Enjoy your study ! }
*

