1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. g3
{ This is a variation that has been used a lot and which is really interesting. }
5... dxc4 6. Qa4+ Nfd7 { The main and the best move in this line. } 7. Qxc4 Nb6
8. Qd3 O-O 9. Bf4 Nc6 10. Rd1 Bf5 11. Qd2 Bg4
{ We can see how Carlsen exerts pressure on d4, the key element of the position and the center of the fight. }
12. Bg2 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nxd4 14. Bxb7 Nc4 15. Qc1 Rb8 16. b3 Rxb7 17. bxc4 c5 18.
O-O Rb4 19. Bh6 Bxh6 20. Qxh6 Rxc4 21. Ne4 Nxe2+ 22. Kg2 Qa8 23. f3 Rxe4
{ Pretty much forced. } 24. fxe4 Qxe4+ 25. Kf2 Nd4 26. Qe3 Qd5 27. Rd2 e5
{ The game is already decided and Black has a decisive advantage. } 28. Re1 Re8
29. Qe4 Qe6 30. Re3 Kg7 31. Rb2 c4 32. g4 Qf6+ 33. Ke1 Qg5 34. Kf2 Re6 35. Ke1
h5 36. h3 Rf6 37. Kd2 Rf4 38. Qxe5+ Qxe5 39. Rxe5 Nf3+ 40. Ke3 Nxe5 41. Kxf4
Nd3+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction and Appetizers"]
[Black "Nakamura, Hikaru vs. Svidler, Peter -  Moscow Tal Memorial (2011)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4 c5 8.
Ne2 Nc6 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O Bg4
{ The absolute main line of the classical Exchange Variation. Black combines development and pressure on White's centre in order to prevent White from securing his space advantage in the long run or switching to a successful kingside attack. }
11. f3
{ The well-known tabiya of the 80's that was the object of many debates. }
11... Bd7
{ Initially 11... Na5 was considered the main and only logical move. } 12. Rb1
Qc7 13. Bd3 Rfd8 14. Qd2 a6 15. f4 e6 16. dxc5
{ A key moment, the pawn structure is forever changed. We should pay attention to these details. }
16... Na5 17. Nd4 e5 18. fxe5 Qxe5
{ Stop for a moment and observe the current position. What is the truth of the position according to you ? How would you evaluate it ? It is not an easy position to evaluate, but let's observe a few points:  1  White has his minor pieces centralized, which seems to help controlling the centre.  2  The rooks seem active.  However, Black is not unhappy. Even though White's minor pieces are centralised, they lack some purpose. They are not carrying out active tasks ! The knight is blocking the d-file, whereas the dark-squared bishop is defending too.  Black, on the other hand, is a pawn down, but it is up to White to show that it is worth something ! }
19. Qb2 Rac8 20. Qb4 { Hikaru takes the defense of the c5-pawn too seriously. }
20... Qxc5 21. Qxc5 Rxc5 22. Ne2 Rc6 23. Bb6 Rxb6
{ A great concept by Svidler. The exchange sacrifice is really instructive. }
24. Rxb6 Bc6
{ White's position is far from coordinated. The pawn structure is severely weakened and Black is just better despite the fact that he has sacrificed the exchange. }
25. Rf3 f5 26. Rb4 Bf8 27. Rd4 Bc5 28. Re3 Re8 29. e5 Bd5 30. Kf2 Bxa2 31. Ra4
Bxe3+ 32. Kxe3 Rxe5+ 33. Kf4 Bb3 34. Kxe5 Bxa4 35. Kd6 Bc6 36. g3 Kg7 37. Nd4
Be4 38. Bxe4 fxe4 39. Nc2 Nc4+ 40. Kd5 Nd2 41. Kc5 Kf6 42. Kb6 Ke5 43. Kxb7 Kd5
44. Ne3+ Kc5 45. Kxa6 Nb1 46. Kb7 Nxc3 47. Kc8 Kd4 48. Ng2 Kd3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction and Appetizers"]
[Black "Donald Byrne vs. Robert James Fischer - Third Rosenwald Trophy (1956)"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. d4 O-O 5. Bf4 d5 6. Qb3 dxc4 7. Qxc4 c6 8. e4
Nbd7 9. Rd1 Nb6 10. Qc5 Bg4 11. Bg5 Na4 12. Qa3
{ 12. Nxa4 is met by Nxe4 and White is in serious trouble. } 12... Nxc3
{ You may have the wrong impression that we help White bring a pawn to the center. But nothing further from the truth, Fischer's plan is actually to destroy the center ! He sacrificies an exchange in a very instructive way in order to demolish White's centre. }
13. bxc3 Nxe4 14. Bxe7 Qb6 15. Bc4 Nxc3 16. Bc5 Rfe8+ 17. Kf1 Be6
{ A move that will remain forever in the annals of chess history. Fischer sacrifices the queen for a very strong initiative and attack with the rest of the pieces. }
18. Bxb6
{ 18.Bxe6  White falls on the trap and faces the 'Philidor Mate'.  18...Qb5+  19.Kg1  Ne2+  20.Kf1  Ng3+  21.Kg1  Qf1+  22.Rxf1  Ne2# }
18... Bxc4+ 19. Kg1 Ne2+ 20. Kf1 Nxd4+ 21. Kg1 Ne2+ 22. Kf1 Nc3+ 23. Kg1 axb6
24. Qb4 Ra4 25. Qxb6 Nxd1 26. h3 Rxa2 27. Kh2 Nxf2 28. Re1 Rxe1 29. Qd8+ Bf8
30. Nxe1 Bd5 31. Nf3 Ne4 32. Qb8 b5
{ The queen looks beautiful and with lots of space. However, everything in Black's position is defended. What is White supposed to do ? }
33. h4 h5 34. Ne5 Kg7 35. Kg1 Bc5+ 36. Kf1 Ng3+
{ Now Byrne finds himself entangled in Fischer's mating net. } 37. Ke1 Bb4+ 38.
Kd1 Bb3+ 39. Kc1 Ne2+ 40. Kb1 Nc3+ 41. Kc1 Rc2# *

