1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5 Ne4 5. cxd5 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Qxd5 7. Nf3 Bg7 8.
e3 c5
{ It was a reality in 1922 and it is a reality nowadays, Black needs this pawn break to get counterplay ! And that is something that Gruenfeld understood very well. }
9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. c4 Qe4 11. O-O Bxb5 12. cxb5 Nd7 13. Rc1 b6 14. Qb3 h6 15. Bh4
O-O 16. Rc4 Qe6 17. Rd1 Rfe8 { Black gets ready to play ...e5. } 18. d5 Qd6 19.
Bg3 e5 20. dxe6 Qxe6 21. Rd6 Qe7 22. Ra4 Nf8 23. Qd5 Rad8 24. Nd2 Rxd6 25. Bxd6
