[White "Introduction and Appetizers"]
[Black "Topalov, Veselin vs. Shirov, Alexei - Linares 15th (1998)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bb5+
{ Not the most exciting variation. However, wait to the endgame and you will understand why I included this game in the appetizers ! }
7... c6 8. Ba4 O-O 9. Ne2 Nd7 10. O-O e5 11. f3 Qe7 12. Be3 Rd8 13. Qc2 Nb6 14.
Bb3 Be6 15. Rad1 Nc4 16. Bc1 b5 17. f4 exd4 18. Nxd4 Bg4 19. Rde1 Qc5 20. Kh1
a5 21. h3 Bd7 22. a4 bxa4 23. Ba2 Be8 24. e5 Nb6 25. f5 Nd5 26. Bd2 Nb4 27.
Qxa4 Nxa2 28. Qxa2 Bxe5 29. fxg6 hxg6 30. Bg5 Rd5 31. Re3 Qd6 32. Qe2 Bd7 33.
c4 Bxd4 34. cxd5 Bxe3 35. Qxe3 Re8 36. Qc3 Qxd5 37. Bh6 Re5 38. Rf3 Qc5 39. Qa1
Bf5 40. Re3 f6 41. Rxe5 Qxe5 42. Qa2+ Qd5 43. Qxd5+ cxd5 44. Bd2 a4 45. Bc3 Kf7
46. h4 Ke6 47. Kg1 Bh3
{ There you go ! This is the reason why I included this game, just this move ! Shirov found this fascinating move as he needed to push his two pawns as quickly as possible. The bishop is on the king's way to e4, so by going to h3, it wins the tempo it needs ! }
48. gxh3 { 48.Kf2  Kf5  49.Kf3  Bxg2+  50.Kxg2  Ke4  -+  (Shirov) } 48... Kf5
49. Kf2 Ke4 50. Bxf6 d4 51. Be7 Kd3 52. Bc5 Kc4 53. Be7 Kb3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction and Appetizers"]
[Black "Navara, David vs. Vachier Lagrave, Maxime - Bundesliga (2018)"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this game, we have a great example of dynamic advantage. MVL will do whatever is necessary to keep a strong initiative ! }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3
{ With this move, we enter the Russian System. White gets to exert pressure on the center before Black. In exchange, the queen may be misplaced at some point and we can benefit from gaining some tempi, often translated into an initiative. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Nc6 8. Be2 e5
{ Black rapidly challenges the center. This variation is far from being the main line for Black. However, it happens to be one of Vachier-Lagrave's favourite ones in these lines ! }
9. d5 Nd4 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Qxd4 c6 12. Qc4 b5 13. Qxc6 Bd7 14. Qd6
{ Vachier-Lagrave has sacrified two pawns, but then, what does he get in exchange for that ? In his mind probably was the idea of progressively annoy White's development and not allowing him to castle. White is already behind ! }
14... Re8 15. Bd3 a5
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that White cannot take on b5 as otherwise e4 would be hanging. }
16. f3 { White defends e4 and gets ready to take on b5. } 16... b4
{ But there is no time for that ! With 15... a5, Black wanted to support the b4 push. }
17. Ne2 Bf8 18. Qg3 Qb6 19. Bg5 Rac8 20. Qf2 Bc5 21. Qh4 Nxd5
{ A great tactical blow ! } 22. Bc4 h6 23. Bxd5 hxg5 24. Qxg5 Bf2+ 25. Kf1 Bb5
26. Qd2 Be3 27. Qd1 Qf6 28. Ke1 a4 29. Rb1 Rc7 30. b3 a3 31. f4 Rec8
{ White's position is about to collapse. } 32. e5 Qf5 33. Bc4 Rd7 34. Bxb5
Rxd1+ 35. Rxd1 Qc2 36. e6 fxe6 37. Bd7 Rc3 38. Bxe6+ Kf8
{ And Navara surrendered. A great display of active play from MVL. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction and Appetizers"]
[Black "Pascua, Haridas vs. Laylo, Darwin - Quezon City op (2014)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2
e5 9. d5 c6 10. O-O-O cxd5 11. exd5 Na6 12. h4 h5 13. Be2 Bd7 14. g4
{ This move does not seem to be a mistake, but White is not ready to start operations on the kingside. He has other things to worry about on the queenside first. 14. Kb1 would have been a better attempt. }
14... Rc8 15. gxh5
{ This is an important moment. It looks intimidating at first sight to let White take on h5. So, what does Black get in exchange ? }
15... Nb4 { Black is threatening checkmate if White does nothing ! } 16. Kb1
{ A needed move.   16.Nh3 ??  Bf5 !  17.Ng5  Nxa2# } 16... Nc4
{ Making use of the c4 outpost, a common motif that we will see over and over again in the Grunfeld ! }
17. Bxc4 Bf5+
{ This is the answer to the previous question. Black gets the important f5 square for the bishop. It becomes a very important positional factor now as White's light-squared bishop is about to disappear from the board. }
18. Ne4 Rxc4 { Black has a decisive advantage. } 19. Qg2 Qa5 20. a3 Nxd5 21.
Bc1 Qa4 22. Re1 Qb3 23. Ka1 Rfc8 24. Ne2 Nb4 25. axb4 Qa4+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction and Appetizers"]
[Black "Farago, Ivan vs. Ftacnik, Lubomir - Passau op (1994)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3 c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 7. cxd5
{ This is an alternative line that has not been played much in practice as White realised that Black does not have any problems. The absolute main line of the 4. Bf4 variation would be 7. Rc1. }
7... Nxd5 8. Qxd5 { Other moves are clearly worse for White. } 8... Bxc3+ 9.
bxc3 Qxc3+ 10. Ke2 Qxa1 11. Be5 Qb1
{ Black chooses the ambitious line here. You will find an informational line as part of the 4. Bf4 chapter where I show how Black can force a draw if desired with 11... Qc1. }
12. Bxh8 Be6 13. Qd3 Qxa2+ 14. Kf3 f6
{ An important moment. Now White has to decide if he wants to save the bishop. If so, Black will generate a strong initiative. }
15. Kg3 { This alternative to 15. Bg7 is not better. } 15... Kf7 16. Nf3
{ This is a mistake. White cannot coordinate his position with this move, which also happens to get White into tactical variations that favor Black. 16. Nh3, for example, was certainly a better attempt. }
16... Nd7 17. Qc3 Qd5
{ Now Black is threatening both the bishop on h8 and the pawn on c5, while not allowing White to carry out his plan. }
18. h4 Nxc5 19. Ng5+ Qxg5+
{ There was no need for this. Black is better off taking with the pawn.   19...fxg5  20.Qg7+  Ke8  21.Bb5+  Nd7  -+  Everything is defended ! White's king is in a really poor condition. }
20. hxg5 Ne4+ 21. Kf4 Nxc3 22. Rxh7+ Kg8 23. Rh6 Rf8 24. Bd3
{ The final mistake. Now Ftacnik has an easy life creating yet another threat pushing the a pawn. }
24... a5 25. Bxg6
{ White achieves nothing with his bishops and his rook. There is no real threat. }
25... a4 26. Bd3 a3 27. gxf6 exf6 28. Rh1 a2 29. Bh7+ Kf7 *

