[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Summaries"]
[Black "The GrÃ¼nfeld Revisited - Global Quick Summary"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this chapter, I want to provide a reference summary so you can have a general overview of the chapters included in this course and which options I recommend against the different approaches White can adopt. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3
{ 3.f3  Known as the Saemisch variation or the Anti-Grunfeld variation.  d5  The main recommendation   3...Nh5 !?  Recommended as a surprise weapon  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4  Nb6   3.g3  The Fianchetto variation.  Bg7  4.Bg2  Both fianchettoed bishops will exert pressure on the centre. In these variations, by nature, we are not playing the asymmetrical structures and unbalanced positions we look for in the Grunfeld.  d5  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.e4  Nb6 }
3... d5 4. cxd5
{ 4.Qa4+  White inserts this check before trying to enter the Russian System.  Bd7  5.Qb3  Nc6 !?  A very interesting approach that exploits White's move-order.   4.e3  The Closed Grunfeld  Bg7  5.Nf3  O-O  6.Be2  c5  Remember the key idea of challenging the center. This is the main line.   4.Bg5  The Taimanov variation. White puts pressure on d5 by attacking the knight on f6, which is a similar idea to ours when we play ...Bg4 in the Exchange Variation.  4...Bg7 !?  A very interesting approach. 4... Ne4 is the main move, but it requires knowing some serious theory and tricky transpositions.  5.Bxf6  The main line. Logically, White will try to prove that we have not enough compensation for the pawn sacrifice.  5...Bxf6  6.cxd5  c6 !  Generating counterplay as quickly as possible. This leads to rich and unbalanced positions we should be happy with.   4.Bf4  The Bishop variations. The key to remember here is that depending on White's setup and move-order, we should adopt different approaches. So in this line it is better to understand the concepts than trying to memorise the variations  (well, that applies in general to learning all openings !)  .  4...Bg7  5.e3  c5 !   4.Nf3  Bg7  5.Qb3  The Russian System. White exerts a lot of pressure on d5 and tries to establish domination on the centre.  5...dxc4  This is what I recommend. We give White a firm grasp on the centre. However, the queen loses a few tempi and we will try to get a significant lead in development and pose some problems.  6.Qxc4  O-O }
4... Nxd5 5. e4
{ 5.Na4 !?  An old, but interesting idea we should know. This move is two-fold: White wants to occupy the whole centre without allowing ...Nxc3. At the same time, he prevents ...c5, our thematic pawn break.  5...Nf6 !?  Responding in kind. It will be very difficult for White to prove any advantage without playing e4. If the repetition is not something you are looking for, I recommend taking a look at 5... e5 !?   5.Bd2 !?  A line that has grown in popularity lately. White's idea is to take on c3 with the bishop. If that happens, our dark-squared bishop, often a very strong piece in the Grunfeld, will have an opposition.  Nb6 !?  5... Bg7 is the main line. However, I like the approach we adopt with this move.   5.Nf3  Bg7  6.Qa4+  Often used as a surprise weapon.  Bd7  7.Qb3  Nxc3  8.bxc3  c5 !  Just remember that this tends to be good for us and give us great counterplay. }
5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4
{ The classical Exchange Variation.   7.Nf3  The modern Exchange Variation.  c5  8.Rb1 !?  The absolute main line.  O-O  9.Be2  cxd4  10.cxd4  Qa5+  11.Bd2  Qxa2  A theory giant and the main line of the modern variation. White plays with a dynamic advantage, whereas we have a static advantage  (the extra material)  . From this positions, many debates have been generated for a long time. }
7... c5 8. Ne2 { The main move. Allowing f3 in case of ...Bg4. } 8... Nc6
{ We keep pressuring White's centre. } 9. Be3 O-O 10. O-O Bd7
{ And this is my recommendation. A positional approach. The main line is ...Bg4. With this move, we have an easy idea to remember now: we want to play moves such as ...Na5, ...Qc7 or ...Rc8. We want to control the c4-square, an anchor point in many variations of the Grunfeld. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Summaries"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld - 3.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works!)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. cxd5
{ This move is by far the most played option in the Grunfeld move order.   5.Nf3  The second most used option for White in this position.  O-O  This is our choice. However, ...dxc4 is also a possibility, as shown in an informational line. With this move order, White has the option of taking on d5, in which case we are following the main line within the 5.Nf3 variation.  6.cxd5  If we consider games from all the different move orders White can use, this is actually the most common line in the Fianchetto. His idea will be to castle and play with e4, trying to establish a good centre and make us lose a tempo with our knight.   6.O-O  dxc4  6... c6 also equalises, so feel free to explore this option. However, I chose 6... dxc4 because it is consistent with the repertoire and style I propose in this course.  7.Na3  By far the most common and best option for White. 7. Nc3 would transpose to one of the lines seen in 5. Nc3.  Nc6 !?  7... c3 is the main continuation and an option worth exploring if you are interested. However, to keep consistency throughout our repertoire, I recommend this option, which is easier to understand for our purposes. Do not think ...Nc6 is an inferior move at all, it is just another option and has been played by players such as Nepomniachtchi, Dominguez Perez, Nunn and Ftacnik  8.Nxc4  other moves do not make sense  Be6  9.b3  The only serious option for White in order to fight for the advantage.  Bd5  The idea behind this move is three-fold: 1- We threaten ...Bxf3, so we force White to protect the vulnerable pawn on d4. 2- We make it difficult for white to mobilize his knight on f3, as exchanging the light-squared bishops benefits us. 3- It also prevents a potential e4 from White.  6...Nxd5  7.O-O  Nb6 !?  A prophylactic move against e4.  8.Nc3  Nc6  9.e3  It is far more popular than 9. d5  Re8  10.Re1  The most played option for White in this position, opposing the enemy rook on e8 and getting ready to play d5 followed by e4 if ...e5 is played.  a5 !?  In this variation we switch our play entirely to the queenside ! Remember this key move after 9... Re8, making as if we were going to play ...e5   5.Qb3  Is a move that has only been used, in high-level games, by Kempinski in 2005. I have included his game as a reference for you to check.  dxc4  6.Qxc4  White commits his queen too early and loses time, which allows us to have a comfortable lead in development and annoy the queen while placing our pieces on better squares on the queenside.  O-O  7.Nf3  Nc6  8.O-O  Be6 !   5.Nc3  Is another secondary variation that we should know how to face. However, you will be glad to know that this variation is not good for White after our next move, in which White's best variation scores just around 36%!  dxc4 !  We can already fight for the advantage, which can turn into a comfortable and clear advantage in many lines if White does not play accurately.  6.Qa4+  This is White's universal response in the 5... dxc4 variation, with around 200 games. White is threatening to win the pawn back immediately.  Nfd7 !  An odd-looking move. However, this option, chosen by players such as Vachier-Lagrave, Kempinksi and Miles, among other strong GMs, has proved to be a very strong antidote against White's attempt, as we can see from White's score in these variations  (around 29%)  . We want to question the position of the White Queen by winning at least a tempo. Also, this is a prophylactic move against e4.  7.Nf3  White's main option at this point.  Nc6  8.e3  Looks like a solid move. However, the continuation hopefully makes you understand why 8. Qxc4 is a better try and, also, how practical is to enter these lines from Black's perspective, which maintains a better score overall.  Nb6  Winning a tempo on the queen.  9.Qb5  Qd6  10.O-O  a6  11.Qc5  Bf5 !?  A great maneuver, taking advantage of the weak d3 square in White's territory.  12.Ng5  Bd3  13.Rd1  Qxc5  14.dxc5  Bxc3  15.cxb6  Bf6  16.Nh3  O-O-O  17.bxc7  Kxc7  ∓  Black is clearly better. See Malyshev-Savchenko, Moscow op.  2018  . }
5... Nxd5 6. e4
{ The most testing move. The position will acquire an independent nature compared to other lines, which could be reached from different transpositions. Note also how 6. Nf3 transposes to 5. Nf3. }
6... Nb6 7. Ne2
{ White's idea is to play d5 if we play ...Nc6, as we would usually do. After that, we would need to play either . ..e6 or ...c6 to get some space to develop our army. As Rowson mentioned in his book. It is common to see White with a clamping pawn on d5, and we can just slowly play to get rid of it. As we remove the d5 pawn, we uncover the g2-bishop and make it stronger, so White is not totally unhappy with that in any case. }
7... c5
{ It is well known that in the Grunfeld it is important to hit the center as soon as possible. There are other options, like ...Nc6 or ... e5 !? I was indeed considering ...e5 for this repertoire, and it is perfectly playable, but I believe ...c5 matches the rest of our repertoire better in general. }
8. d5 { The main move in this position. } 8... O-O 9. O-O e6
{ A common idea in the Grunfeld, putting pressure in White's center as soon as possible. You should avoid capturing on d5 quickly here, as a pawn advancing to d6 after capturing opens the h1-a8 diagonal for the White bishop. The pawn on d6 on itself is not really dangerous and not the main concern for us, but the pressure exerted by the g2-bishop could prove decisive in some variations. If White advances to d6 himself, that pawn will become vulnerable. As a rule of thumb, we will keep the tension on the centre until White defines where his knights will head to, as we will explore in the different variations now. }
10. Nec3
{ The main move and a stronger continuation  (scores better)  than 10. Nbc3. White coordinates his knights better with this move, as Nd2 is an option, covering the c4 square.   10.Nbc3  The alternative makes our life easier as White's knights will not find the most natural squares and we have interesting ways to take advantage of that.  Na6 !?  The idea is to play ... e5 !? blockade on d6 and play actively with the knights on the queenside, while trying to advance the a-b pawns to gain space. Taking on d5 directly is also an option now that White has defined where his knights will go. }
10... Na6
{ We keep an eye on playing ...e5. The b6-knight will end up on d6, supporting both common pawn breaks: ...f5 and ...b5. Depending on White's play, we will react on one side or the other. }
11. a4 { The main option for White. } 11... exd5 12. exd5 Nc4 13. Nd2
{ White's main option.   13.Na3  An alternative that has been played in a few games.  Ne5 !  An important move to keep in mind. The a3-knight will not have an easy time coming back into the game. }
13... Ne5 14. Nde4 Bg4 { Provoking f3 before heading to d7. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Summaries"]
[Black "The Saemisch - 3.f3 Nh5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ This is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... Nh5
{ Even though this move does not lead to typical Grunfeld positions, I recommend this choice as a surprise weapon. We can indeed catch White off guard with this line in more than one variation. I would like to bring your attention to something. If White plays the strongest moves that he has at his disposal, both IM Mikel Huerga and I have our doubts about Black's position, more precisely about the fact that it is exactly pleasant to play and in the spirit of the Grunfeld. However, we still believe this variation can serve you really well as a surprise for certain games and it has, without any doubts, a very dangerous poison waiting to be released ! Black's idea revolves around a quick ...e5 !, taking advantage of the weak dark-square complex around White's king as we open lines for our queen. At this point, White has four main options: e4, which is the main move, g4, Bg5 and Nc3. }
4. e4
{ White's main option, grabbing more central space.   4.g4  White's attempt to question our knight's position weakens his position and we can play very actively with  e5 !  5.Nh3 !?  White develops his knight to h3 and is ready to meet our Qh4+ ideas with Nf2. As White does not take on e5, we need to come up with a plan and the best way to develop our pieces. The positions that arise from this variation can be sharp, but they will undoubtedly be of the taste of adventurous players.   5.gxh5 ?  Is a mistake and Black is clearly better after a short sequence  Bb4+ !  6.Nc3  White's only move that does not lose on the spot  Qh4+ !  7.Kd2  exd4   5.Be3  Ng7  6.dxe5  Nc6  7.Nc3  Nxe5  GM Kayden W. Troff played 7... Be7, but I recommend taking on e5 first in this situation. They seem similar, but ...Be7 gives White more options which may be better than what followed in the game provided.   5.dxe5 ?  This is a mistake, now the White King is too weak and the dark-square weaknesses are very noticeable.  Qh4+  6.Kd2  Ng3  7.Qe1  Nxf1+  8.Qxf1  After this sequence of force moves, it is clear that Black hast almost a decisive advantage due to the exposed White King and the multiple weaknesses generated.  5...Ng7  6.Nc3  Probably White's most logical continuation.   6.dxe5  Qh4+  7.Nf2  Ne6  8.Nc3  Nc6  9.e3  d6  10.exd6  Bxd6  11.Bg2  h5 !  The position is about equal. You may claim White has a small edge as we are not fully mobilised yet and our pieces are not placed in the best possible squares, but we have dynamic play in the kingside, we will castle longside and prepare to pose White a few problems in order to not make his life easy.  6...Qh4+   4.Bg5  The idea of this move is to prevent ...e5, which would question White about his early f3, weakening the kingside in exchange for imminent control of the center.  Bg7  5.Nc3  h6 !  I believe this is a more accurate move order than what Mikhalevski played, which was 5... c5 in his game against Kavutskiy that happened in Calgary op, 2016 . The idea is to force Be3 or, even better for Black, Bh4 ?!, where the dark-square White bishop loses his influence on the queenside and we are ready to strike with ...c5 !  6.Be3  An original idea, and probably White's best option.   6.Bh4  c5 !  7.d5  transposes to the game mentioned before.  d6  8.e3  Qa5 !  N  We have a very clear plan here and we should delay castling in this position in my opinion. The position is about equal, but we have an easier plan and White will have to spend a few tempo to bring his h4-bishop back into the game later on.  6...c6 !?  We will now break with ...d5 ! Note how White now has to lose an extra tempo to move the e-pawn.  7.Bf2  d5 !  8.e3  O-O =  With a comfortable game.   4.Nc3  e5 !  5.g3  Bg7  6.d5  f5  The position is about equal, yet still playable. In this line we can see that if White does not play accurately, Black gets to equalize without much trouble. White does not have an easy task figuring out where to place his pieces and how to coordinate them. Something I really like about 3... Nh5 !? is the fact that it can be used as a surprise weapon, leading us to positions we will be most likely more familiar with than our opponents. }
4... e5 5. Be3
{ White's best move and the only serious option to fight for the advantage. White supports the center and defends the weak dark square complex in the kingside. This is the variation I mentioned in the introduction which may not be of the like of all players. However, White has to know these lines to play the strongest moves all the time, and these lines are not very common !   5.dxe5 ?  Qh4+ !  6.Kd2  Ng3  =+   5.Nc3  Qh4+ !  6.Ke2  d6  7.g4  Ng7  8.d5  f5 }
5... Bb4+ { We take advantage of this tempo to develop our bishop. } 6. Nc3
exd4 7. Qxd4 O-O 8. O-O-O Nc6 9. Qd2 d6 10. g4 Ng7 11. a3 Ba5
{ We keep pinning the queen on d2, which makes White make up his mind at this point and reduces his flexibility. Also, ...Bb6 is a more attractive option than ...Bc5 directly in my opinion. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Summaries"]
[Black "The Saemisch - 3.f3 d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ This is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... d5 { The f6-Knight usually ends up on b6 in this variation. } 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 { 6. Be3 will most likely transpose after 6... Bg7 7. Nc3 }
6... Bg7
{ Note how now our common plan in the Grunfeld of playing with ...c5 to challenge White's centre does not work as our knight is on b6 and White wins a tempo ! }
7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2
{ The main move in this variation. White keeps his options open and, while castling queenside is common in these positions, followed by advancing the pawns on the kingside, leaving the king on the center in some variations will be possible too, so we need to pay attention as White may go wrong and not assess his options accurately.   8.f4  The most serious attempt for White, after the main move, which is 8. Qd2, to get an advantage.  Nc6  9.d5  White's main move by far.  Nb8 !?  I want to recommend this move over 9... Na5, which is perfectly playable, but I have found that White can win the initiative in some lines I have studied from different sources.  10.a4  The most logical response from White, 10. Nf3, does not work very well due to ...c6 ! We would challenge the center, making room for our pieces and, also, we will follow with the thematic ...e5 !  e5 !  We need to hit the center immediately due to White's threat: a5. We want to release the e5 square for our knight  (Nd7-e5)   8.a4  White tries to question our setup, but by doing so he weakens the b4 square.  a5  fixing the queenside and bolstering the b4 outpost.  9.Rc1  e5 !?  I really like this idea, and it makes even more sense after our next move. It is a recurrent concept on the Grunfeld to break White's center, we can not just let White occupy the center at his will.  10.d5  Bh6 !  N  This is a novelty. The idea is to highlight the weaknesses on White's queenside dark squares by exchanging our 'blocked' bishop. We will try to make use of the b4-square if White allows so.   8.Rc1  Often considered as a waiting move in these variations. It could lead to some tactical variations where White should pay attention not to get a worse position.  Nc6  9.d5  Ne5  10.Bd4  The most played move.  c6 !  We are following Goglidze-Spielmann, Moscow 1935.  11.f4  The only serious option for White. Other moves are not problematic at all for us.  Ng4  12.Bxg7  Kxg7  13.Be2  White may think he has achieved his main goals: natural development, central advantage and exchanging the dark-square bishops, and even taking on c6 and thus getting a better pawn structure on the queenside, but Black has a very strong resource in this position:  e5 !  We make use of some tactics to break through and fully equalise  14.Bxg4  Qh4+  With a complicated position. However, this has been thought to be good for Black for a number of years now. }
8... e5
{ This is my recommendation here. 8.. .e5 leads to very interesting position that I have found lately score slightly better than 8... Nc6 }
9. d5 c6 10. h4
{ This position has been played in multiple high-level games.   10.O-O-O  White must be careful in these lines as we can often generate a very strong initiative against the King.   10.d6  This has not been played much, but we get access to the e6 square and we can play around the d-pawn.  Re8  11.Rd1  Bf8 !?  I like this idea, forcing White to react actively or otherwise getting a slightly worse position. The d6-pawn may end up being a weakness more than a strength, as happens in many lines of the Exchange Variation that we will explore in another Chapter. }
10... h5
{ ...cxd5 is surprisingly the main move by far. It was played in one of the included model games: Shen-So, ICC Int  (2014)  . All said, I analysed the main move, however, I firmly believe the suggested move improves our chances significantly and scores much better for Black at this point ! }
11. g4
{ This is White's main option at this point and Ivanchuk's novelty against Akesson, back in 2004. White tries to mobilise the kingside fast as we have our army grouped around the queenside. We should pay special attention to this variation.   11.Be2  White wants to prevent our plan, which is to take on d5 and play ...Bf5.  cxd5  12.exd5  N8d7  13.d6  Nf6  14.Bg5  Qe8 !?  N  I really like this idea now, which leads to a complicated position. Apart from unpinning the Queen, we have two ideas in mind: 1  We can counterattack with ...e4 !; or 2  We may use the c4 outpost to generate counterplay in the queenside. 14... Re8 ?! was played in the reference game I have included between Kramnik and Shirov, WCC Cazorla  (1998)  . However, as Stohl pointed out in his excellent analysis, this logical move will give White tactical chances connected with a later d7 advance with tempo. }
11... cxd5 { The main and most principled response. } 12. exd5
{ The only move that makes sense for White. } 12... Na6
{ Has only been tried in three games, but I think this is a good way to face this variation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Summaries"]
[Black "Bf4 Variations"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4
{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. e3
{ White's absolute main line, used far more than other alternatives.   5.Qa4+  A rare line that should not worry us much.  Bd7  6.Qb3  Nc6 !  7.e3  White's main move at this point.   7.Qxb7 ?  Way too risky.  Nxd4 !  7...Na5  8.Qb4  c5 !?  ...Nxc4 is the main move, however I am surprised this move has not been played more often in high-level games.   5.Rc1  An independent secondary variation which, to be honest, you are not really likely to face over the board.  Nh5 !  The main move here is 5...O-O, with around 300 games and an average score of 55% for White. However, this move, in my opinion, is a clear improvement. It has been played in less than 100 games, but it shows a score of 45% in Black's favor !  6.Bg5  Is the most played move at this point.   6.Bd2  Maybe a more logical move than Bg5. White is ready to play e3 next, defending or recapturing on c4.  c5 !?  Releasing the indirect pressure on c7 and putting it on d4, once again the thematic pawn break in the Grunfeld. It is interesting to explore ...dxc4 !?, however, I am more comfortable playing the kind of positions that we reach after ...c5. In the other lines, White gets more than enough compensation and we need to play accurately and remember some lines.   6.Bfe5 ?!  If White had played Nf3, then this move would be reasonable and more annoying. And that is precisely the reason why ...Nh5 ! is a good move, because White does not play Nf3 before Rc1.  Bxe5  7.dxe5  d4 !  ∓  6...h6  Asking the Bishop where he'd like to go. It also controls the g5 square, which allows us to play ...Be6 without having to worry about a potential Nf3-g5.  7.Bh4  Is the main retreat and the one that makes more sense after Bg5.   7.Bd2  Contrary to other lines in the Grunfeld, h6 is not really a weakness here. The rook on c1 prevents White from playing Qc1, which would be annoying with h6 made, as the battery would pose some questions on how we want to proceed on the kingside.  dxc4 !  So, why do we play ...dxc4 now instead of ...c5 as in 6. Bd2 then ? Well, the difference is the fact that we have played h6. The structure looks a little draughty now. We will castle and play ...Be6, trying to secure the pawn that we just won, a different approach. Remember what I mentioned regarding different solutions for different move orders at the beginning of the chapter about 4. Bf4 ? Here we have a perfect example.  7...dxc4 !?  Once again ! As a rule of thumb, remember that if we have included ... h6, then we will continue with ...dxc4 and the ...Be6 strategy. Feel free to explore ...c5 ! It makes more sense than in the Bd2-retreat variation positionally. However, I believe this is easier to remember and we keep consistency in our repertoire while following solid, good variations.  8.e3  Be6  9.Be2  Nf6 !  It is a good idea to keep an open mind in the Grunfeld, in some variations we may want White to capture on h5 to gain the bishop pair advantage. However, in this concrete line the structural damage would be serious and the compensation clearly not enough.   5.Nf3  The second most played option.  O-O !  as White chose to play Nf3 instead of e3, there is a big difference in the resulting position: 1- White can not play Ne2-c3 anymore. 2- Qf3 is not an option. 3- The bishop can go back to d2 to defend potential weaknesses on the dark squares.   5...c5  You can see the differences between castling and playing ...c5 in this example line.  6.dxc5  Qa5  7.cxd5  Nxd5  8.Qxd5  Bxc3+  9.Bd2 !  a move that would not be legal if White had played e3 instead of Nf3 ! This is considered to be clearly better for White according to current theory.  Bxd2+  10.Qxd2  Qxc5  11.Rc1  Qf5  12.Nd4  Qd7  13.Qh6  ±  White is clearly better. Black has some serious problems to mobilise and coordinate his position. The dark squares on the kingside are suffering too.  6.Rc1  6. e3 - 6... c5 will transpose to one of the lines that we will study under the 5. e3 move order.  dxc4 !  Again, an early Rc1 points out the right approach we should choose, it is again not to play ...c5. Hopefully this will help you remember the right plan ! Note how now ...Nh5-Be5 ! is annoying for our purposes.  7.e4  White's main line at this point and the most logical one, grabbing central space.   7.e3  is a sober move that does not pose many problems for our purposes. We can have a comfortable game after  Be6 !  ...c5 !? is Svidler's recommendation and is also another interesting option to explore. However, I believe this fits better in our repertoire, let me explain why: It is important to remember that at this point we are choosing what to do with our bishop as we mobilise our position. However, it is even more important to understand why against 7. e4 we play ...Bg4 and why now we decide to play ..Be6. The key is the pressure that we can apply against White's center. In this case, contrary to what happens in the e4 variation, we are not applying real, serious pressure on d4 as e3 bolsters White's center. Therefore, we defend our c4-pawn, an idea that we have seen before.  7...Bg4  ...c5 !? is also possible and is the option that Svidler recommends. However, this is the main line and the move that makes more sense to me. Our idea is to put pressure on f3 and d4. We want to take on f3 and make White recapture with pawn as if he does with queen, he does not defend on d4 anymore ! That's the whole point. We also enable the idea of ... Nh5 !? once again as Be5 will not be as good now with the knight pinned. }
5... c5 6. dxc5
{ The absolute main line of this variation. The alternatives are clearly worse than this. If White allows us to take on d4, we will get a very comfortable game and the initiative in many variations.   6.Bxb8 ?!  Is not good for White. This move has not been played much but it is important to know why we get an advantage in this line.  Rxb8  7.Qa4+  Bd7  8.Qxa7  White grabs a pawn, but this is too risky and we can easily obtain a big initiative.  cxd4  9.Qxd4  O-O  10.cxd5  We quickly obtain a demolishing initiative after  Qa5 !   6.Nf3  White's secondary option, more respectable than Bxb8, but still worse than dxc5, the main line.  cxd4  As White does not take on c5, we take on d4 and try to get an initiative.  7.Nxd4  White's most serious line and main option.   7.exd4  has also been tried in many games, but it is not as serious as the main variation.  O-O  8.Be2  Nc6  Black has a very comfortable position in which White's dark-squared bishop does not sit comfortably on f4 and would be better on g5, as in the Taimanov lines.  7...O-O  8.Ndb5 !  White's only serious change to fight the the advantage. White tries to question Black's c7 square, which is usually Achilles heel for Black in these lines.  Qa5 !  This is the key move to remember. We can fight for the initiative while solving our problems. }
6... Qa5 7. Rc1
{ White's absolute main line in the 4. Bf4 variation.   7.cxd5  Has been played in around 50 games at this point. Black does not have any problems in this line.  Nxd5  8.Qxd5  Other moves are clearly worse.  Bxc3+  9.bxc3  Qxc3+  10.Ke2  Qxa1  11.Be5  Qb1 !?  Black wants to win !   11...Qc1  Black can force a draw if desired after  12.Bxh8  Be6  13.Qxb7  Qc2+ =  Wherever the king goes, there will always be a check, be it on f5 or on c1/c2.   7.Qa4+  White's second most played option. Probably White's best choice after the main line: 7. Rc1.  Qxa4  8.Nxa4  Bd7 !  The best move according to current theory.  9.Nc3  Ne4 !  Black's whole idea is to increase the activity of his pieces by means of temporarily sacrificing a second pawn. }
7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O
{ If therere some general tips that I extracted after studying 4. Bf4 in Rowsons book these would be the following: 1  Rc1 from White usually means that we should capture on c4. 2  We should not take on c5 before castling. 3  Castling and taking on c5 are priorities and should, generally, go before ...Nc6   8...Qxc5 ?  Do not think this wins a pawn, it is a huge mistake !  9.Nb5  Qb4+  10.Kf1 !  O-O  11.a3  Qxb2 ?  12.Rb1  Leitao-Van Wely, Antwerp  (1998)  . }
9. Nf3
{ Is the most played move from White.   9.Nge2  Should be taken seriously. It is White's second option and has scored slightly better than Nf3, the main line. White has some ideas in mind: 1- A common maneuver once the queen takes on c5 is Ng3-e4, threatening the queen. 2- We will have to find a role for our light-squared bishop, as it will be chased with f3 and g4/e4, or even with Ng3. 3- It can recapture on f4 after a potential ...Nh5. However, a knight on e2 has less influence on the centre and can not jump to e5, aiming at f7, one of the two vulnerable squares in our position along with c7. Something else to notice is that our dark-squared bishop will be really strong in these lines.  Qxc5  10.Qb3  the main move at this point. We have to play well in this position knowing what is the main issue for us in this position: We have to develop while keeping an eye on threats like Nd5, aiming at the most vulnerable square in our position: c7.   10.Nb5 ?!  Looks very logical and human, but it is easily refuted after  Qb4+ !  11.Kf1  Ne4 !  Other sources recommend ...a6, which is interesting, but I believe the following sequence gives Black the advantage.  12.a3  Qxb2 !  N  ...Nd2 was played in De Firmian-Wolff, New York  (1987)  . The recommended novelty is much stronger.  10...Qa5 !?  10... Nc6 is the main move. However, this secondary option scores as well as the main line and I like the ideas behind this move.  11.O-O  Nbd7 !?  Keeping flexibility. In my opinion it is better than ... Nc6 for our purposes. }
9... Qxc5 10. Bb3
{ White's main line by far. It is also the most natural move in this position. }
10... Nc6
{ 10... Qa5 and then ...Nc6 is also possible. However, White does not have any dangerous discovered attacks as we can check with Qb4 or Qa5. }
11. O-O Qa5 12. h3
{ The main line by far. It prevents ...Bg4 and gives a escape to the dark-squared bishop.   12.Qe2 !?  In this line we can see some of the problems White need to face without including h3.  Nh5 !  13.Bg5  Bg4  14.Bh4  White's most played option at this point.  g5 !?  14... Qb4 gives Black a fully equal game, as mentioned by Rowson and Avrukh.  15.Bg3  Nxg3  ∓ }
12... Bf5 { The main line and a logical developing move. } 13. Qe2
{ White's absolute main option, preparing to battle but only after calling in his last soldiers !   13.Nd4  It is common knowledge among Grunfeld players that this move has been considered good for Black's purposes since 1989, when Petursson-Ivanchuk played a game that Black managed to win and White had many problems to equalise.  Bd7  14.Qe2  Nxd4  15.exd4  e6  16.Be5  Bc6  17.Rfd1  Rfd8 =  See the mentioned game. The position is equal. }
13... Ne4
{ After the last two moves, we can see that Black's position look harmonious and coordinated. White has to play accurately to avoid falling in a worse position already ! Also, note how with this knight exchange, we will open the diagonal for our bishop. }
