[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Summaries"]
[Black "Qa4+ Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qa4+
{ This move often transposes to the line starting with Qb3. Indeed with Qa4+, White's idea is to enter the Russian System  (with Qb3)  , but first disrupting Black's development. The reason why this is a separate chapter from Qb3 is the fact that I am proposing an approach that has not been played much yet, but that I believe is quite interesting and sound. }
4... Bd7 { We win a tempo in exchange though. } 5. Qb3 Nc6
{ This is the approach I would like to recommend against an early Qa4...Nc6 is an interesting move that explots the fact that the White's king knight is still on g1. We attack the center and at the same time pose a threat with ...Na5. }
6. Nf3
{ Moves like e3 instead of Nf3 allow us to play ...Na5, targeting c4 and winning another tempo on the queen. White can not really afford to fall behind in development even more, that would give us a very comfortable position.   6.cxd5 ?!  Is clearly worse than other alternatives.  Nxd4  7.Qd1  Nb5 !  We exploit our better development to get a slight, comfortable advantage. }
6... Na5 7. Qc2
{ White's best and most challenging move.   7.Qb4  Nxc4  8.Nxd5  The only move that makes sense for White at this point.   8.Qxb7 ?!  N  Is not good for White. It leads to a somewhat forced variation where we will have a great advantage.  Rb8 !  9.Qa6  Rb6 !  This is the idea, we will have a huge lead in development and pose problems to White's king.  8...Nd6 !  N  This is a novelty. ...Nxd5 was played in Dolezal,J-Filip,M/Prague 1954/MCD  (46)  , but I believe ...Nd6 is a stronger move.  9.Nc3  a5 !  We keep winning tempi and space on the queenside due to the White queen's compromised position. }
7... c6
{ 7...Nxc4  We do not really want to go down this path due to  8.Nxd5 !  the beginning of a sequence that will give White a promising center.  Nxd5  9.Qxc4  Nb6  10.Qc2  Bg7  11.e4  Bg4  We would like to be able to challenge the center, but with the queen on c2, White can simply play  12.Ne5 !  +=  Our bishop feels out of play. White has a slight, comfortable advantage. }
8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Bg5
{ White wants to exchange his worst minor piece for our knight. Otherwise, .. .Rc8 with the option of ...Ne4 becomes a strong plan that will potentially give us the upper hand.   9.e3  White will have a problem developing and finding a role for his dark-square bishop, we get a comfortable advantage in these lines. }
9... Rc8 10. Bxf6 exf6
{ Even though the pawn structure seems odd, we have enough reasons to believe in our position ! The pawns cover good squares too, allowing us to position our pieces well, granting us with some extra options like the files ! }
11. a3 Bd6 12. e3 O-O 13. Bd3 Nc4 14. O-O Re8 15. Rfc1 a6
{ Black controls the position quite comfortably and the bishop pair compensates the damaged structure. If White does not play carefully, we could get a better position when transitioning to the endgame. }
