[White "Repertoire Summaries"]
[Black "The Closed Grunfeld: 4.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ A quiet move leading to a closed kind of game in which White can decide among different follow-ups in the following move. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ The absolute main line, which leads to a flexible system for both sides.   5.b4  White's idea is to take the game to a positional ground where he will try to show the advantage by playing on the queenside.  O-O  6.Nf3  Other moves from White, for instance Bb2 or Qb3, will end up transposing to variations we will cover soon after White plays Nf3.  c6  7.Bb2  White's most tried option at this point, making total sense of the b4 move.  Be6 !?  8.c5  This gives us a straight plan involving ...e5 !   8.Ng5  may look like an active option, questioning the position of our light-squared bishop. Nothing further from the truth, as our bishop was never meant to be on e6, but on...  Bf5  9.h3  h6  And the knight will have to retreat.  8...Nbd7  9.h3  this is necessary, otherwise ...Bg4, ...Re8 and ...e5 makes our life really easy.  Re8 !? N  An interesting novelty. Our idea is to play ...Bf5 and ... e5 ! We force White to play Bd3 to stop our idea, which will generate another interesting plan !  10.Bd3  Bf5 !  11.Bxf5  gxf5  Opening the g-file is good for us in this case. The f-pawn is not really weak as it bolsters the e4-outpost, which is indeed very nice for a knight.   5.cxd5  Has been increasingly played lately, but to be honest this line is unlikely to cause us many problems.  Nxd5  6.Nxd5  White's main response.  Qxd5  7.Ne2  The absolute main line in this variation. White wants to gain a tempo with Nc3.  O-O  8.Nc3  Qd6 !?  A very solid option that has been played by super GMs like Caruana or Li. The other main option is ...Qd8...Qd7 followed by ...b6 is another interesting option which I was seriously considering, but I finally decided to opt for ...Qd6.  9.Be2  c6  10.O-O  Nd7  Black will not have any problems after ...e5.   5.Qb3  By far White's second option, with more than 750 games where this move has been played.  e6  Our choice and the best move, which happens to achieve the best score for Black  (around 49%)  . It is better to keep flexibility with the c-pawn as we may want to play ...c5 at some point later in the game.  6.Qa3  This is the whole point behind Qb3. White tries to prevent Black from castling. Fortunately, we have a concrete idea in this line.  a5 !  We will drive our knight to b4, where it will block the a3-f8 diagonal, allowing us to castle.  7.Nf3  c6 !  A very important in-between move that has been played in a number of games. Black defends the a5 pawn and prevents White's maneuver Qa4+ and Qb3, followed by a3, driving our future knight on b4 away and leading to unnecessary complications.  8.b3  White's main option at this point. 8. Be2 ?? allows dxc4, and White can not recapture on c4 due to ...b5 !, winning a piece.   8.cxd5  The capture cxd5 from White does not change our plan of blocking the diagonal and castling.  exd5  9.Bd3  Na6  Black is completely fine. Many times, this line leads to a position where White has hanging pawns on e3 and d4, but remember that we can control them efficiently.  8...Na6  After ...Nb4, we will be able to castle. }
5... O-O 6. Be2
{ The most played option by far. It was made popular by Mamedyarov in 2012, where he used this line in multiple games with positive results.   6.Bd2  A flexible move that has become popular recently. This move has been used by elite GMs such as Mamedyarov, Anand, Ivanchuk...  c5 !?  Other moves are possible, but this is a straightforward and known way of striking the center in the Grunfeld that we should always consider.  7.dxc5  By far White's main option.  Na6  8.cxd5  Nxc5  9.Bc4  a6   6.Bd3  Has been played in many games. It is a logical move that does not give Black many problems to reach a comfortable position.  c5  7.O-O  Solving the tension in the center with a pawn capture does not help White in any way, as we have seen in other lines. This is a most challenging approach.  cxd4  8.exd4  White's best option and most tried one at this point.   8.Nxd4 ?!  We can easily grab space in the center.  e5 !  8...Nc6  9.h3  Playing prophilactically against ...Bg4 as the pin would be really uncomfortable for White to handle.  dxc4  10.Bxc4  We reach a IQP position where White does not have his pieces well positioned for the required strategy. We have no problems after this example line:  Na5  11.Bd3  Be6  12.Re1  Rc8  13.Bg5  White continues developing his pieces, with the idea of Rc1 next.  Nc6 !  This is Avrukhs recommendation. Black changes his plans and will apply pressure on d4 and b2 at the same time after ...Qb6 !   6.cxd5  Nxd5  7.Bc4  The most popular option by far. Other options are not really challenging for Black and youd better off remembering the ideas in this line to apply them successfully in your own games.  Nb6  We will strike the center with the thematic ...c5, regardless of where the bishop goes. }
6... c5 { The most direct answer. } 7. O-O
{ The absolute main line in this variation.   7.cxd5  A secondary line not used much as Black has better chances.  Nxd5  8.Qb3  A most logical try in my opinion.   8.O-O  Surprinsingly the most used option.  Nc6  9.dxc5 ?!  Nxc3  10.bxc3  Qa5 !  8...Nxc3  9.bxc3  Nc6  A very common pawn structure in this opening. We will potentially win a tempo on the misplaced queen with ...Na5.   7.dxc5  Used often as an alternative of O-O.  dxc4 !?  ...Qa5 is another option, but the simpler recommendation already equalises easily for our purposes in this repertoire.   7...Qa5  This is an alternative if you want to keep queens on the board for longer.  8.O-O  dxc4  9.Bxc4  Qxc5  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  9.Bxc4  Nbd7  10.c6  bxc6  11.O-O  Nb6 =  With ... Nfd5 coming next, the position is equal. }
7... cxd4 8. exd4
{ White's main played capture.   8.Nxd4  Has been tried in a number of games as well. It will be enough for our purposes to see the general plan we should follow in this secondary variation.  dxc4  9.Bxc4  a6  We threaten ...b5, giving us a very comfortable position. }
8... Nc6
{ Black's main response and the most logical one, generating more pressure on White's center and developing. }
9. h3
{ White's main option, which has been played in around 700 games. The idea is to avoid ...Bg4, a thematic move in the Grunfeld when generating pressure on d4. From here, Black has tried around 5 successful ideas, which highlights White's weak intentions with his setup.   9.Be3  One of White's main alternatives at this point and a logical move, defending the d4-pawn against Black's silent pressure.  dxc4  10.Bxc4  Na5  11.Be2  Be6 !  We have seen this thematic move before in the Grunfeld. }
9... Be6
{ This is a my recommendation. It is indeed a good way to proceed that fits well in our repertoire. I was extremely tempted to choose ...b6 !? over this move, especially after White decides to play h3. However, for the purpose of our repertoire and to have a more standard way of facing these lines, I decided to recommend ...Be6 !?, which is as good as ...b6 or even the main line   ...dxc4  . Let's explore our ideas. }
10. c5
{ White's main move. White solves the central tension by leaving our bishop 'blocked' on e6.   10.Ng5  Has also been tried by White in many games. And it is really a logical move, questioning the position of our bishop on e6.  Bf5  11.Be3  dxc4  12.Bxc4  Na5 }
10... Ne4 11. Bf4
{ This variation allows a very nice idea from Black of a different nature. }
11... h6
{ 11.Be3  White's most played option, which allows a straightforward continuation which favors Black.  Nxc5 !  A very timely tactical blow.  12.dxc5  d4  13.Nxd4  Nxd4  14.Bf3  Rc8 !  We could apply a well-known saying in this case. 'To take is a mistake', referring to the capture in f3, which is not as good as ...Rc8 !  15.Bd5  Bxd5  16.Bxd4  e5  17.Be3  Bc4  18.Qxd8  Rfxd8  19.Rfd1  f5 !  =+  Black has the advantage. See Adly-Ponomariov, Khanty-Mansiysk,  (2005)  .  An interesting move. With ...g5, we will win space and White may have some problems in coordinating his position if we take him out of his known lines. }
