[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Summaries"]
[Black "The Russian System"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3
{ 4.Qb3  White employs a tricky move order which most likely will end up in the main variation of the Russian System after Nf3 is played. Sometimes White delays the development of the king's knight, but we should not be distracted and confused into another line.  dxc4  5.Qxc4  Bg7  6.e4  6. Nf3 O-O transposes to the main line.  O-O  7.Be2  7. Nf3 Nc6 transposes to the main line once again.  Nc6  8.Be3  After 8. Nf3 we are, once again, in the main line, which will be covered under the main move order: 4. Nf3 Bg7, 5. Qb3. Be3 is an independent, secondary line. This idea is not White's best option. We can get a comfortable game after  (e5 ! ⇆)  Black get's a great counterplay. }
4... Bg7 5. Qb3
{ This move characterises the Russian System. White exerts a lot of pressure on d5. There are two solutions to fight against that pressure: 1  Play passive, solid moves like ...e6 or ...c6; and 2  Take on c4 and give White a bigger control of the centre, but gaining a lead in development in exchange. The first one is not in the spirit of the Grunfeld at all, we should no doubt the second point should be our approach !   5.Qa4+  With this check, White wants to disrupt our natural development. Ivan Sokolov has played this line in several games against the Grunfeld guru Peter Svidler.  Bd7  But we also gain a tempo here !  6.Qb3  6... Nc6 loses a pawn for nothing in exchange here. Do not confuse the idea here: there is a huge difference between 4. Qa4+ and 5. Qa4+ as the d4 pawn is now defended by the developed knight on f3.  dxc4  7.Qxc4  The best and most logical response from White.   7.Qxb7  This is not a good idea for White in this line due to  Nc6 !  The threat ...Rb8 followed by ...Nb4 is too strong for White to handle.  8.Bf4  Rb8  9.Qxc7  Qxc7  10.Bxc7  Rxb2  ∓  And Black was clearly better in Trmal-Hollis, Leningrad  (1960)  .  7...O-O  8.Bf4  The main line from White. This option has grown in popularity over the last couple of years.   8.e4  It used to be the main line a few years ago, but it has been relegated to the main alternative at White's disposal. And this is not a surprise, as Svidler highlights as well: 'this is worse than in the normal Qb3 lines, as Black has the very important additional option of...'  b5 !  There has been a lot of analysis in these lines and this is currently known as the clearest way to equalize for Black.  9.Nxb5  This is the main line   9.Qb3  White may refrain from taking on b5. This is the other played option at this point.  c5 !  10.e5  This is considered to be the most challenging attempt, but I believe the alternative 10. dxc5 is more challenging. In this variation, I found an improvement in this line that I think is really significant for future analysis.   10.dxc5  Na6 !  This gives us great counterplay for the pawn. White also needs to be accurate in these lines as he can end up in danger if he does not tread carefully.  10...Ng4  11.dxc5  White's main line at this point.  Be6 !? N  A very interesting novelty. We sacrifice another pawn to obtain a fierce initiative. 11... Na6 has been the tried option, but the suggestion is simply stronger.  9...Nxe4  10.Qxc7  This is the main and most logical reply.   10.Nxc7  This line is considered to be very dangerous for White.  Nc6 !  11.Nxa8  Qa5+  An extremely strong move for White to face.  10...Nc6  11.Bd3  White's main option.  Nb4  The old line is my recommendation in this position. This is considered to be absolutely fine for Black, as Svidler points out.  8...Be6 !?  This is my recommendation. We ignore the hanging pawn on c7, but we will get something in return !  9.Qxc7  Nc6  10.e3  This is White's main line and the move that scores the best.   10.Qxb7  Nxd4 !  N  This is a strong novelty. ...Rac8 was played by Vachier-Lagrave against Berkes in 2008. However, the suggested option is stronger.  10...Nb4 !  We oblige White to take a decision now. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4
{ We reach the starting point of the classical Qb3 variation, and we also reach a crossroad. We have a variety of options here: ...a6, ...Na6, ...Nc6, ...Bg4, ...Nfd7, ... Be6, etc.   7.Bf4  A respectable variation that we should know how to meet. However, I believe 7. e4 is the most challenging move.  Na6 !?  Remember this key idea. At the same time we defend the c7-pawn, we get ready to challenge the center. We can not simply let White get the whole centre ! We would also like to point out that, instead of ...Na6, you can transpose to one of the lines in the 5. Qa4+ Bd7 variation where Black plays 8...Be6. It is a good idea in terms of simplicity. However, 7...Na6 is a really dynamic move that we liked a lot in this position !  8.e4  c5 !  9.dxc5  By far White's main choice.   9.d5  White's main alternative.  e6 !  10.Be2  White's most tried option, although I believe d6 is more challenging if we do not know the position !   10.d6  The main alternative.  e5 !  A move that was played by Garry Kasparov. Black sacrifices a pawn to get the initiative !  10...exd5  11.exd5  This positions reminds of the ...Na6 variation in the Russian System, but with the big difference that White has not castled yet ! Instead, the dark-squared bishop is developed and we can benefit from that.  Nb4 !  11... b5 !?N is a very interesting novelty. The idea is to follow with ...Re8 and ...Bb7 ! Playing really actively for the sacrifice and bringin all our pieces to play quickly, while also targeting the d5 pawn. I encourage you to take a look at it at it could really surprise your opponent. However, this move is the main recommendation and the safest option while maintaining a very good game.   9.Rd1  This secondary line does not give us many problems to equalise and have a comfortable game.  cxd4  Black's main and most accurate continuation in my opinion.  10.Rxd4  The most logical capture.  Qb6  11.e5  Be6  12.Qb5  Nd7 !  Here I like Avrukh's comment: 'It is important for Black to react actively.'  9...Be6  ...Qa5 is also possible. However, I like the recommended move more.  10.Qb5  The only move that makes sense for White in this position.  Bd7  11.Qxb7  11. Qc4 would lead to a repetition.  Nxc5  12.Qb4  Ne6  Normally in these lines, the lead in development we enjoy will give us enough compensation for the pawn, and sometimes even more if White does not play carefully !  13.Be5  a5 !  The perfect moment to chase White's queen away from the b4 square. In some variations this is key in order to target the e4 pawn. }
7... Nc6
{ Even though this is not the most popular choice at the top level, I decided to opt for ... Nc6 as it is more consistent with our repertoire and also rich in play and ideas. GM Avrukh defines ...Nc6 at this point as a 'viable alternative to the more common lines.' }
8. Be2
{ The absolute main line, but White has some other options too that have been played at top level.   8.d5 ?!  White advances his d-pawn too fast. The idea of the 7... Be6 !? move is precisely that, to provoke d5 in order to undermine White's center with ...c6 followed by ...e6. Hopefully this will help you remember the right plan for Black in this position.  Na5   8.Bf4  Bg4  ...Nh5 and ...Nd7 are more common moves. But I like this idea, which so far has been played in less than 10 games according to my database. It has however caught the attention of players such as Khalifman, Ganguly and Inarkiev.  9.d5  Bxf3  10.gxf3  The natural continuation.   10.dxc6  b5 !  A great tactical resource worth keeping in mind, as it is typical in these positions of the Russian System.  10...Nh5  11.Be3   11.dxc6 ?!  is quite risky for White because of  b5 !  12.Qxb5  A better move than Bxc7 at this point.  Rb8  Black has a strong initiative.  11...Ne5  12.Qe2  b5 !  13.O-O-O  Nc4 !  N  A novelty. ...c6 was played in Tomashevsky-Khalifman, Moscow  (2012)  . I have included the game for you to check more ideas, but the recommended move is stronger.   8.Bg5  has not been played in many games, but has brought White some good results so far.  Bg4  9.O-O-O  Nd7  10.e5  Pretty much the only move that has been played by the elite at this point. White prevents us from playing typical ideas such as ...e5.  Nb6  11.Qc5  f6  12.Be3  fxe5  13.dxe5  Qe8 !  is a better move than ...Qc8. The queen exerts more control from e8 and also is not exposed to White ideas like h4-Bh3 after we exchange or sacrifice the exchange on f3, which could be a possibility.   8.e5  The right pawn to advance if White really feels compelled to advance one of them.  Be6 !?  An interesting move that will leave us with queen and two pawns for three minor pieces for White.  9.exf6  Bxc4  10.fxg7  Kxg7  11.Bxc4  Nxd4  12.Nxd4  Qxd4  13.Be2  Qb6 !?  ∞  A highly unclear position. We have the queen and two pawns for three pieces, but White has no weaknesses. It is interesting and I believe the right plan, apart from grabbing the d-file, is to use our pawns cleverly in order to try and limit White minor pieces. Also, we should aim at creating some weaknesses that we can target at some point in White's position. }
8... e5
{ A very interesting move completely in the spirit of the Grunfeld. Vachier-Lagrave has played this a couple of times recently. Other ideas are ...Bg4 or ...Nd7. }
9. d5
{ White's main option by far. Now that we counterattack in the centre, White fixes it gaining space and hoping that we can not find a good plan or squares for our pieces.   9.dxe5  Another option where we usually will not have many problems equalising and White should be careful in some risky lines.  Ng4  10.Nd5  The most testing attempt from White.   10.O-O  We will not have problems with equalising if White plays normal development moves.  Ngxe5  11.Nxe5  Nxe5  10...Be6  11.Bg5  The only move that has been seen in practice as far as I am aware.  Ngxe5  12.Bxd8  Nxc4  13.Bf6  Probably White's only move that does not leave him in a worse position, as otherwise we take on b2 and have an advantage on the queenside.   13.Bxc7 ?!  Too optimistic for White.  13...Bxd5  14.Bxg7  Kxg7  15.exd5  N6e5 =  Completely equalises. We have centralised pieces and no weaknesses. }
9... Nd4 10. Nxd4
{ White's main move by far.   10.O-O  is not a problem for Black.  c6 !  11.dxc6  bxc6  N  ...Be6 was played in Mitsis-Petr, Fischer Memorial  (2018)  . However, the recommended novelty takes the game into tactical territory that happens to benefit us objectively speaking. }
10... exd4 11. Qxd4 c6 12. Qc4
{ White's main option at this point.   12.Qd1  has been played about 20 times. It probably does not have the reputation of Qc4, but it is a very logical move.  cxd5  13.exd5  b5 !  I have to admit that I these lines tend to be kind of drawish if played well, but this move allows us to fully equalise here.   12.d6 ?!  Dubious. The d-pawn advances too far and too son. White is not in the best situation to start engineering anything sophisticated. This is true of many lines in the Russian System, where White should be careful not to fall too far behind in development.  Re8 !  13.Qd3  White tries to fight for the advantage in this position.   13.e5  Nd5 !?  N  ...Ng4 has been tried before, but White could get an advantage with accurate play. The truth is that this interesting move is more challenging and equalises without problems even if White is especially inspired.  13...b5 !  The key to remember in this position. We target the e4 pawn, create the threat of ...b5-b4 and have a good maneuver with the rook via e6-d6. }
12... b5
{ Introduced by Vachier-Lagrave a few years ago. The old line is 12... cxd5. }
13. Qxc6
{ White main's attempt to prove an advantage in this position.   13.Qb3  cxd5  14.exd5  a5 !?  N  An interesting novelty I would recommend in this position. ...b4 and ...Re8 have been tried before, but there are not many games. The idea of ...a5 is to keep the b4 pawn defended once we advance it and gain space on the queenside. We keep our options open and have a flexible position. }
13... Bd7 14. Qd6 Re8
{ We are two pawns down, but we are also ahead in development and keep good chances. }
