[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Summaries"]
[Black "Taimanov Variation: 4.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5
{ The Taimanov variation. White puts pressure on the d5 defender, the f6-knight. Once again, White develops the queenside before the kingside. 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 transposes to the 5. Nf3 line. }
4... Bg7
{ 4... Ne4 is the main move, but it requires knowing a great deal of difficult theory and tricky transpositions. The alternative recommendation is solid and we will be backed by a recommendation by Svidler in the sole line was thought to create problems for Black. }
5. Bxf6
{ The absolute main line. White will try to prove that Black has no compensation for the pawn sacrifice.   5.e3  As other authors point out, it is a surprise that this is the second most played option. It feels like it does not mix very well with Bg5. We have a straightforward way to respond  c5 !  well-known resource in the Grunfeld, attacking White's center at the first chance we get.  6.dxc5  Qa5  And we are fine in all lines of this variation.   5.Nf3  Ne4  The absolute main line in this position is what I recommend. Other options are ...dxc4, which could lead to extremely sharp positions, and . ..c5, which is interesting, but Black struggles to generate enough compensation in all the lines if White knows the theory. White has three main options at this point: cxd5, Bh4 and Bf4.  6.cxd5  Is the most famous reply to ...Ne4. Note how both 6. Nxe4 ?? and 6. Nxd5 ?? lose material.   6.Bh4  Is second most tried option for White, and it makes more sense than Bf4 because of the knight on f3.  Nxc3  7.bxc3  dxc4  8.Qa4+  Qd7  8... Nd7 !? is a challenging option, but objectively it is probably worse than the recommendation.  9.Qxc4  b6 !  We want to use the white's queen compromised position to win a tempo while developing our light-square bishop.   6.Bf4  Is not the best option due to the fact that there is a knight on f3.  Nxc3  7.bxc3  c5  8.e3  O-O  9.cxd5  cxd4  10.cxd4  Qxd5  11.Be2  Nc6  12.O-O  Bf5  This is a well-known position which has been studied for many years and it is considered to be completely safe for Black.  6...Nxg5  7.Nxg5  e6  8.Nf3  The most played move for White at this point.   8.Qd2  The second most tried option after Nf3.  h6 !  I want to avoid getting into the theoretical tree of ...exd5 here, which is fine for Black but requires a lot of studying. I believe it is easier to grasp the ideas and lineas of ...h6, which actually, and to my surprise, score better at this point than ...exd5.   8.Qa4+  This has also been tested in a reasonable number of games, but Black is fine.  c6  9.dxc6  Nxc6  10.Nf3  Bd7  =∞  With beautiful compensation.   8.dxe6 ?  Risky and wrong approach. White is not in good condition to exploit our exposed king because he is so behind in development.  Qxg5  9.exf7+  Kxf7  10.e3  Re8  11.Bc4+  Kf8  12.O-O  c6 !  ∓  8...exd5  9.e3  O-O  10.Be2  c6  This variation leads to complex positions in which we have interesting play. }
5... Bxf6 6. cxd5
{ The only way for White to fight for an advantage.   6.Nxd5 ?!  Bg7  7.e3  c5  8.Nf3  Nc6  9.Be2  e6  =+  is clearly good for Black. }
6... c6
{ Generating counterplay at the first chance we get. We enter a kingdom of unbalanced positions that every Grunfeld player should enjoy. }
7. e4
{ White's absolute main line. An ambitious move which poses Black some problems to solve.   7.Rc1  White's main alternative, which has been used just a few times less than the main move: e4.  O-O  8.dxc6  8. e4 Bg7 ! transposes to 7. e4.  Qxd4 !?  This is the recommendation by Svidler I mentioned at the beginning of the line, which solves Black's problems in this line.  9.Qxd4  Bxd4   7.dxc6  Bxd4  8.cxb7  Bxb7  =∞  Black has full compensation and maybe more. White has nothing interesting in this position he can be proud of. Also, this is not played much and it is not likely you will face it at the board. }
7... O-O
{ The main line is my recommendation here. However, I would like to bring 7... Bg7 !? to your attention. The idea is to play prophilactically against a possible e5. Black will enter positions with a great positional compensation thanks to two very strong bishops, Black's main aim is not to get the pawn back though. I would suggest keeping an eye on such lines. Unfortunately, there are not many high-level games yet, but it is likely to be used in the future. }
8. e5
{ The main move and most ambitious for White. The absolute test for Black in this variation.   8.Nf3  Is not challenging for our purposes.  Bg4 !?  ...cxd5 is also possible.  9.Qb3  Bxf3  10.gxf3  Bxd4  11.Rd1  If White takes on b7, we will transpose with ...Nd7 and ...Qa5 ! with a decisive advantage.  c5 ! N  An interesting novelty with converts into active play for Black. }
8... Bg7 9. Bc4 b5 { Needed if we want to win material back. } 10. Bb3
{ White's main option, remaining in the a2-g8 diagonal, keeping an eye on d5.   10.Bd3  b4  11.Nce2  Qxd5  12.Qc2  Qxg2  13.Ng3  Qd5  Necessary as White threatened Be4, trapping the queen.  14.N1e2  Ba6 !  Black is threatening ...Bxd3 and ...Bxe5.   10.Be2 !?  An interesting attempt. White prefers to develop his knight via f3, rather than e2, where the knight sits strangely. With Be2, White minimises the effect of ...Bg4 as well, as recapturing on f3 with bishop is possible.  b4  11.Na4  cxd5  12.Nf3  Bg4 !?  Black sets a bind on the White squares and will recycle his bishop to the a3-f8 diagonal, playing on the queenside first and if White tries to release the tension there, the b-pawn will become a potential target. }
10... b4 11. Nce2
{ White's plan is to start an initiative on the kingside. This is the most challenging attempt.   11.Na4 !?  White, instead of switching his play to the kingside, tries to prevent our plan on the queenside.  cxd5  12.Ne2  e6  13.O-O  Nd7 !?  N  An interesting novelty: our idea is to trade knights and play with f6. }
11... cxd5 12. h4
{ White's most ambitious attempt, taking advantage of the fact that he has the upper hand on the kingside at the moment. We have no weaknesses and our g7-bishop is a good defender though. This leads to unclear positions.   12.Rc1  Din Liren tried this move against Piorun, but Black ended up winning the game and this has not been played more since.  e6  13.h4  Qb6  14.h5  Nc6  15.Ba4  Bb7  16.h6  Bh8  17.Nf3  f6  18.Nf4 ?  A better try was Bxc6, exf6 and then O-O, with the idea of playing Qd2, Rfe1 and try and take advantage of Black's numerous weaknesses. White would not be worse after that in any case and would hold a comfortable advantage.  fxe5 !  19.Nxe6  e4 !  Black has a clear advantage. See Liren D.-Piorun, Cappelle op.  2014  . }
12... Nc6 13. h5
{ Has been tried twice in practical high-level games.   13.Rc1  Was played in Matlakov-Robson, Moscow op  (2012)  . And now I suggest  (Qb6 ! N)  A strong novelty which does not make life easy for White at all. The queen sits well on b6 and Black will continue with the development. ...Na5 was played in the mentioned game. However, White could have been more accurate and make it more difficult for Black. }
13... e6 14. Nf3 Ba6 { Now White has tried two options: Nf4 and Bc2. } 15. Nf4
{ In my opinion, this is more challenging than the alternative Bc2.   15.Bc2  f6 !?  N  15... Qb6 was played in Bluebaum-Mista, FRA-chT  (2016)  . However, the odd-looking recommendation is simply stronger.  16.hxg6  seems the most logical move at this point, trying to prove Black's weaknesses.  fxe5  17.dxe5  Nxe5  18.Nxe5  Bxe5  And Black is fine, the position may look scary, but there is always a good defense for Black to keep the game balanced, as well as counterplay if White tries too hard ! }
15... Rc8 16. hxg6 hxg6 17. Bc2 b3
{ A great concept, gaining the b4 square for the knight and creating a weakness to target. }
18. axb3 Qb6
{ And Black enjoyed a good compensation. See Bukavshin-Matlakov, Moscow op  (2011)  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Summaries"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3
{ 5.Na4 !?  An old, interesting idea. White wants to take on the whole center without allowing ...Nxc3. Also, it prevents our thematic pawnbreak: ...c5.  Nf6 !?  The main move by far is 5... Bg7. With the suggested odd-looking move, we are breaking the rule ! We are moving the knight back to f6, but, why ? We simply take advantage of the fact that White will have a very difficult time proving any advantage without e4. Several well-known GMs have used this move before, such as: Sasikiran, Wang, Yermolinsky, Belov, McShane... If repeating moves is not something that you have in mind for any reason, I recommend taking a look at 5... e5 !?, an option which leads to rich positions in which Black is by no means worse after 6. dxe5 Nc6.  6.Nf3  The main option and the most logical one for White.   6.g3 ?!  Does not work now due to  Nc6 !  7.Nf3  e5 !  N  ...Bg7 was played in Rogule-Zaksaite, Oropesa del Mar  (1999)  . However, the recommended novelty is much stronger.   6.f3  Nc6 !  7.e3  e5  8.Bb5  This is the only move that has been played so far. 8. dxe5 ?! is not a very good idea for White as after exchanging queens, take on e5 and play ...Nh5 followed by ...f5 ! With a very good position.  exd4  9.Bxc6+  bxc6  The d5 square for our knight and the pressure on d4 with the dark-squared bishop will compensate for the damaged structure. We will likely win a pawn, but White could be able to hold the endgame with accurate play. Nevertheless, the trend is in Black's favor.  6...Bg7  7.Bf4  O-O  8.e3  Nbd7  9.Rc1  White tries to avoid ...c5. GM Narciso Dublan used this move in a blitz match against McShane.   9.Be2  is just slightly less popular than Rc1.  c5 !  our thematic pawn break !  9...c6 !  After Rc1, with ...c5 not being an option, we will choose to play with the other thematic pawnbreak: ...e5 !   5.Bd2 !?  This line has become increasingly popular over the last few years. White's idea is to take on c3 with bishop. This way, our dark-squared bishop will have opposition along the a1-h8 diagonal.  Nb6 !?  5... Bg7 is the main line. However, this scores better nowadays and is regaining popularity. I recommend this move as taking on c3, which is also viable, will mean that the bishop on c3 will make the pawnbreaks on c5 and e5 less efective, or the game will take a different direction. I believe this line fits better in our repertoire. Now White has four different options which are similar in terms of popularity.  6.Bg5  Here we should remember the idea of an early ...c5 ! As The dark-squared bishop from White will be out of the pawn chain and wont be able to defend on c3, we can destroy White's pawn structure.   6.e3  A secondary line which may look very sober and not really ambitious, but it hides a line that could be really problematic if we underestimate it !  Bg7  7.f4  The main line, which has been played by many top GMs. 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Rc1 transposes to a line that will be covered under the 6. Nf3 move order.  O-O  8.Nf3  c5 !  And again, the thematic pawnbreak. By means of this pawn sacrifice, we activate our position and get interesting play.   6.Nf3  Also a popular option. White will try to prevent ...c5.  Bg7  7.Rc1  7. Bg5 transposes to a line seen under 6. Bg5.  Nc6 !  8.e3  White has to play this move. The alternatives are clearly worse.  O-O  9.Bb5  The critical attempt. Other choices are worse and we have a comfortable game after  e5 !  9... Bd7 is the main move, but I believe is worse than the recommended option, which has been defended by players such as: Sasikiran, Nielsen or Krasenkow.   6.Bf4  Is also a secondary line which enjoys a similar reputation that 6. e3.  Bg7  7.e3  this is the main continuation. Nf3 most often transposes.  O-O  Our choice also happens to be the main continuation.  8.Nf3  Be6 !?  I firmly believe this move gives us good play. We prepare ...Nc6, put an eye on the thematic c4-square and keep our ...c5 pawnbreak option open. The main move here is 8... c5. 8... Bg4 is also interesting, but a rather passive choice, as highlighted by Svidler in his analysis.  6...Bg7  7.e3  c5 !?  This is the second most used move, notably after the main option: O-O. However, this variation scores much better than the main move and is therefore our choice. }
5... Bg7 6. Qa4+
{ An independent line often used as a surprise. The rest of the options are covered in other chapters, where Nf3 from White happens later on in the game. For example, 6. e4 transposes to the Exchange Variation, 6. e3 transposes to the Closed Grunfeld, 6. g3 transposes to the Fianchetto Variation, etc. }
6... Bd7
{ Here Black has played three options which are reasonable and similar in terms of popularity. Probably ...Nc6 !? is the most recent approach; however, finally I decided to suggest ...Bd7 as I believe it fits better in our repertoire. }
7. Qb3
{ The main move and probably the most logical one as well.   7.Qa3  has been tried a couple of times, notably by Greenfeld against Gupta in 2017. However, this idea has not worked very well for White and Black is fine after  Bc6  8.e3  O-O  9.Be2  Nd7  10.O-O  e5 !?  challenging White's centre. }
7... Nxc3
{ The main move here is ...Nb6. However, I found a new idea in this alternative variation  (almost virgin soil)  that I recommend. }
8. bxc3
{ White's main capture and the logical move.   8.Qxc3  Na6 !?  N  ...Bc6 !? with the idea of playing ...Bd5 is also an interesting idea, but I really like this novelty. Our plan is to play with a quick ...c5 and get a really active position.  9.e3  c5  10.Bxa6  bxa6  We have seen a similar structure already in one of the 6. e3 variations.  11.Qxc5  The most human and logical response, taking the pawn on c5.   11.O-O  Rc8  ∞  The bishop pair is clearly a good asset in our favor. This fully compensates the damaged pawn structure.  11...Bb5  Black's compensation is clear and the bishop pair clearly makes up for the damaged pawn structure and White's extra pawn. }
8... c5
{ And again, the thematic pawnbreak in the Grunfeld seen in action. We activate the long dark-squared diagonal and get a really comfortable game with great chances. }
9. e3
{ 9.Qxb7 ?!  This would be a dream for us.  Nc6 =∞  Black has more than full compensation and a great initiative. }
9... O-O
{ This pawn structure, as highlighted by Grunfeld experts such as Avrukh, is virtually always good for Black. }
10. Be2 Qc7 11. O-O Nc6 12. Rd1 Na5
{ 12... Rac8 was played in Turner-Seidman, New York  (1957)  . I have included the game as a reference. I think it is best not to commit the rook to c8 yet, as we can see in the given line. }
13. Qa3 b6 14. dxc5 Be6
{ Remember this maneuver, it is a really good way for Black to end up with the two best minor pieces. }
15. e4
{ 15.cxb6 ?!  White is better off not taking on b6 as, after  (axb6 =+)  Black is already better and with multiple immediate threats.   15.Nd4  Is another attempt from White which is best met by  Bc4  16.cxb6  axb6  =∞  Black has full compensation. }
15... Bc4 16. Bxc4 Nxc4
{ Black has equalised comfortable and mayben even more. I would always choose Black over White in this position. }
17. Qb4 Qxc5 18. Qxc5 bxc5
{ Black is more than fine in this position and has an easier position to play than White. Our minor pieces are better and exert a higher pressure. }
