[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Summaries"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3
{ 7. Bc4 is the main line and the classical option. Nf3 is considered the modern approach  (compared to Bc4)  of the Exchange Variation. In these lines, White intends to develop his pieces to natural squares: Nf3, Be3, Be2 and O-O.  In the long term, White's idea is to consolidate his centre with d5 and eventually c4. We must keep in mind that the best approach will still be the same and we should play in the Grunfeld's spirit ! The main idea to keep in mind is that, contrary to what happens in the 7. Bc4 lines, we have the annoying thematic pin: ...Bg4. }
7... c5
{ Challenging the center immediately. The best move order.   7...O-O ?!  This is not the right move order. There is not enough pressure against White's centre and therefore our opponent can consolidate without the practical problems posed with ...c5 !  8.Be2  c5  9.O-O !  Nc6  If ...Bg4, White can disturb our plan with Rb1 !  10.Be3  Bg4  11.d5 !  And White has consolidated his position. However, imagine none has castled yet. Then the story would be really different with ...Bxc3+ ! }
8. Rb1
{ The absolute main line in this variation and with an interesting idea which is not really obvious. This is also the pet line of Boris Gelfand. Rb1 is a consolidatory move, as Rowson first defined it in his book on the Grunfeld.  White prophylactically takes the rook off the long diagonal, where it is vulnerable to the attack of our dark-squared bishop once he decides to advance his center with d5. Now it will be possible to play d5 in many lines, sacrificing on c3, but without leaving the rook en prise. This move also plays against our ...Bg4 ideas, putting indirect pressure on d4, as our b7-pawn would not be defended anymore.   8.Be2 ?!  A secondary line and also a dubious move. You probably know what I mean if you have seen the informational line with 7...O-O.  Nc6 !  We keep challenging the center.  9.Be3  White's main option by far.  Bg4 !  We gradually increase the pressure on White's centre. Also, as the c3-pawn is unprotected, White practically does not have any options but  10.e5  White has weakened his centre, giving us the important d5 square. Also, now White's options have been limited and his centre is not that mobile anymore.  cxd4  11.cxd4  Qa5+ !?  ...O-O is also possible. However, I like Avrukhs comment on ... Qa5+, which forces White to make a difficult decision.   8.Bb5+  Is White's third option.  Nc6  9.O-O  O-O  ...cxd4 is also possible, but I like this specific approach in this situation.  10.Be3  Qa5 !?  ...Bg4 or ...cxd4 would transpose to the main line with 9... cxd4  11.Qa4  Qxa4  12.Bxa4  cxd4  13.cxd4  f5 !  A key move after queens are exchanged as the risk of getting mated is not that much of a threat anymore !   8.Be3  White's second option at this point, but this is also a big main line of the Nf3 variation. White overdefends the pawn on d4. White will develop his queenside entirely before even worrying about his kingside. After Be3, White usually plays Qd2 and Rb1/Rc1. With Rc1, White's idea is to quickly protect c3, following up with the d5 strategic threat.  Qa5  9.Qd2  The main line by far.   9.Bd2  An odd-looking move. White will try to exploit the position of our queen.  O-O  10.Be2  Bg4 !  Black has more options, but this is the main line and the most logical move. In the Grunfeld, we should always pressure and challenge the center !  9...O-O !?  ...Nc6 is the main line. However, this scores slightly better lately and I believe is a tricky more order to play against if White does not know the theory ! Also, we make White move the rook before taking on d4 ! Keep this small nuance as a reminder of the line !  10.Rc1  The main line by far.   10.Rb1  This move is less accurate if we have castled already, as seen in the following line:  Nc6 !?  White's plan was to provoke ...a6 given the Rb5 threat. However, we choose a different an interesting, alternative path which will involve a queen sacrifice.  11.Rb5  Any other move allows us to play ...b6, consolidating the queenside and assuring the position of our queen on the queenside, where it annoys White the most.  cxd4 !?  And here it is ! We offer the queen in exchange for great compensation and good play. Some players that decided to give this line a go have been, for example, Shirov or Svidler.  12.Rxa5  dxe3  13.Qxe3  Nxa5  Black enjoys a beautiful compensation for the material. The plan is clear, attack c3 ! This position has been reached 43 times, and the score is balanced.  10...Nd7 !?  This is a really interesting alternative which scores well for Black. White has overprotected d4 and c3 so much that our most common ideas do not work in this position. However, we also have the thematic pawnbreak ...e5 ! This is our plan in this position. Note how 10... Nc6, intending ...e5, does not work due to d5 from White. This is the reason why we play 10... Nd7 !? This option has been used by many elite GMs, for example: Vachier-Lagrave, Svidler, Morozevich... The main line is ...Rd8, and also interesting is ...cxd4, which is the second option used by Black in this position.   8.h3  This move became briefly popular after the match Kramnik-Kasparov, Wijk aan Zee  (2000)  . Then, it was not seen much in the elite for a while, but now it seems to have experienced another burst of popularity at the top level.  O-O  9.Be2  Is the main move, and now that White prevents .. .Bg4, I recommend playing  b6 !?  Here I like this logical idea. We try to underline the fact that 8. h3 could just have been a loss of time, as mentioned by Krasenkow in his analysis. }
8... O-O 9. Be2 { By far the most important of White's options at this point. }
9... cxd4
{ We are not obliged to take on d4, solving White's problem with the pawn structure and releasing the pressure against the center. However, it is tactically justified and we will play a game in which we will have static advantage  (the extra material as we grab a pawn)  and White will enjoy the dynamic advantage. It used to be common knowledge that Black needed to memorise a lot in this variation. Now that is not exactly true and it has been proved that Black is fine and comfortable in the main lines if we play reasonably. 9... Nc6 and 9... b6 are other options which are perfectly playable. }
10. cxd4 Qa5+ { The beginning of the trip to the queenside for our queen ! }
11. Bd2
{ The main move by far.   11.Qd2  Far less popular than Bd2, the main line. However, it is not bad and we should not lower our guard.  Qxd2+  12.Bxd2  b6 !  The main move and the most logical one. As White's ahead in development, playing both ...e6 and ...b6 will mean that he will be even more ahead ! We will connect our rooks and undermine White's centre whenever he advances his pawns ! }
11... Qxa2
{ Our queenside pawns become a long-term asset. However, White has reasons to believe his position is solid and promising too. }
12. O-O
{ So. Why would White want to play such a position with a pawn less, granting Black with two passed connected pawns on the queenside ? 1  White has a large lead in development. However, his bishops will have to move again as they occupy passive squares. 2  f7 and e7 are weak against White's bishop, and also the kingside is not very well protected with the knight gone. 3  White can try to establish domination with the central control, changing the play from one side to the other of the board. Luckily, we can prevent this from happening with }
12... Bg4
{ Trying to consolidate the material gain, developing and annoying White. } 13.
Bg5
{ A theory giant and the main line of the 8. Rb1 variation. The active way of defending d4 is considered the best attempt for White. We give back the material gained in order to catch up in development and complicate the position.   13.d5  An independent sideline worth taking a look at. White's rook can no longer annoy the queen as our bishop controls the whole diagonal. Also, we have an easier task undermining White's centre with either ...e6 or ...f5.  Nd7 !   13.Be3  It used to be very popular among GMs, but rather recent theory dismantled White's plans.  Nc6  The natural developing move is the best option. We also challenge the center.  14.d5  The main line and pretty much forced, the pressure is really high.   14.Rxb7  This is harmless for Black, but we need to know the ideas and again, not lower our guard !  Rab8  15.Rxb8  15. Rc7 will transpose to the main variation. One rook will be exchanged and the remaining one will go to d8 !  Rxb8  16.h3  d5 and ...Ne5 can not give White more than a balanced game.  Bxf3  17.Bxf3  Rd8 !?  We indeed want to force White to play d5 ! ...e6 !? was interesting, playing against a push on d5. However, this gives us a good game and I do not believe it is inferior at all ! Id rather be practical in this case.   17...Nxd4 ??  This does not work due to  18.Bxd4  Rd8  19.Qa1 !  +-  18.d5  The e5 square is now free to be occupied by our knight !  Ne5  14...Na5  15.Bg5  The main move at this point. 15. Bc5 transposes after ...b6 !? 16. Bxe7.  b6 !  This is what I meant when I pointed out than Be3 was really popular in the past. This move was a major breakthrough, as described by Svidler, Black can simply ignore the Bxe7 threat and get a very safe position. 15... Qa3 is the main line. However, after Re1, we reach an extremely complex position and I do not believe it is practical to memorise long lines for the purposes of this repertoire.   13.Rxb7  Regaining the pawn, but not for long !  Bxf3  14.Bxf3  Bxd4  Black is fine here. }
13... h6
{ We want to limit the dark-squared bishops scope by making it go somewhere else. It is key to understand the idea behind this great move. White has to make up his mind now about the future of the bishop: 1  If he decides to take on e7, we will get a quick counterplay. 2  If White decides to play Bh4, it will lose its influence over the c1-h6 diagonal. 3  If White decides to play Be3, our e7-pawn is not targeted anymore. }
14. Be3
{ The main move by far. Compare this position to 13. Be3. The difference is, indeed, the pawn on h6. Black weakens his kingside slightly, however, we also prevent White from using the g5 square for his minor pieces. White will try to keep our dark-squared bishop attached to defending h6. Also, White will have ideas linked with Bc4, targeting the g6-pawn, as the f7-pawn would be pinned.   14.Bxe7  Is a harmless move and Black here fights for a better game already.  Re8  15.Rxb7  Nd7 !?  15...Nc6 was played in Kramnik-Kasparov, Novgorod  (1994)  . However, the recommended move looks slightly better as we are not exposing our knight to White's mobile centre. See Hultin-Ernst, Gausdal  (1991)  . I believe Black has an edge in this position due to the fact that White lacks coordination and is highly pressured.   14.Bh4  A serious alternative which requires careful study.  a5 !?  ...g5 is the main line and has been played more, as it is also an older idea. However, I believe ...a5 is now more popular and stronger, and is also a preference of Vachier-Lagrave, who has played it recently. White has another big problem now: the a-pawn runs wild !  15.Rxb7  g5 !  16.Bg3  a4  There is not reason not to keep running ! }
14... Nc6 15. d5
{ White's main move by far.   15.Rxb7  Again we see this idea in a different position. It is important to understand the nuances. However, our play will be similar to the line without including h6.  Rab8 !?  Offering the exchange. White's rook is more active, and when the exchange happens, our rook on b8 will be more active than the opponents rook on f1.  16.Rxb8  Rxb8  17.h3 !  Bd7 !  The small nuance I mentioned. When we have played h6, the bishop should go to d7 instead of exchanging on f3 ! Now we defend our knight against White's threat: Qc1. }
15... Ne5
{ This is my recommendation. ...Na5 is the main line, and ...Bxf3 is also interesting. I trust Kasparov, who believed this was the strongest move. Black has no problems after }
16. Rxb7 a5
{ Again, I believe this gives Black a comfortable game and it also gives White another reason to worry about if he tries to overextend. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Repertoire Summaries"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Bc4 and 11...Qc7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4
{ And we reach the last chapter of the book. This is the classical choice of the Exchange Variation and it is also the most played option in the Grunfeld. White's idea is to continue the development with Ne2, avoiding the annoying pin with ...Bg4 after Nf3. In order to execute his plan, c4 is pretty much the only square the bishop can go to. The position of the bishop has been widely discussed among theoreticians. The main drawback for White is that the bishop could be vulnerable to future attacks  (...Rc8 or ...Na5)  . This means that, potentially, we may gain some tempi. }
7... c5
{ We challenge White's centre straight away. The 'd4 battle' will be a tough one ! }
8. Ne2
{ The main move by far and what makes sense after 7. Bc4. An alternative which transposes to the main line is 8. Be3 O-O 9. Ne2 Nc6. White also has the chance to transpose the 8. Nf3 variation after 9. Nf3.   8.Nf3 ?!  Generally speaking, the bishop on c4 and the knight on f3 do not work well together against the Grunfeld.  O-O  We are ready now to keep challenging the centre. }
8... Nc6 { Note that against 8... Bg4, White can reply with f3 ! } 9. Be3
{ 9.d5 ?!  Is not problematic for Black. But we should know how to meet this move.  Na5  10.Bb5+  Bd7  11.Qa4  Exchanging bishops would help us tremendously. We will make use of the c4-outpost, a very well-known idea in the Grunfeld.  b6  12.O-O  a6  13.Bxd7+  Qxd7  14.Qc2  Black has a very comfortable endgame if White exchanges queens. See Kuechler-Vargas Solano, Hermosillo  (2002)  .  O-O  15.Bg5  Nc4  16.a4  b5 !  I believe this is the best move at Black's disposal in this position. 16... e5 is also a logical possibility, but less ambitious. See Christiansen-Gulko, Estes Park  (1987)  . }
9... O-O 10. O-O
{ Is the main move which leads to the well-known tabiya of the 7. Bc4 variation.   10.Rc1  This move is a serious alternative to O-O. White is provoking ...cxd4, followed by ...Qa5+, but, why ? What is the idea behind this mysterious move ? Well, White wants to continue with h4, therefore he does not want to castle. At the same time, the rook on c1 defends c3 and the bishop on c4, which is a weakness at the moment.  cxd4  11.cxd4  Qa5+  Black's main and most logical continuation.  12.Kf1  By far White's main move in this position. White will try to launch an attack against our King. Also, note how White prefers to play Kf1 over Bd2. What do you think is the reason ? Well, losing the right to castle is better than affecting the central coordination and control, which is the biggest treasure White has in these positions.   12.Bd2  Is a logical alternative which is seen more at club level. However, this move is not very ambitious and does not cause us any problems. White weakens his center and his position lacks some coordination.  Qh5  13.d5  This is not the only move, but certainly the most challenging one at this point. It will be enough to know the ideas in this variation.  Ne5  White will have to lose the bishop pair as he cannot simply allow ...Nd3+. Black is doing fine in this position, as highlighted by Svidler in his analysis.  12...Qa3 !  A great move, it deserves at least one '!', but I think it should have one and a half at least ! This move has been played by Svidler and Anand, among other elite grandmasters. This movement's idea is two-fold: 1  We want to play ... Na5, attacking White's light-squared bishop. 2  We prevent h4, as ...Bg4 would be really annoying as f3 is not possible because the dark-squared bishop would be hanging ! }
10... Bd7
{ This positional approach is my recommendation. There are many other alternatives here for Black, and many of them interesting. However, apart from the fact that this variation scores well for Black, I believe it fits well in our repertoire and I have found some interesting ideas. Some elite GMs have played this move many times, like for example Vachier-Lagrave and, notably, Svidler. }
11. Rb1
{ The absolute main move of this variation. This move also happens to be the only one that scores above 50% at this point.   11.Rc1  A logical alternative. White indirectly defends the bishop on c4 in case there is a pawn exchange on d4. Note that White sometimes starts with 11. Qd2, but it transposes after ...Rc8 12. Rac1.  Rc8 !  Responding in kind.  12.Qd2  The main move in this variation.  Qa5 !  We are threatening ...cxd4, entering in a very good endgame for us.  13.Qb2  White's main move.   13.d5  An important alternative that we should know, as it is one of the main motifs to understand about the Exchange Variation in the Grunfeld. White has achieved one of the strategic aims of this variation: playing d5. So, what do we get in exchange for allowing this ? We will never allow White to play a comfortable c4 ! Our plan know is to prevent White from consolidating his position, we will gather our efforts around the c4-square. Another idea is to play the pawnbreak ...e6 in the right time.  Ne5  14.Bb3  Qa6 !  In order to understand this move, you should be aware of the fact that we almost never want to play ...c4 in this position. That would make it easier for White to find squares and an active role for his pieces. Instead, our plan is to place our knight on c4 ! Then, we have the plan of playing ...e6. If White plays c4 himself, then we have a very tempting pawnbreak with ...b5 !, generating a great counterplay on the queenside.  13...cxd4 !?  13... b6 is the move that Svidler recommends. It is a simple move, but it gives Black a comfortable game as well. However, the move I recommend provides us with a straightforward solution.   11.Qd2  This line transposes to 11. Rc1 after  Rc8  12.Rac1 }
11... Qc7
{ This is the main move at this point in the 10... Bd7 !? variation. It has been played regularly by elite GMs like Vachier-Lagrave or Svidler. 11... b6 !?N is analyzed in a separate chapter. }
12. Bf4
{ This is the main move. However, it does not score very well for White  (around 47%)  .   12.Bd3  A prophylactic, alternative idea which enjoys a similar popularity to Bf4. It is defined by Svidler, and I agree, as the central and most critical line of the whole ...Bd7 variation.  Rad8  This is Black's main option at this point. This move seems to be the favourite option from Vachier-Lagrave in this variation.  13.Qc1  White's main option at this point. His idea is to drive the queen to a3 and exert great pressure on Black's queenside now that the a-rook has moved to d8.  Bc8  A move that has been used before by Vachier-Lagrave and Mikhalevski, among others GMs.   13...Qd6  As mentioned by Svidler in his analysis, you have the option to sort out all your opening problems with this tactical sequence, which leads to a long forced sequence where we will sacrifice the queen for compensation.  14.Rd1  cxd4  15.cxd4  Nxd4  16.Nxd4  Bxd4  17.Bxd4  Qxd4  18.Bb5  Qxd1+  19.Qxd1  Bxb5  And now I like the analysis provided by Svidler for this variation: 'Black is a queen down, although he clearly has excellent drawing chances as his queenside will be very secure with the bishop on c6.'  14.Rd1  This is the universal reply to . ..Bc8.  Na5 !? N  I think this novelty becomes a really strong asset for this variation ! I have to confess that it was not easy to make up my mind between this move and ...e6 !?, which is also interesting. And now, let me show you an example of how this game may look like:   12.dxc5  If you have been studying the previous chapters, you may have the right feeling that this move should not give us many problems, it is actually what we want to happen !  Ne5 !?  This move has only been tried once in high-level games by Shishkin. In my opinion, ...Ne5 is a slightly better move than ...Na5 in this position. Apart from keeping an eye on c4, we have other moves in mind like ...Ng4. It is the flexibility what made me choose this one over ...Na5. In a5, the knight is too restricted in this case without having full control over c4 unlike in other variations.   12.Qd2  A move that gained some popularity around three years ago, but that has not been used in many games so far. White scores decently with it, but there are not many games and also it is not a hot line at the moment, so I believe it is difficult to evaluate it as of now.  cxd4 !? N  I am surprised that this is a novelty to be honest. By means of the following tactical sequence, we manage to simplify the position into a resulting one where Black is doing fine. The main move here is ...Rad8, and also ...Na5 is an option. }
12... e5
{ 12... Qc8 is the main line. However, I believe I have found an idea to bring this variation back to life ! }
13. Bg3
{ This is the main option. A move that has been analysed before and that is thought to give White the advantage, but I cannot agree with that evaluation.   13.dxe5  The alternative does not give Black any problems after  Nxe5 !  14.Bxe5  This is the only move that has been played in practice according to my database. Now Black was fine after   14.Bd5 !?  This could be a better attempt. It has been highlighted in other analysis, but without showing a way to reply to this idea. I think Black can continue with  Rab8  We want to continue with ...b5, gaining space and making White's light-squared bishop become sort of an observer of the position.  14...Bxe5  15.f4  Bg7  16.Bd5  Creating problems to our b7-pawn, but nothing really too serious.  Bc6  17.c4  Rab8  We want to continue with the pawn break ...b5, an idea that we have seen before in other chapters and what the position demands at this point. }
13... Rad8
{ I believe this is the strongest continuation for Black. We are threatening ... cxd4 now. }
14. Bd5
{ This is the main move, used in a couple of games more than the alternatives. This move is thought to give White a very nice position.   14.Bh4  This move is highlighted by Svidler as a good move for White in his analysis. The super GM gives ...Rc8 now for Black, but then White gets a really beautiful position and Black suffers. However, I recommend this interesting idea:  exd4 !  A great positional exchange sacrifice ! Black will get a great compensation with a strong dark-squared bishop.  15.Bxd8  Rxd8  16.cxd4 ?!  This is the only move that has been played in the only game in this variation, according to my database.  Nxd4  17.Nxd4  Bxd4  =∞  This happened in Fitiak-Vokarev, Izmailov Memorial  (2011)  . Black has sufficient compensation for the exchange and has no problems in this position. Note how strong is the dark-squared bishop, who has no counterpart, by the way !   14.d5  This move is not a problem for us, one of our ideas has always been ...Na5 anyway !  Na5  15.Bd3  c4 !?  An interesting strategic motif has arisen: we restrict White's position and gain the important c5 square. We will drive our queen there for now, who will have a great control of the dark squares in White's territory. }
14... Be6
{ This is, in my opinion, an extremely interesting novelty that may revolutionize the 12... e5 variation, hopefully giving it the credit it deserves ! }
*

