[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nf3 { The second most used option for White in this position. } 5...
O-O
{ This is our choice. However, ...dxc4 is also a possibility, as shown in an informational line. With this move order, White has the option of taking on d5, in which case we are following the main line within the 5.Nf3 variation. }
6. O-O dxc4
{ 6... c6 also equalises, so feel free to explore this option. However, I give 6... dxc4 to be consistent with the repertoire and style I propose in this course. }
7. Na3
{ By far the most common and best option for White. 7. Nc3 would transpose to one of the lines seen in 5. Nc3. }
7... Nc6
{ 7... c3 is the main continuation and an option worth exploring if you are interested. However, to keep consistency throughout our repertoire, I recommend this option, which is easier to grasp for our purposes. Do not think ...Nc6 is an inferior move at all, it is just another option and has been played by players such as Nepomniachtchi, Dominguez Perez, Nunn and Ftacnik. }
8. Nxc4 { other moves do not make sense } 8... Be6 9. b3
{ The only serious option for White in order to fight for the advantage. } 9...
Bd5 { 9... Qc8 !? is also possible and interesting. } 10. Bb2 a5
{ This is the main position of this line. White has space advantage and given the position of our pieces it will be difficult for us to prepare a pawn break to fight against d4. However, as Rowson points out in his book analysis, we have some assets that make up for that:  1- We have good control of the central light squares.  2- Our f8-rook will either go to d8  (after we find a good square for our Queen depending on White's play)  , or even stay on f8 to push a ...f5 pawn break.  3- The f6-knight may find another route via e8-d6 and sometimes may end up on e4, depending on White's play.  One important thing to note about this position is that we have to keep in mind that we need to find a plan and play with purpose. It is common knowledge that in the Grunfeld we need pawn breaks to play actively, so if we do not have these at our hand at the moment, it is not difficult to feel lost, but the comments provided in this line hopefully will help you with that. }
11. Rc1
{ a natural move and also the best one for White and the most played one. }
11... a4
{ adding some tension to the game proved to be in Black's favor. See Nikolic-Piket, Hoogovens Wijk aan Zee  (1997)  . 11... Ra6 !? is an interesting attempt. The a8-rook supports the a-pawn push. This idea was introduced by Korchnoi, and he followed with ...Na7-b5. See Van der Sterren, Kortschnoj, Lost Boys  (1997)  . }
12. bxa4 Ra6 13. Nfe5
{ This is a common idea we should pay attention to in these lines. Sometimes White plays this with good timing. If we maneuver without considering White's plan, we may find ourselves in a very compromised position. }
13... Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Qa8 15. Nxc6
{ In this specific situation, the open lines on the queenside make up for the damaged pawn structure. }
15... bxc6
{ The position is really interesting to play for both colors probably, but I would rather be Black here. Objectively speaking, it is an equal position. }
