[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 13"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nf3 { The second most used option for White in this position. } 5...
O-O
{ This is our choice. However, ...dxc4 is also a possibility, as shown in an informational line. With this move order, White has the option of taking on d5, in which case we are following the main line within the 5.Nf3 variation. }
6. cxd5
{ If we consider games from all the different move orders White can use, this is actually the most common line in the Fianchetto. His idea will be to castle and play with e4, trying to establish a good centre and make us lose a tempo with our knight. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O Nb6 { A prophylactic move against e4. } 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d5
{ The second most played option, with some reputation. This move has been played by Carlsen or Anand, for example. }
9... Na5 { equalises } 10. e4 c6
{ an important idea. We want to strike the center, get some space and open the c-file to support the ...Nc4 idea, also providing a good blockade on the d6 square if needed, but we should rely more on active play from our side, as we will see in many of the following lines. }
11. Bf4
{ An interesting move and the second most used option at this point. To be honest, in this case I would prefer White to play Bg5 than Bf4 if I had the black pieces. The move ...h6 is not really weakening as in other lines we will see in other chapters, where Qd2 comes handy, threatening on h6 with the bishop-queen combo, as we always have Nc4 to annoy White's setup. Also, b3 is not an option in many lines due to the fact that d5 is played and the a1-h8 diagonal is weak. }
11... Nac4 12. b3
{ is an interesting move that invites us to take on c3. White will get compensation for the exchange, but we should not be worse in any case. }
12... Bxc3 13. bxc4 Bxa1 14. Qxa1 cxd5 15. cxd5 f6
{ Honestly, in practical chess, I do not see any reasons not to play this move and try to keep the exchange. It is true that White has enough compensation for it, but I believe we should make it as difficult as we can for White and make him prove that on the board. We can always give the exchange back if needed under favourable conditions and seek active play again. }
16. Bh6 Re8 { The rook on e8 supports the e5 pawn break. } 17. e5
{ if White had not played e5, we would have played it ourselves either directly or after ...Bg4 }
17... Nxd5 18. Rd1 Qa5 { The position is about equal. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 14"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nf3 { The second most used option for White in this position. } 5...
O-O
{ This is our choice. However, ...dxc4 is also a possibility, as shown in an informational line. With this move order, White has the option of taking on d5, in which case we are following the main line within the 5.Nf3 variation. }
6. cxd5
{ If we consider games from all the different move orders White can use, this is actually the most common line in the Fianchetto. His idea will be to castle and play with e4, trying to establish a good centre and make us lose a tempo with our knight. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O Nb6 { A prophylactic move against e4. } 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d5
{ The second most played option, with some reputation. This move has been played by Carlsen or Anand, for example. }
9... Na5 { equalises } 10. e4 c6
{ an important idea. We want to strike the center, get some space and open the c-file to support the ...Nc4 idea, also providing a good blockade on the d6 square if needed, but we should rely more on active play from our side, as we will see in many of the following lines. }
11. Bf4
{ An interesting move and the second most used option at this point. To be honest, in this case I would prefer White to play Bg5 than Bf4 if I had the black pieces. The move ...h6 is not really weakening as in other lines we will see in other chapters, where Qd2 comes handy, threatening on h6 with the bishop-queen combo, as we always have Nc4 to annoy White's setup. Also, b3 is not an option in many lines due to the fact that d5 is played and the a1-h8 diagonal is weak. }
11... Nac4 12. Qe2
{ has been the most tried option at this point, and it is probably the most logical move. }
12... cxd5
{ 12... e5 is also an interesting move and I have to confess that it was not easy to make a decision at this point, I like both options, but I finally decided to keep 12...cxd5 as the main move and suggest the other idea I like as an alternative line along with a reference game. }
13. Nxd5
{ has not been tried in many games, and I think the reason why is that it does not really pose many real problems for Black in practical terms. }
13... Nxd5 14. exd5 Nb6
{ 14... Nxb2 has been played before, but White can continue with 15. Ne5 ! which gives him a great initiative and compensation. }
15. d6
{ interesting idea. Rather than losing the pawn on d5 and allowing us to play ...e6, White gives us the pawn and has a clear target while getting some initiative and developing his pieces. }
15... exd6 16. Rad1 d5 17. Rfe1 Bg4
{ provoking h3, we have seen this idea before. } 18. h3 Bd7 19. Qd2 Rc8
{ The rook on c8 aims at the entry square on c2, a great idea! } 20. Be5 Nc4
21. Qxd5 Nxe5 22. Nxe5 Be6
{ We give up a pawn, but get really active play in exchange. With that in mind and the bishop pair, we have more than enough compensation and the game is about equal. If White does not take the pawn on b7, we will have a slight advantage and a move we should keep in mind is ... Qa5 !, targeting the pawns on the queenside the knight on e5. }
23. Qxb7 Qc7 *

