{ 12... e5 is also an interesting move and I have to confess that it was not easy to make a decision at this point, I like both options, but I finally decided to keep the main move the main move and suggest the other idea I like as an alternative line along with a reference game. }
13. exd5 { The main option here for White. } 13... Bg4 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nd6
{ was played by Wei against Carlsen in the Bilbao Masters of 2016. I have included the game for you to have as a reference. Wei managed to establish a very solid position and Carlsen just could not break through, until Wei could play with ...e5 ! in good timing, ending up in a drawn endgame. Topalov played 15... Re8 against Carlsen one year later, followed by ...e5, but Carlsen proved Topalov's approach to be mistaken as that released the light-square bishop, allowing Carlsen to exchange it for the knight sitting on d5 just on time to create too many complications for the Bulgarian player. Carlsen won the game very convincingly. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 17"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nf3 { The second most used option for White in this position. } 5...
O-O
{ This is our choice. However, ...dxc4 is also a possibility, as shown in an informational line. With this move order, White has the option of taking on d5, in which case we are following the main line within the 5.Nf3 variation. }
6. cxd5
{ If we consider games from all the different move orders White can use, this is actually the most common line in the Fianchetto. His idea will be to castle and play with e4, trying to establish a good centre and make us lose a tempo with our knight. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O Nb6 { A prophylactic move against e4. } 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d5
{ The second most played option, with some reputation. This move has been played by Carlsen or Anand, for example. }
9... Na5 { equalises } 10. e4 c6
{ an important idea. We want to strike the center, get some space and open the c-file to support the ...Nc4 idea, also providing a good blockade on the d6 square if needed, but we should rely more on active play from our side, as we will see in many of the following lines. }
11. dxc6
{ is a weaker move than any of the bishop moves we have seen already. It seems that White simply does not want to put up a fight and Black is comfortable. }
11... Nxc6 12. Qe2 Bg4 13. Be3 Bxc3
{ This is not a very usual exchange in the Grunfeld. Why would we exchange our strong dark-squared bishop for the knight on c3? Well, it is justified in this position because we will create a perfect outpost on c4 for our knights, which will also allow us to regroup into a nice setup. }
14. bxc3 Ne5 15. h3 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Qc7
{ The position is about equal, but Black has a small edge. The knight will be a very good piece on c4. If White decides to exchange the knight on b6, it will be easier for us to target the weak pawns of White's queenside, there is not much risk for Black here and White needs to be careful. }
*

