[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nf3 { The second most used option for White in this position. } 5...
O-O
{ This is our choice. However, ...dxc4 is also a possibility, as shown in an informational line. With this move order, White has the option of taking on d5, in which case we are following the main line within the 5.Nf3 variation. }
6. cxd5
{ If we consider games from all the different move orders White can use, this is actually the most common line in the Fianchetto. His idea will be to castle and play with e4, trying to establish a good centre and make us lose a tempo with our knight. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O Nb6 { A prophylactic move against e4. } 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. e3
{ It is far more popular than 9.d5 } 9... Re8 10. d5
{ The second option. White tries to establish domination over the center and is confident that Black does not have sufficient play with a knight relegated to a5. }
10... Na5 11. Nd4 Bd7
{ This is the best way to challenge the center at the moment. } 12. b3 Rc8 13.
Bb2 c5 14. Nde2 { We do not have any problems in this line. } 14... e6 15. d6
Bc6 16. Rb1 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rc6
{ The pawn on d6 is going nowhere, we gain space on the queenside and are already doing better in this position. }
*

