6... Nxd5 7. O-O Nb6 { A prophylactic move against e4. } 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. e3
{ It is far more popular than 9.d5 } 9... Re8 10. d5
{ The second option. White tries to establish domination over the center and is confident that Black does not have sufficient play with a knight relegated to a5. }
10... Na5 11. Nd4 Bd7 12. e4 Rc8 13. Re1
{ The most logical continuation, preparing e5. } 13... c5 14. dxc6
{ with e4 made, it does not make much sense to capture on c6 to fight for any advantage here or even to get a comfortable position. This exchange favors Black's purposes. }
14... Nxc6 15. Nxc6 Bxc6
{ The position is objectively about equal, but, again, from a practical point of view I think Black has an edge and I would rather be Black here, no doubts. }
