[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 36"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces of the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld. However, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we are not playing positions that are typical in the Grunfeld where we get an asymmetrical structure and a rich, unbalanced position where we get a great initiative in exchange for the extra half-move we give White in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nf3 { The second most used option for White in this position. } 5...
O-O
{ This is our choice. However, ...dxc4 is also a possibility, as shown in an informational line. With this move order, White has the option to take on d5, in which case we are following the main line within the 5.Nf3 variation. }
6. cxd5
{ If we consider games from all the different move orders White can use, this is actually the most common line in the Fianchetto. His idea will be to castle and play with e4, trying to establish a good centre and make us lose tempo with our knight. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O Nb6 { A prophylactic move against e4. } 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. e3
{ It is far more popular than 9.d5 } 9... Re8 10. Nh4
{ Is an interesting idea that has been recommended by Avrukh in his Grandmaster Repertoire for White   1.d4  and also by Nicholas Pert on the Chessbase DVD 'Solid and Safe against the wild Indians - Play the Fianchetto'.  By playing Nh4, White has the strategic threat of 11.f4, so our next move is pretty much forced: }
10... e5 11. d5 Nb4
{ 11...Na5 is the main move. However, I found an idea in this variation that will give us good play. }
12. e4 { Is also a logical reply from White. } 12... c6 13. Qb3 Nd3 14. Be3 Nf4
{ This works perfectly for us from a tactical point of view! } 15. Rfd1
{ Black does not have any practical problems after 15.gxf4. } 15... cxd5 16.
exd5 Nxg2 17. Nxg2 Bg4 18. Rd2 Rc8
{ We threaten ...Nc4! White is pretty much obliged to continue with } 19. Bxb6
Qxb6
{ 19...axb6!? was played in Minko-Uzumcu, Veliko Gradiste Silver Lake op.  2017  .  The game is complicated. We have the bishop pair, but White's d-pawn restricts our play.   However, if White advances his pawn too soon, without arranging his army for it, we can always play ...Rc6, maneuver around the pawn until we capture it or generate other threats! Bear that in mind! }
*

