6... Nxd5 7. O-O Nb6 { A prophylactic move against e4. } 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. e3
{ It is far more popular than 9.d5 } 9... Re8 10. Nh4
{ Is an interesting idea that has been recommended by Avrukh in his Grandmaster Repertoire for White   1.d4  and also by Nicholas Pert on the Chessbase DVD 'Solid and Safe against the wild Indians - Play the Fianchetto'.  By playing Nh4, White has the strategic threat of 11.f4, so our next move is pretty much forced: }
10... e5 11. d5 Nb4 12. a3
{ In my opinion, starting with this move before e4 makes perfect sense. However, the alternative 12.e4 is similar and both moves enjoy a similar popularity. }
12... Na6 13. e4 c6 14. dxc6 bxc6
{ Do not believe the c6-pawn is weak. In this position, it controls the d5 and b5 squares. And later on, it can carry out more adventurous duties! }
15. Qc2 Nc5 16. Rd1 Qe7 17. Be3 Be6
{ an interesting novelty. 17...Ne6 has been played before by IM's Lei and Stany. However, I believe this recommendation is an improvement. For example: }
18. Bxc5 Qxc5 19. Nf3 { Coming back to the game after a while! } 19... Qe7
{ Black does not have any problems in this position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 38"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nf3 { The second most used option for White in this position. } 5...
O-O
{ This is our choice. However, ...dxc4 is also a possibility, as shown in an informational line. With this move order, White has the option of taking on d5, in which case we are following the main line within the 5.Nf3 variation. }
6. cxd5
{ If we consider games from all the different move orders White can use, this is actually the most common line in the Fianchetto. His idea will be to castle and play with e4, trying to establish a good centre and make us lose a tempo with our knight. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O Nb6 { A prophylactic move against e4. } 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. e3
{ It is far more popular than 9.d5 } 9... Re8 10. Re1
{ The most played option for White in this position, opposing the enemy rook on e8 and getting ready to play d5 followed by e4 if ...e5 is played. }
10... a5
{ In this variation we switch our play entirely to the queenside ! Remember this key move after 9... Re8, making as if we were going to play ...e5 }
11. Qe2 Be6
{ White has a weak complex of squares on the queenside, a recurring motif in the Grunfeld, we need to take advantage of it! }
12. Rd1 Bc4 13. Qc2 a4
{ winning more space on the queenside and preparing ...Nb4. } 14. Qb1
{ playing prophylactically. } 14... Nb4 15. e4 c5
{ A great move. We open the diagonal for our dark-square bishop and the pressure that we apply is significant. We are in position of creating weaknesses. }
16. dxc5
{ Is a better choice, but Black can equalise without much trouble and his position is easier to play in many cases. }
16... Bd3 17. Rxd3 Nxd3 18. cxb6 a3 19. e5 Rc8
{ The position is about equal with good play from White. We can take on b6 as the d3-knight is not really hanging as we have axb2. }
20. Qc2 Qxb6 21. Qxd3 axb2 22. Rb1 bxc1=Q+ 23. Rxc1 Red8
{ Again, White has to be very precise here not to fall in a worse position. We have great play with our rooks on the open files and our queen will play a very active role. }
*

