1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nf3 { The second most used option for White in this position. } 5...
O-O
{ This is our choice. However, ...dxc4 is also a possibility, as shown in an informational line. With this move order, White has the option of taking on d5, in which case we are following the main line within the 5.Nf3 variation. }
6. cxd5
{ If we consider games from all the different move orders White can use, this is actually the most common line in the Fianchetto. His idea will be to castle and play with e4, trying to establish a good centre and make us lose a tempo with our knight. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O Nb6 { A prophylactic move against e4. } 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. e3
{ It is far more popular than 9.d5 } 9... Re8 10. Re1
{ The most played option for White in this position, opposing the enemy rook on e8 and getting ready to play d5 followed by e4 if ...e5 is played. }
10... a5
{ In this variation we switch our play entirely to the queenside ! Remember this key move after 9... Re8, making as if we were going to play ...e5 }
11. Qe2 Be6 12. Nd2 { Preventing ...Bc4. } 12... Nb4 13. Rd1 c6 14. a3 N4d5 15.
Nce4
{ White controls the c5 square. This is a key moment in which we should react before White gets comfortable. }
15... Bf5 16. Nc5 e5
{ We finally strike the center and get some space for our pieces, while potentially opening the a1-h8 diagonal for our bishop. }
17. dxe5 Qe7 18. Nd3
{ any other choices are clearly worse. For example, 18. e4 allows us to play 18... Qxc5, with a better position. }
18... Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Qxe5
{ The position is complicated, but with good, active play from Black I believe. White has the bishop pair in his favor, but we have good squares for our knights and can generate some threats. See Nyzhnyk-Nepomniachtchi, Warsaw  (2011)  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 43"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Qb3
{ is a move that has only been used, in high-level games, by Kempinski in 2005. I have included his game as a reference for you to check. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4
{ White commits his queen too early and loses time, which allows us to have a comfortable lead in development and annoy the queen while placing our pieces on better squares on the queenside. }
6... O-O 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. O-O Be6
{ 8... Nd7, with similar ideas, was played in Kempinski-Schmidt  (Pol-cht, 2005)  . }
9. Qa4 Nd5
{ And Black is doing fine in this position. We will have active piece play and we will aim at playing ...e5 in the right moment to try and have a pawn majority on the queenside. Also, we could end up playing against an IQP  (isolated queen pawn)  . Luckily we have good blockaders and active play too. To sum up, the position is rich and complex enough to have a great game ahead ! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 44"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nc3
{ is another secondary variation that we should know how to face. However, you will be glad to know that this variation is not good for White after our next move, in which White's best variation scores just around 36%! }
5... dxc4
{ We can already fight for the advantage, which can turn into a comfortable and clear advantage in many lines if White does not play accurately. }
6. Nf3 { This is the second alternative from White, with about 45 games. } 6...
c6 7. O-O
{ 7. a4 a5 was played in Lombardy-Tarjan, USA-ch, Pasadena  (1978)  . I have included this game because I find the way Black plays very instructive. }
7... O-O 8. a4 Na6 { And this is good for Black. For example: } 9. Ne5
{ A logical move, but we have a dynamic and active response: } 9... Ng4
{ With this move, we put a great amount of pressure on d4. } 10. Nxg4 Bxg4 11.
Be3
{ White simply can not afford playing passively here, he is a pawn down and we quickly mobilise our pieces. }
11... Qa5
{ Our queen is placed well on a5 temporarily, giving support to a possible ...Nc5 after d5 from White. It also leaves the d8 square for a rook to carry out our plan. }
12. Qc1 Rad8 13. Rd1 Rfe8 { We are preparing ...e5 } 14. h3 Bf5
{ Normally, in these variations, we would play ...Be6, but in this case White can not follow up with e4, so the bishop is slightly better placed on f5. We will follow with ...e5 and enjoy a clear advantage. }
*

