[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nc3
{ is another secondary variation that we should know how to face. However, you will be glad to know that this variation is not good for White after our next move, in which White's best variation scores just around 36%! }
5... dxc4
{ We can already fight for the advantage, which can turn into a comfortable and clear advantage in many lines if White does not play accurately. }
6. Nf3 { This is the second alternative from White, with about 45 games. } 6...
c6 7. O-O
{ 7. a4 a5 was played in Lombardy-Tarjan, USA-ch, Pasadena  (1978)  . I have included this game because I find the way Black plays very instructive. }
7... O-O 8. a4 Na6 { And this is good for Black. For example: } 9. Ne5
{ A logical move, but we have a dynamic and active response: } 9... Ng4 10.
Nxg4 Bxg4 11. d5
{ The best attempt by White at this point, trying to justify being a pawn down with active play, but we are clearly better again. }
11... Nb4 12. dxc6 bxc6 13. a5
{ White prevents ...a5, bolstering a knight on b4 and minimizing his options on the queenside. }
13... Qc7
{ We are again clearly better. While White may have a slight compensation for the pawn due to his better pawn structure, it is not really such, as our pawns on the c-file prevent White from using a few squares to execute his plans. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 46"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nc3
{ is another secondary variation that we should know how to face. However, you will be glad to know that this variation is not good for White after our next move, in which White's best variation scores just around 36%! }
5... dxc4
{ We can already fight for the advantage, which can turn into a comfortable and clear advantage in many lines if White does not play accurately. }
6. Nf3 { This is the second alternative from White, with about 45 games. } 6...
c6 7. O-O
{ 7. a4 a5 was played in Lombardy-Tarjan, USA-ch, Pasadena  (1978)  . I have included this game because I find the way Black plays very instructive. }
7... O-O 8. a4 Na6 { And this is good for Black. For example: } 9. e4
{ This has been the most played move after 8... Na6 !? See Shabalov-Atalik, Philadelphia  (1998)  for a reference game against 9. a5 from White. }
9... Bg4
{ We are ready to put some extra pressure on the center. Always pay attention to these moments, it is the key of the Grunfeld. }
10. Qe2 Nb4
{ 10... Bxf3 ?! would give White some initiative unnecessarily. It is true that we would be two pawns up, but only temporarily as White will play either Be3 or Rd1, winning tempo and then capturing on c4. This is not a path we want to go down to. }
11. Be3 Nd3 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3
{ After 13. Qxf3, we can react the same way, with e5 ! This leads to a very similar position with the same plan. }
13... e5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. Rab1
{ 15. e6 ?! is the typical move that many players believe is good as it damages the opponent's pawn structure. The truth is it opens more options for us: now we will have the f-file open for us, the a1-h8 diagonal is open and our bishop in the best possible square the moment  (without needing to take on e5 and come back to g7 after Bg2 and f4)  . Also, we have to keep in mind that we may want to play ... c5 in the future  (preparing our push on the queenside)  , but the d5 square will be protected by the e6-pawn. }
15... Qa5 { Black has the advantage and an easier game. } *

