[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 51"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nc3
{ is another secondary variation that we should know how to face. However, you will be glad to know that this variation is not good for White after our next move, in which White's best variation scores just around 36%! }
5... dxc4
{ We can already fight for the advantage, which can turn into a comfortable and clear advantage in many lines if White does not play accurately. }
6. e4
{ is not the best idea for White in this position, as the scoring shows for this variation. }
6... O-O 7. Nge2 c6
{ the idea here is to bolster the d5 square and prevent White from advancing his center with e5 under good conditions. We will gain space on the queenside and try to have the square b4 as well at our disposal with the idea of Na6-b4 at the right time. }
8. O-O Na6 { We are preparing to mobilize the queenside. } 9. f4 Nc7 10. a4
{ preventing ...b5 } 10... a5 11. h3
{ 11. e5 is a bad move due to Nfd5 !  (we see the idea of ...c6)  . We have great play with ideas like ...Nb4-d3, ...b5 at some point... Black would have a clear advantage in such position. }
11... Na6
{ now with a4-...a5 played, Na6 makes sense once again, we have the square b4 for our knight and we can organise a possible ...b5 in good conditions, and the a5 pawn will be defended by the queen once the a-file opens if that's the case. Black has a slight edge in this position. }
12. g4 Nb4 13. Be3 e6
{ White has some compensation for the pawn, but it is clearly not enough and we have a slight, comfortable advantage. }
14. g5
{ White must try something or his position will simply be worse and passive and we would have free hands to play on the queenside, place our pieces in better squares and then play with ...b5 ! at some point. }
14... Ne8 15. h4 f5
{ We can not let White play f5 himself, that would give him too much space and good squares for his pieces. We try to establish a bind on the kingside and play comfortably on the queenside. It may be necessary to give back the pawn at some point to get a good initiative and dynamic play. Black is slightly better in this position. }
