[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 52"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nc3
{ is another secondary variation that we should know how to face. However, you will be glad to know that this variation is not good for White after our next move, in which White's best variation scores just around 36%! }
5... dxc4
{ We can already fight for the advantage, which can turn into a comfortable and clear advantage in many lines if White does not play accurately. }
6. Qa4+
{ This is White's universal response in the 5... dxc4 variation, with around 200 games. White is threatening to win the pawn back immediately. }
6... Nfd7
{ An odd-looking move. However, this option, chosen by players such as Vachier-Lagrave, Kempinksi and Miles, among other strong GMs, has proved to be a very strong antidote against White's attempt, as we can see from White's score in these variations  (around 29%)  . We want to question the position of the White Queen by winning at least a tempo. Also, this is a prophylactic move against e4. }
7. d5
{ White's attempt to avoid our natural development with ...Nc6 followed by ...Nb6 is not good enough. }
7... O-O 8. Qxc4 c6 9. dxc6 Ne5 10. Qh4 Nbxc6 11. Nf3
{ 11. Bxc6 ? See Agdestein-Ftacnik, Manila  (1990)  . After 11... bxc6, White makes Black's life easier by opening the b-file too. Black is ahead in development and Ftacnik soon showed how to gradually increase the pressure until White has nothing better than resigning. A very instructive game. At this point, Black's advantage is almost decisive. }
11... Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 Qa5 13. O-O Bf6 { White was threatening Bxc6 and Qxe7 }
14. Qf4 Rd8
{ In this symmetrical position, the only differential factors are the position of the queens  (ours is better placed)  and the fact that we get to occupy the d-file first. Black has an edge in this position. }
*

