1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. Nc3
{ is another secondary variation that we should know how to face. However, you will be glad to know that this variation is not good for White after our next move, in which White's best variation scores just around 36%! }
5... dxc4
{ We can already fight for the advantage, which can turn into a comfortable and clear advantage in many lines if White does not play accurately. }
6. Qa4+
{ This is White's universal response in the 5... dxc4 variation, with around 200 games. White is threatening to win the pawn back immediately. }
6... Nfd7
{ An odd-looking move. However, this option, chosen by players such as Vachier-Lagrave, Kempinksi and Miles, among other strong GMs, has proved to be a very strong antidote against White's attempt, as we can see from White's score in these variations  (around 29%)  . We want to question the position of the White Queen by winning at least a tempo. Also, this is a prophylactic move against e4. }
7. Nf3 { White's main option at this point. } 7... Nc6 8. e3
{ Looks like a solid move. However, the continuation hopefully makes you understand why 8. Qxc4 is a better try and, also, how practical is to enter these lines from Black's perspective, which maintains a better score overall. }
8... Nb6 { Winning a tempo on the queen. } 9. Qb5 Qd6
{ The queen sits well on d6. } 10. O-O a6 11. Qc5 Bf5
{ A great maneuver, taking advantage of the weak d3 square in White's territory. }
12. Ng5 Bd3 13. Rd1 Qxc5 14. dxc5 Bxc3 15. cxb6 Bf6 16. Nh3 O-O-O 17. bxc7 Kxc7
{ Black is clearly better. See Malyshev-Savchenko, Moscow op.  2018  . } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 55"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. cxd5
{ This move is by far the most played option in the Grunfeld move order. } 5...
Nxd5 6. Nc3
{ Combining the Fianchetto with Nc3 seems strange for White because of } 6...
Nxc3 7. bxc3
{ White has a weak light-square complex on the queenside, especially the c4 square, which is no longer guarded by the light-square bishop. }
7... c5 8. e3
{ as Rowson highlighted, this was the preferred option many years ago, bolstering the center and blocking our g7-bishop. However, White has some problems with the coordination of the pieces and the dark-square bishop has some problems to play an active role. }
8... Qa5
{ This option is a modern approach that scores well for Black, putting pressure and leaving the d-file for the rook. }
9. Bd2 O-O 10. Ne2 Nc6 11. O-O Rd8 12. Nc1
{ White recycles the knight, which will go to b3. } 12... Qc7
{ prophylaxis against Nb3. } 13. Nb3 b6
{ A nice idea. We invite White to take the pawn, and then again on b6 ! We generate a great initiative in exchange. }
14. d5 { is most likely a better try from White. } 14... c4 15. dxc6 cxb3 16.
axb3 Be6 { A great maneuver to capture the weak pawn on c6. } 17. Qc2 Bd5
{ Objectively speaking, the position is about equal, but I think Black could have a small edge due to the fact that we can create weaknesses that are easier to target, especially with ...a5-a4. }
