[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 61"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 { This move is by far the most played option. } 5... Nxd5 6. Nc3
{ Combining the Fianchetto with Nc3 seems strange for White because of } 6...
Nxc3 7. bxc3
{ White has a weak light-square complex on the queenside, especially the c4 square, which is no longer guarded by the light-square bishop. }
7... c5 8. Nf3 { The most logical continuation and the main move. } 8... Nc6
{ We can delay castling in these lines. } 9. Be3
{ The move we should really pay attention too and White's main option at this point. }
9... cxd4
{ 9...O-O is also possible, but I like to give the chance to White of going wrong by capturing on d4 with pawn. }
10. Nxd4 Na5
{ Clearly we deny exchanging knights! We want to take advantage of White's weaknesses on the queenside! }
11. O-O a6
{ We secure the b5 square with the idea of playing Qc7 and apply some pressure on the c-file. Also, after castling, our rook may end up on d8 and ... e5 is always an interesting idea. }
12. Qd3 O-O 13. c4 Qc7 14. Rac1 Rd8
{ See Bai-Zhao, CHN cht  (2018)  . The position is about equal, we can achieve active play, as you can see in the mentioned game, and that compensates for the space advantage from White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Fianchetto Variation - 3.g3"]
[Black "Fianchetto Grunfeld: 3.g3 Bg7 62"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 { This move is by far the most played option. } 5... Nxd5 6. e4
{ The most testing move. The position will acquire an independent nature compared to other lines, which could be reached from different transpositions. Note also how 6. Nf3 transposes to 5. Nf3. }
6... Nb6 7. Ne2
{ White's idea is to play d5 if we play ...Nc6, as we would usually do. After that, we would need to play either ...e6 or ...c6 to get some space to develop our army. As Rowson mentioned in his book. It is common to see White with a clamping pawn on d5, and we can just slowly play to get rid of it. As we remove the d5 pawn, we uncover the g2-bishop and make it stronger, so White is not totally unhappy with that in any case. }
7... c5
{ It is well known that in the Grunfeld it is important to hit the center as soon as possible. There are other options, like ...Nc6 or ...e5 !? I was indeed considering ...e5 for this repertoire, and it is perfectly playable, but I believe ...c5 matches the rest of our repertoire better in general. }
8. dxc5
{ A rare continuation. We could almost count with our fingers the number of times this has been played in high-level games. }
8... Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Na4 10. Nbc3 Nxc5 11. Be3 Nba6 12. Kc2
{ And now it is important that you know that Black obtains good play with several options. Do not get obsessed with memorising lines at this point and try to remember the ideas ! }
12... f5
{ We spice things up with ...f5. The open files generated will give us a good game with fair chances, but objectively the position is equal. }
13. a3 O-O 14. Rad1 fxe4 15. b4 Nd3 16. Nxe4 Ne5
{ Black is doing fine in this equal position. 16... Nb2 !? was played in Filippov-Goloshchapov, Dubai op  (2002)  and it is also another possibility. Take a look at the game included for reference to get a better feeling of the position. }
*

