1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ As GM Rowson mentioned in his excellent book 'Understanding the Grunfeld', this is an option Grunfeld players do not like to face. We are used to our g7-bishop being one of the strongest pieces on the board in many variations due to the nature of the Grunfeld.  Here, however, we will have a mirror image on g2 pointing at the center, and White gets to exert pressure on the center before us  (this is how the game works !)  . This means we don't get to play the typical richly unbalanced Grunfeld positions with an asymmetrical structure and a great initiative to compensate for White's extra half-move in the opening. It is important to keep this in mind as we would need to play as the position demands. }
3... Bg7
{ 3... d5 is also possible and should transpose, but it is less flexible } 4.
Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 { This move is by far the most played option. } 5... Nxd5 6. e4
{ The most testing move. The position will acquire an independent nature compared to other lines, which could be reached from different transpositions. Note also how 6. Nf3 transposes to 5. Nf3. }
6... Nb6 7. Ne2
{ White's idea is to play d5 if we play ...Nc6, as we would usually do. After that, we would need to play either ...e6 or ...c6 to get some space to develop our army. As Rowson mentioned in his book. It is common to see White with a clamping pawn on d5, and we can just slowly play to get rid of it. As we remove the d5 pawn, we uncover the g2-bishop and make it stronger, so White is not totally unhappy with that in any case. }
7... c5
{ It is well known that in the Grunfeld it is important to hit the center as soon as possible. There are other options, like ...Nc6 or ...e5 !? I was indeed considering ...e5 for this repertoire, and it is perfectly playable, but I believe ...c5 matches the rest of our repertoire better in general. }
8. d5 { The main move in this position. } 8... O-O 9. O-O e6
{ A common idea in the Grunfeld, putting pressure in White's center as soon as possible. You should avoid capturing on d5 quickly here, as a pawn advancing to d6 after capturing opens the h1-a8 diagonal for the White bishop. The pawn on d6 on itself is not really dangerous and not the main concern for us, but the pressure exerted by the g2-bishop could prove decisive in some variations. If White advances to d6 himself, that pawn will become vulnerable. As a rule of thumb, we will keep the tension on the centre until White defines where his knights will head to, as we will explore in the different variations now. }
10. Nec3
{ The main move and a stronger continuation  (scores better)  than 10. Nbc3. White coordinates his knights better with this move, as Nd2 is an option, covering the c4 square. }
10... Na6
{ We keep an eye on playing ...e5. The b6-knight will end up on d6, supporting both common pawn breaks: ...f5 and ...b5. Depending on White's play, we will react on one side or the other. }
11. a4 { The main option for White. } 11... exd5 12. exd5 Nc4 13. Na3
{ An alternative that has been played in a few games. } 13... Ne5
{ An important move to keep in mind. The a3-knight will not have an easy time coming back into the game. }
14. Be3 Bg4 15. Qb3 Nf3+ 16. Kh1
{ The move played by So in 2011. Black has nothing to be afraid of. If White decides to go greedy and take on b7 after Bxf3, we will play 17... Qf6 !, will more than full compensation for the pawn and a great initiative and dynamism. }
16... Qd7 17. d6
{ I believe this move has not been played before at high-level. It is probably a better move than any other alternative at this point. White's idea is to free the h1-a8 diagonal before taking on b7. }
17... Qxd6 { This is not a good idea for us } 18. h3 Nd4 19. Qxb7 Rfb8 20. Qe4
Bf5 21. Qh4
{ White is slightly better in this position, and we would have to play really accurate not to fall on a clearly worse position. }
