{ taking the king out of the g1-a7 diagonal. } 19... Nb4 20. Bxe5 Bxe5 21. f4
Bf6
{ The position is objectively equal. White has to be careful with advancing the d-pawn too quickly as it could be very vulnerable on d6. We cover important squares with the position of our pieces. White may push with a5 and Na4 to put pressure on the c5 pawn, with ideas ike Rc1, but we will exchange the d7-bishop if that happens. We will control the d-pawn from advancing further with Rad8 and take on g5 too if necessary. }
