[White "Saemisch Variation (surprise) - 3.f3 Nh5!?"]
[Black "The Saemisch: 3.f3 Nh5!? 8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ this is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... Nh5
{ Even though this move does not lead to typical Grunfeld positions, I recommend this choice as a surprise weapon. We can indeed catch White off guard with this line in more than one variation. I would like to bring your attention to something. If White plays the strongest moves that he has at his disposal, both IM Mikel Huerga and I have our doubts about Black's position, more precisely about the fact that it is exactly pleasant to play and in the spirit of the Grunfeld. However, we still believe this variation can serve you really well as a surprise for certain games and it has, without any doubts, a very dangerous poison waiting to be released ! Black's idea revolves around a quick ...e5 !, taking advantage of the weak dark-square complex around White's king as we open lines for our queen. At this point, White has four main options: e4  (the main move)  , g4, Bg5 and Nc3. }
4. g4
{ White's attempt to question our knight's position weakens his position and we can play very actively with }
4... e5 5. Be3 Ng7 6. dxe5 Nc6 7. Nc3 Nxe5
{ GM Kayden W. Troff played 7... Be7, but I recommend taking on e5 first in this situation. They seem similar, but ...Be7 gives White more options which may be better than what followed in the game provided. }
8. b3 Ne6
{ it is a great idea to centralize our second knight, that gives us a great control on the position. It is not easy to see what is the best way for White to develop his pieces in this position. For example, after }
9. Nh3 b5
{ This is the idea I would like to propose in this position. We sacrifice a pawn in exchange for development, which would make it even harder for White to coordinate his pieces harmoniously. }
10. cxb5 Bb7
{ With this move, we are threatening ...Nxg4 as the rook on h1 is hanging! }
11. Rg1 d5
{ This is the key to fully understand Ne6, we have a great control over the position and have a much healthier pawn structure. Note how the extra pawn for White is irrelevant in this position. Also, note how tactics work in our favor as we have a more coordinated position and due to White's many weaknesses. }
12. f4 { this quite does not work for White due to } 12... d4 13. fxe5 dxe3 14.
Qxd8+ Rxd8 15. Bg2 Bb4 16. Rc1 Bxg2 17. Rxg2 h5 18. g5 Rd2 *

