[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Saemisch Variation (surprise) - 3.f3 Nh5!?"]
[Black "The Saemisch: 3.f3 Nh5!? 17"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ this is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... Nh5
{ Even though this move does not lead to typical Grunfeld positions, I recommend this choice as a surprise weapon. We can indeed catch White off guard with this line in more than one variation. I would like to bring your attention to something. If White plays the strongest moves that he has at his disposal, both IM Mikel Huerga and I have our doubts about Black's position, more precisely about the fact that it is exactly pleasant to play and in the spirit of the Grunfeld. However, we still believe this variation can serve you really well as a surprise for certain games and it has, without any doubts, a very dangerous poison waiting to be released ! Black's idea revolves around a quick ...e5 !, taking advantage of the weak dark-square complex around White's king as we open lines for our queen. At this point, White has four main options: e4  (the main move)  , g4, Bg5 and Nc3. }
4. Bg5
{ the idea of this move is to prevent ...e5, which would question White about his early f3, weakening the kingside in exchange for imminent control of the center. }
4... Bg7 5. Nc3 h6
{ I believe this is a more accurate move order than what Mikhalevski played   5...c5  in his game against Kavutskiy  (Calgary op, 2016)  . The idea is to force Be3 or, even better for Black, Bh4 ?!, where the dark-square White bishop loses his influence on the queenside and we are ready to strike with ...c5 ! }
6. Bh4 c5 7. d5 { transposes to the game mentioned before. } 7... d6 8. e3 b5
{ was the option chosen by Mikhalevski. I can not negate that the idea is interesting, following a Benko Gambit approach, and this is why I would like to recommend this line as an alternative should you happen to feel adventurous at some point. Objectively, Black is not worse in this position and it is really sharp and full of active plan. Our compensation for the pawn will be on the open a and b files and some great piece play on the queenside, apart from a very good bishop on g7. }
