[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Saemisch Variation (surprise) - 3.f3 Nh5!?"]
[Black "The Saemisch: 3.f3 Nh5!? 25"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ this is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... Nh5
{ Even though this move does not lead to typical Grunfeld positions, I recommend this choice as a surprise weapon. We can indeed catch White off guard with this line in more than one variation. I would like to bring your attention to something. If White plays the strongest moves that he has at his disposal, both IM Mikel Huerga and I have our doubts about Black's position, more precisely about the fact that it is exactly pleasant to play and in the spirit of the Grunfeld. However, we still believe this variation can serve you really well as a surprise for certain games and it has, without any doubts, a very dangerous poison waiting to be released ! Black's idea revolves around a quick ...e5 !, taking advantage of the weak dark-square complex around White's king as we open lines for our queen. At this point, White has four main options: e4  (the main move)  , g4, Bg5 and Nc3. }
4. e4 { White's main option, grabbing more central space. } 4... e5 5. Be3
{ White's best move and the only serious option to fight for the advantage. White supports the center and defends the weak dark square complex on the kingside. This is the variation I mentioned in the introduction which may not be to the liking of everyone. However, White has to know these lines to play the strongest moves all the time, and these lines are not very common ! }
5... Bb4+ { We take advantage of this tempo to develop our bishop. } 6. Nc3
exd4 7. Qxd4 O-O 8. O-O-O Nc6 9. Qd2 d6 10. g4 Ng7 11. a3 Ba5
{ We keep pinning the queen on d2, which makes White make up his mind at this point and reduces his flexibility. Also, ...Bb6 is a more attractive option than ...Bc5 directly in my opinion. }
12. Qc2
{ It is really human to get rid of the pin. However, I believe this is a wrong plan executed in a wrong time. 12. h4 ! would have given White better chances. }
12... Bb6 13. Bxb6 { 13. Nd5 may be a better attempt. } 13... axb6 14. h4 Ne5
15. Kb1 h5
{ An interesting novelty ! 15... f5 was played in Sviridov-Fedoseev, Kolomna  (2016)  , which I have included as a reference as it is a really instructive game. }
16. gxh5 Nxh5 17. Qc1 { White's best move, threatening to continue with f4. }
17... f5
{ And we reply actively ! 15... h5 !? was a move preparing this pawn break, which gives us active chances. }
18. f4 Ng4 19. Nh3 fxe4 20. Nxe4 Bf5 21. Bd3 Qd7 22. Rhg1 Rae8 23. Ng3 Nxg3 24.
Rxg3 Kf7
{ Black does not have any problems in this position. Our pieces are on good squares and we can embark our King on a journey towards the queenside via e7. }
*

