[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Saemisch Variation (main) - 3.f3 d5"]
[Black "The Saemisch: 3.f3 d5 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ This is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... d5 { The f6-Knight usually ends up on b6 in this variation. } 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 { 6. Be3 will most likely transpose after 6... Bg7 7. Nc3 }
6... Bg7
{ Note how now our common plan in the Grunfeld of playing with ...c5 to challenge White's centre does not work as our knight is on b6 and White wins a tempo ! }
7. Be3 O-O 8. f4
{ The most serious attempt for White, after the main move   8.Qd2  , to get an advantage. }
8... Nc6 9. Nf3 Bg4
{ If White delays d5, we want to develop our light-square bishop to the best possible square at this point. }
10. d5 Na5
{ Remember this idea ! Now it makes more sense to play ...Na5 ! After including the moves Nf3-Bg4. }
11. Bd4 Bxf3 12. gxf3 e6
{ Black is slightly better here already, tactics work in our favor and there are a few threats on the board. If White does not play accurately here, the advantage soon will increase and we will be clearly better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Saemisch Variation (main) - 3.f3 d5"]
[Black "The Saemisch: 3.f3 d5 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ this is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... d5 { The f6-Knight usually ends up on b6 in this variation. } 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 { 6. Be3 will most likely transpose after 6... Bg7 7. Nc3 }
6... Bg7
{ Note how now our common plan in the Grunfeld of playing with ...c5 to challenge White's centre does not work as our knight is on b6 and White wins a tempo ! }
7. Be3 O-O 8. f4
{ the most serious attempt for White, after the main move   8.Qd2  , to get an advantage. }
8... Nc6 9. Nf3 Bg4
{ if White delays d5, we want to develop our light-square bishop to the best possible square at this point. }
10. d5 Na5
{ Remember this idea ! Now it makes more sense to play ...Na5 ! After including the moves Nf3-Bg4. }
11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nbc4
{ 12... c6 was played in Ivanisevic-Fedoseev, Wch Blitz 9th  (2015)  , and it really does not change things much if you take a look at the mentioned game that I have included for your reference.  12...Nac4 is also playable. However, we do not want to give White the option of Bxb6. }
13. Bxc4 Nxc4 14. Bf2 c6
{ The game is about equal at this point, but White still needs to be precise or we can fight to get a tangible advantage. For example, playing careless with O-O-O would give us a tremendous initiative on the queenside with ...Rc8 and ...Qa5. In case you are wondering whether 14... Nxb2 is possible or not at this point. Well, it is; however, after 15. e5, the position is highly complex. }
*

