[Round "?"]
[White "Saemisch Variation (main) - 3.f3 d5"]
[Black "The Saemisch: 3.f3 d5 5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ this is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... d5 { The f6-Knight usually ends up on b6 in this variation. } 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 { 6. Be3 will most likely transpose after 6... Bg7 7. Nc3 }
6... Bg7
{ Note how now our common plan in the Grunfeld of playing with ...c5 to challenge White's centre does not work as our knight is on b6 and White wins a tempo ! }
7. Be3 O-O 8. f4
{ the most serious attempt for White, after the main move   8.Qd2  , to get an advantage. }
8... Nc6 9. d5 { White's main move by far. } 9... Nb8
{ I want to recommend this move over 9... Na5, which is perfectly playable, but I have found that White can win the initiative in some lines I have studied from different sources. }
10. a4
{ The most logical response from White, 10. Nf3, does not work very well due to ...c6 ! We would challenge the center, making room for our pieces and, also, we will follow with the thematic ...e5 ! }
10... e5
{ We need to hit the center immediately due to White's threat: a5. We want to release the e5 square for our knight  (Nd7-e5) }
11. a5
{ 11. fxe5 is not a problem. We can just recapture the pawn and play ...Bg4. That is what happened in Gheorghiu-Ftacnik, Mallorca  (1989)  . }
11... N6d7 12. Nf3 exf4 13. Bxf4 Qe7 14. Bxc7 Nc5
{ White's position falls apart, he can not grab the pawn on c7. } 15. d6 Bxc3+
16. bxc3 Qxe4+ *

