[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Saemisch Variation (main) - 3.f3 d5"]
[Black "The Saemisch: 3.f3 d5 7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ this is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... d5 { The f6-Knight usually ends up on b6 in this variation. } 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 { 6. Be3 will most likely transpose after 6... Bg7 7. Nc3 }
6... Bg7
{ Note how now our common plan in the Grunfeld of playing with ...c5 to challenge White's centre does not work as our knight is on b6 and White wins a tempo ! }
7. Be3 O-O 8. a4
{ White tries to question our setup, but by doing so he weakens the b4 square. }
8... a5 { fixing the queenside and bolstering the b4 outpost. } 9. Rc1 e5
{ I really like this idea, and it makes even more sense after our next move. It is a recurrent concept in the Grunfeld to break White's center, we can not just let White occupy the center at will. }
10. d5 Bh6
{ This is a novelty. The idea is to highlight the weaknesses on White's queenside dark squares by exchanging our 'blocked' bishop. We will try to make use of the b4-square if White allows it. }
11. Bxh6 Qh4+ 12. g3 Qxh6
{ White worsens his pawn structure for no real reason and we are slightly better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Saemisch Variation (main) - 3.f3 d5"]
[Black "The Saemisch: 3.f3 d5 8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ this is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... d5 { The f6-Knight usually ends up on b6 in this variation. } 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 { 6. Be3 will most likely transpose after 6... Bg7 7. Nc3 }
6... Bg7
{ Note how now our common plan in the Grunfeld of playing with ...c5 to challenge White's centre does not work as our knight is on b6 and White wins a tempo ! }
7. Be3 O-O 8. a4
{ White tries to question our setup, but by doing so he weakens the b4 square. }
8... a5 { fixing the queenside and bolstering the b4 outpost. } 9. Rc1 e5
{ I really like this idea, and it makes even more sense after our next move. It is a recurrent concept on the Grunfeld to break White's center, we can not just let White occupy the center at his will. }
10. d5 Bh6
{ This is a novelty. The idea is to highlight the weaknesses on White's queenside dark squares by exchanging our 'blocked' bishop. We will try to make use of the b4-square if White allows so. }
11. Qd2 { White's most logical reaction. } 11... Bxe3 12. Qxe3 Na6 13. Bxa6
{ if White does not take on a6, we simply play ...Nb4 !, followed by ...c6. Black does not have any problems in that case. }
13... Rxa6 14. b3 c6 15. dxc6 bxc6 16. Nge2 Qh4+ 17. g3 Qh3
{ Our idea is to cause White some problems with his coordination  (especially the rook on h1 and his king)  . Once our queen has to move from h3 we will simply go to e6 and apply pressure on b3, which is why we will play ...Nd7 and ...Rb6 too ! The position is about equal, but I would rather be in Black's shoes here as I would find it easier to come up with a plan. }
