1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ this is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... d5 { The f6-Knight usually ends up on b6 in this variation. } 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 { 6. Be3 will most likely transpose after 6... Bg7 7. Nc3 }
6... Bg7
{ Note how now our common plan in the Grunfeld of playing with ...c5 to challenge White's centre does not work as our knight is on b6 and White wins a tempo ! }
7. Be3 O-O 8. Rc1
{ considered often as a waiting move in these variations. It could lead to some tactical variations where White should pay attention not to get a worse position. }
8... Nc6 9. d5 Ne5 10. Bd4 { The most played move. } 10... c6
{ We are following Goglidze-Spielmann, Moscow 1935. } 11. f4
{ the only serious option for White. Other moves are not problematic at all for us. }
11... Ng4 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Be2
{ White may think he has achieved his main goals: natural development, central advantage and exchanging the dark-square bishops, and even taking on c6 and thus getting a better pawn structure on the queenside, but Black has a very strong resource in this position: }
13... e5 { We make use of some tactics to break through and fully equalise }
14. Bxg4 Qh4+
{ With a complicated position. However, this has been thought to be good for Black for a number of years now. }
