[White "Saemisch Variation (main) - 3.f3 d5"]
[Black "The Saemisch: 3.f3 d5 12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ this is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... d5 { The f6-Knight usually ends up on b6 in this variation. } 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 { 6. Be3 will most likely transpose after 6... Bg7 7. Nc3 }
6... Bg7
{ Note how now our common plan in the Grunfeld of playing with ...c5 to challenge White's centre does not work as our knight is on b6 and White wins a tempo ! }
7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2
{ The main move in this variation. White keeps his options open: While it is common in these positions to castle queenside, followed by advancing the pawns on the kingside, leaving the king in the center will also be possible in some variations. So we need to pay attention as White may go wrong and not assess his options accurately. }
8... e5
{ This is my recommendation here. 8... e5 leads to very interesting position that I have found lately score slightly better than 8... Nc6 }
9. d5 c6 10. O-O-O
{ White must be careful in these lines as we can often generate a very strong initiative against the King. }
10... cxd5 11. exd5 Na6 12. h4 h5 13. Be2 Bd7 14. g4 Rc8
{ Black is clearly better. We are following Pascua, Haridas - Laylo, Darwin, Quezon City  (2014)  . }
15. gxh5 Nb4 16. Kb1 Nc4 17. Bxc4 Bf5+
{ and Black won after a few more moves. } *

