[White "Saemisch Variation (main) - 3.f3 d5"]
[Black "The Saemisch: 3.f3 d5 16"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ this is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... d5 { The f6-Knight usually ends up on b6 in this variation. } 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 { 6. Be3 will most likely transpose after 6... Bg7 7. Nc3 }
6... Bg7
{ Note how now our common plan in the Grunfeld of playing with ...c5 to challenge White's centre does not work as our knight is on b6 and White wins a tempo ! }
7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2
{ The main move in this variation. White keeps his options open: While it is common in these positions to castle queenside, followed by advancing the pawns on the kingside, leaving the king in the center will also be possible in some variations. So we need to pay attention as White may go wrong and not assess his options accurately. }
8... e5
{ This is my recommendation here. 8... e5 leads to very interesting position that I have found lately score slightly better than 8... Nc6 }
9. d5 c6 10. h4 { This position has been played in multiple high-level games. }
10... h5
{ ...cxd5 is surprisingly the main move by far. It was played in one of the included model games: Shen-So, ICC Int  (2014)  . It it was taking a look at the main move, however, I firmly believe the suggested move improves our chances significantly and scores much better for Black at this point ! }
11. Be2
{ White wants to prevent our plan, which is to take on d5 and play . ..Bf5. }
11... cxd5 12. exd5 N8d7 13. d6 Nf6 14. Bg5 Qe8
{ I really like this idea now, which leads to a complicated position. Apart from unpinning the Queen, we have two ideas in mind: 1  We can counterattack with ...e4 !; or 2  We may use the c4 outpost to generate counterplay in the queenside. 14... Re8 ?! was played in the reference game I have included between Kramnik and Shirov, WCC Cazorla  (1998)  . However, as Stohl pointed out in his excellent analysis, this logical move will give White tactical chances connected with a later d7 advance with tempo. }
15. Rd1 { This is a logical continuation to the game, which we can meet with }
15... e4
{ Generating a great counterplay straightaway is my recommendation ! This leads to a rather forced sequence in which White's best option is to get a draw. 15... Bd7 is another option, which aims at using the c4-square after ... Rc8, ...Qe6 and ...Nc4. }
16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nxe4 Be5 18. Nh3 Bf5 19. Nhf2 Rd8
{ Mobilising all our pieces to generate counterplay. The sacrificed pawn is just anecdotal. }
20. g4 hxg4 21. fxg4 Bxe4 22. Nxe4 Qa4 23. Bf3 Nc4 24. Qg5 Nxd6 25. Qxe5
{ Things could go really wrong for White if he is not accurate, as shown after }
25... Nxe4 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 27. O-O Nd2
{ Black has a decisive advantage, White cannot hold the position. } *

