[Black "The Saemisch: 3.f3 d5 19"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3
{ this is known as the Anti-Grunfeld or Saemisch variation. White's main idea is to build a strong center without allowing Nxc3. It is common knowledge that White usually thinks Black is left with too many pieces and reduced space to maneuver. White, however, commits to a slower development to achieve his main plan, and we'd better react accordingly, as we will explore. }
3... d5 { The f6-Knight usually ends up on b6 in this variation. } 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 { 6. Be3 will most likely transpose after 6... Bg7 7. Nc3 }
6... Bg7
{ Note how now our common plan in the Grunfeld of playing with ...c5 to challenge White's centre does not work as our knight is on b6 and White wins a tempo ! }
7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2
{ The main move in this variation. White keeps his options open: While it is common in these positions to castle queenside, followed by advancing the pawns on the kingside, leaving the king in the center will also be possible in some variations. So we need to pay attention as White may go wrong and not assess his options accurately. }
8... e5
{ This is my recommendation here. 8... e5 leads to very interesting position that I have found lately score slightly better than 8... Nc6 }
9. d5 c6 10. h4 { This position has been played in multiple high-level games. }
10... h5
{ ...cxd5 is surprisingly the main move by far. It was played in one of the included model games: Shen-So, ICC Int  (2014)  . It it was taking a look at the main move, however, I firmly believe the suggested move improves our chances significantly and scores much better for Black at this point ! }
11. d6
{ This is an idea recommended by Larry Kaufman in Sabotage the Grunfeld !  (2014)  . It is likely that this recommendation gives White the advantage; however, I am proposing two different options that lead to unbalanced positions for you to choose the one that draws more your attention ! }
11... Be6 12. O-O-O N8d7 13. Nh3
{ Here Kaufmann comments: 'Whites strong passer and ideas of Ng5 or g2-g4 give him the edge.' The author gives White a clear advantage. It is true that according to the engine White may have the advantage, in practice it is not a bed of roses for White and Black has enough resources to play in a game that is far to be decided yet. The positions arising from this novelty are confusing and unexplored, there is still a lot to be discovered in these lines. }
13... Nf6
{ Here our idea is to regroup our pieces and target the pawn on d6, which will be vulnerable. At the same time, with ...Nf6 we prevent a comfortable ...g4 from White as well. }
14. Kb1
{ After this difficult move to understand and to find, the engine gives White the advantage. White prepares against our plan and wants to transfer the queen to c2 in order to play Na4 and challenge our knight and, more importantly, target the c5 square, from where he could annoy our queen on d7 and play against our setup. In order to carry out this plan, he needs to defend the pawn on a2. }
14... Qd7 15. Qc2 Rfd8 16. Ng5 Nc8 17. Na4
{ Now White threatens ...Nc5, so our next move is forced } 17... b6 18. Nxe6
Qxe6 19. Qxc6 Nxd6
{ Here White probably has a slight advantage, but, as mentioned earlier, the position is complicated but interesting at the same time, with a lot to be discovered. }
