3... d5 { The f6-Knight usually ends up on b6 in this variation. } 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 { 6. Be3 will most likely transpose after 6... Bg7 7. Nc3 }
6... Bg7
{ Note how now our common plan in the Grunfeld of playing with ...c5 to challenge White's centre does not work as our knight is on b6 and White wins a tempo ! }
7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2
{ The main move in this variation. White keeps his options open: While it is common in these positions to castle queenside, followed by advancing the pawns on the kingside, leaving the king in the center will also be possible in some variations. So we need to pay attention as White may go wrong and not assess his options accurately. }
8... e5
{ This is my recommendation here. 8... e5 leads to very interesting position that I have found lately score slightly better than 8... Nc6 }
9. d5 c6 10. h4 { This position has been played in multiple high-level games. }
10... h5
{ ...cxd5 is surprisingly the main move by far. It was played in one of the included model games: Shen-So, ICC Int  (2014)  . It it was taking a look at the main move, however, I firmly believe the suggested move improves our chances significantly and scores much better for Black at this point ! }
11. g4
{ This is White's main option at this point and Ivanchuk's novelty against Akesson, back in 2004. White tries to mobilise the kingside fast as we have our army grouped around the queenside. We should pay special attention to this variation. }
11... cxd5 { The main and most principled response. } 12. exd5
{ The only move that makes sense for White. } 12... Na6
{ only tried in three games, but I think this is a good way to face this variation. }
13. Bh6
{ An interesting alternative and in my opinion more challenging than the main move. }
13... hxg4
{ 13... Bxh6 was played in Ding-Gupta, Masters Doha  (2014)  . Even though the game ended in a draw, the recommended novelty is stronger and gives us better chances. }
14. h5
{ Other moves, like O-O-O, give us no problems and we can follow up comfortably with .. .Nb4 ! }
14... Bxh6 15. Qxh6 Qf6
{ If we had another move, we would like to continue with ...Qg7 ! With a comfortable position. }
16. Bxa6 bxa6 17. hxg6 Qg7
{ The key of the variation ! We get just in time to defend the position. } 18.
Qxg7+ Kxg7 19. gxf7 Rxf7 20. fxg4 Bxg4
{ Despite the fact that we have a strange pawn structure, our active position gives us equal chances in this endgame. }
