1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4
{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. Qa4+ { A rare line that should not worry us much. } 5... Bd7 6. Qb3
Nc6 7. Qxb7 { Way too risky. } 7... Nxd4 8. O-O-O Ne6 9. Be5 Rb8 10. Qa6
{ Whites better off not opening yet another file directly against his king. }
10... d4 11. Nb5 Bh6+
{ In his analysis, Svidler recommends taking directly on ...b5, but I believe including ...Bh6 first makes White weaken his position even more, and we can take advantage of that. }
12. f4 O-O 13. Nf3 Ng4 14. g3 Bxb5 15. cxb5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Qd5
{ The key of this forced sequence. } 17. Nf3 Rxb5
{ White's position is extremely compromised. Our multiple threats, and White's several weaknesses, give us a decisive advantage after: }
18. Qa3 { The only logical move at this point. } 18... Rfb8
{ Increasing the pressure, White's position is falling apart. } 19. Rd2 Ra5 20.
e4 Qh5 { Black is clearly winning. } *

