[White "Bf4 Variations - 4.Bf4 Bg7"]
[Black "Bf4 Variations: 4.Bf4 3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4
{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. Rc1
{ An independent secondary variation which, to be honest, you are not really likely to face over the board. }
5... Nh5
{ The main move here is 5...O-O, with around 300 games and an average score of 55% for White. However, this move, in my opinion, is a clear improvement. It has been played in less than 100 games, but it shows a score of 45% in Black's favor ! }
6. Bd2
{ maybe a more logical move than Bg5. White is ready to play e3 next, defending or recapturing on c4. }
6... c5
{ releasing the indirect pressure on c7 and putting it on d4, once again the thematic pawn break in the Grunfeld. It is interesting to explore ...dxc4 !?, however, I am more comfortable playing the kind of positions that we reach after ...c5. In the other lines, White gets more than enough compensation and we need to play accurately and remember some lines. }
7. e3
{ The alternatives are clearly worse for White as any pawn capture favors Black. }
7... cxd4 8. exd4 dxc4 9. d5 { 9. Bxc4 transposes after ...O-O and d5. } 9...
O-O 10. Bxc4 Nd7 { our knights is heading to b6. } 11. Nf3 a6
{ is key to develop our queenside quickly and winning a tempo on the bishop. It is much stronger than . ..Nb6 directly, as after Bb3, the knight is misplaced and paralyzing the advance of the queenside pawns. }
12. a4 b5
{ A brilliant resource to remember not completely uncommon in the Grunfeld. We are fighting for the center, and we open new lines to take advantage of it ! Our lead in development fully justifies this move. }
13. axb5 Nb6 14. b3 axb5 15. Nxb5
{ Is the only capture that makes sense and the only one that has been played. }
15... Nxd5 { Black has no problems in this position. } *

