{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. Rc1
{ An independent secondary variation which, to be honest, you are not really likely to face over the board. }
5... Nh5
{ The main move here is 5...O-O, with around 300 games and an average score of 55% for White. However, this move, in my opinion, is a clear improvement. It has been played in less than 100 games, but it shows a score of 45% in Black's favor ! }
6. Bg5 { Is the most often played move at this point. } 6... h6
{ Asking the Bishop where he'd like to go. It also controls the g5 square, which allows us to play ...Be6 without having to worry about a potential Nf3-g5. }
7. Bd2
{ contrary to other lines in the Grunfeld, h6 is not really a weakness here. The rook on c1 prevents White from playing Qc1, which would be annoying with h6 made, as the battery would pose some questions on how we want to proceed on the kingside. }
7... dxc4
{ So, why do we play ...dxc4 now instead of ...c5 as in 6. Bd2 then ? Well, the difference is the fact that we have played h6. The structure looks a little draughty now. We will castle and play ...Be6, trying to secure the pawn that we just won, a different approach. Remember what I mentioned regarding different solutions for different move orders at the beginning of the chapter about 4. Bf4 ? Here we have a perfect example. }
8. e3 Be6 9. Nf3 c6 10. Ne4 Bd5 11. Qc2 b5 12. Nc5
{ We are following Pinter-Popovic, Thessaloniki ol.  1988  . Now I like Rowson's recommendation: }
12... Bxf3 { mangling the kingside pawns. } 13. gxf3 O-O
{ We need to castle in this position, as shown in the previous informational line. The reason is White has the nice tactical blow Ne6! Now, once we castle, we are ready to play ...Nd7 }
14. b3 Nd7 { With a complicated position. } *

