6. Bg5 { is the most played move at this point. } 6... h6
{ Asking the Bishop where he'd like to go. It also controls the g5 square, which allows us to play ...Be6 without having to worry about a potential Nf3-g5. }
7. Bh4 { is the main retreat and the one that makes more sense after Bg5. }
7... dxc4
{ Once again ! As a rule of thumb, remember that if we have included ...h6, then we will continue with ...dxc4 and the ...Be6 strategy. Feel free to explore ...c5 ! It makes more sense than in the Bd2-retreat variation positionally. However, I believe this is easier to remember and we keep consistency in our repertoire while following solid, good variations. }
8. e3 Be6 9. Be2 Nf6
{ It is a good idea to keep an open mind in the Grunfeld, in some variations we may want White to capture on h5 to gain the bishop pair advantage. However, in this concrete line the structural damage would be serious and the compensation clearly not enough. }
10. Nf3
{ 10. Bxf6 exf6 ! would lead to a complicated, highly unbalanced position. The double f-pawn will help us to attack Whites central pawns. Recapturing with bishop allows White to win some tempi on the bishops by combining knight and center pawn moves, giving him a clear initiative. }
10... c6 11. Ne5 b5 12. f4 Nd5
{ And Black had a good game in Dreev-Leko, Wijk aan Zee  (1996)  , as you can see in the following example: }
13. Qd2
{ White wants to take his knight on c3 to c5 via e4. Then he will follow up with e4 and b3, trying to break the pawn structure on the queenside and win the c6 backward pawn. }
13... Nxc3 14. bxc3
{ Reduces White's option to cause any harm on the queenside as b3 is not an option anymore, the pawn structure now has transformed in Black's favor. }
14... Bd5 { It's all about controlling the e4 pawn advance at the moment. } 15.
Qc2
{ 15. O-O is not within the demands of the position and we can play ... Nd7 !, quickly aiming at controlling the e4-square via f6. }
15... Bf6 16. Bf2 Bxg2 17. Rg1 Qd5 18. Rxg2 Qxg2 19. Bf3 Qh3 20. Bg4 Qg2
{ And here Dreev and Leko agreed to a draw. If ...Qxh2, then Ke2 ! with a very complicated position. }
