1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4
{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3 { The second most played option. } 5... O-O
{ as White chose to play Nf3 instead of e3, there is a big difference in the resulting position: 1  White can not play Ne2-c3 anymore. 2  Qf3 is not an option. 3  The bishop can go back to d2 to defend potential weaknesses on the dark squares. }
6. cxd5
{ This is not a good idea for White. It is a wrong approach to delay the development of the kingside. }
6... Nxd5 7. Nxd5 Qxd5 8. Bxc7
{ It is well known that taking on c7 is very risky for White. } 8... Nc6 9. e3
Bf5
{ There is more than enough compensation for the pawn. White is really behind in development and we can generate some quick play on the queenside, pressuring White, who will suffer until the end of the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bf4 Variations - 4.Bf4 Bg7"]
[Black "Bf4 Variations: 4.Bf4 11"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4
{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3 { The second most played option. } 5... O-O
{ as White chose to play Nf3 instead of e3, there is a big difference in the resulting position: 1  White can not play Ne2-c3 anymore. 2  Qf3 is not an option. 3  The bishop can go back to d2 to defend potential weaknesses on the dark squares. }
6. Rc1
{ 6. e3 - 6... c5 will transpose to one of the lines that we will study under the 5. e3 move order. }
6... dxc4
{ Again, an early Rc1 points out the right approach we should choose, it is again not to play ...c5. Hopefully this will help you remember the right plan ! Note how now ...Nh5-Be5 ! is annoying for our purposes. }
7. e3
{ is a sober move that does not pose many problems for our purposes. We can have a comfortable game after }
7... Be6
{ ...c5 !? is Svidler's recommendation and is also another interesting option to explore. However, I believe this fits better in our repertoire, let me explain why: It is important to remember that at this point we are choosing what to do with our bishop as we mobilise our position. However, it is even more important to understand why against 7. e4 we play ...Bg4 and why now we decide to play ..Be6. The key is the pressure that we can apply against Whites center. In this case, contrary to what happens in the e4 variation, we are not applying real, serious pressure on d4 as e3 bolsters Whites center. Therefore, we defend our c4-pawn, an idea that we have seen before. }
8. Ng5
{ This is pretty much 'forced', as any other knight move  (be it to d2 or to e5)  , allows us to play .. .c5 !, getting a very comfortable position. }
8... Bd5 { We enter a well-known theoretical sequence that is good for Black. }
9. e4 h6 10. exd5 hxg5 11. Bxg5 Nxd5 12. Bxc4 Nb6 13. Bb3 Nc6
{ We have a good game. } 14. d5
{ has been played about the same number of times as Ne2. } 14... Nd4 15. O-O
Nxb3
{ this line is a bit more drawish and could be a good option depending on your specific situation. }
16. Qxb3 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Qxd5
{ Black fully equalises and has a comfortable endgame. See Erdos-Volokitin, Bundesliga  (2014)  . }
*

