{ ...c5 !? is Svidler's recommendation and is also another interesting option to explore. However, I believe this fits better in our repertoire, let me explain why: It is important to remember that at this point we are choosing what to do with our bishop as we mobilise our position. However, it is even more important to understand why against 7. e4 we play ...Bg4 and why now we decide to play ..Be6. The key is the pressure that we can apply against White's center. In this case, contrary to what happens in the e4 variation, we are not applying real, serious pressure on d4 as e3 bolsters White's center. Therefore, we defend our c4-pawn, an idea that we have seen before. }
8. Ng5
{ This is pretty much 'forced', as any other knight move  (be it to d2 or to e5)  , allows us to play .. .c5 !, getting a very comfortable position. }
8... Bd5 { We enter a well-known theoretical sequence that is good for Black. }
9. e4 h6 10. exd5 hxg5 11. Bxg5 Nxd5 12. Bxc4 Nb6 13. Bb3 Nc6
{ We have a good game. } 14. d5
{ has been played about the same number of times as Ne2. } 14... Nd4 15. O-O
Qd7 { the main move according to theory. } 16. Re1 Rfe8 17. h4 Rad8
{ See Istratescu-Vachier-Lagrave, FRA-chT  (2014)  . The position is equal, Black slowly improves the position of his pieces, now he could follow with ...Qf5, or ...a5, trying to annoy White and make him move his pieces to a worse square. Maybe this is the reason why Istratescu decided to simplify with Ba4. }
