1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4
{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3 { The second most played option. } 5... O-O
{ as White chose to play Nf3 instead of e3, there is a big difference in the resulting position: 1  White can not play Ne2-c3 anymore. 2  Qf3 is not an option. 3  The bishop can go back to d2 to defend potential weaknesses on the dark squares. }
6. Rc1
{ 6. e3 - 6... c5 will transpose to one of the lines that we will study under the 5. e3 move order. }
6... dxc4
{ Again, an early Rc1 points out the right approach we should choose, it is again not to play ...c5. Hopefully this will help you remember the right plan ! Note how now ...Nh5-Be5 ! is annoying for our purposes. }
7. e4
{ Whites main line at this point and the most logical one, grabbing central space. }
7... Bg4
{ ...c5 !? is also possible and is the option that Svidler recommends.   However, this is the main line and the move that makes more sense to me. Our idea is to put pressure on f3 and d4. We want to take on f3 and make White recapture with pawn. If he takes with the queen, he does not defend on d4 anymore !  That's the whole point. We also enable the idea of ... Nh5 !? once again as Be5 will not be as good now with the knight pinned. }
8. Bxc4
{ The chosen option in almost every game. e5 ?! is premature, we can follow up with ...Nh5 and ...c5 !, breaking Whites center and with a great game ahead. }
8... Nh5
{ The most accurate move. We have pinned the knight and are effectively applying pressure on d4. We want to force White to recapture on f3 with the g-pawn. }
9. Be3 { White holds onto the d4 pawn and will recapture with pawn on f3. }
9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 { Whites main option is not to give away the d-pawn ! }
10... e5
{ We challenge Whites centre immediately and fix the weakness on f4 before White can play f4 himself ! }
11. dxe5
{ After 11. d5 Nf4 !, White can not achieve much due to his weakened kingside. }
11... Bxe5 12. Qxd8
{ This is White's most challenging attempt. Trading queens is the best option for White to show a potential advantage with the bishop pair in the endgame. However, we have a structural, static advantage and the f4 outpost for our knight. The position will be balanced. }
12... Rxd8
{ Our plan will be to change one of White's bishops. If we manage to do so, he will not have anything to compensate the damaged pawn structure. }
13. Ne2 { White regains some control over the dark squares and prepares f4. }
13... Nc6 14. f4
{ is not good for White, but we should know how to play this position. } 14...
Bxb2 15. Rb1 Na5 16. Bd5 c6 17. Bxf7+ Kxf7 18. Rxb2 b5
{ The game is unclear. I prefer Black's chances in the endgame. See Hopman-Schut, Tata Steel  (2012)  . }
