{ Whites main line at this point and the most logical one, grabbing central space. }
7... Bg4
{ ...c5 !? is also possible and is the option that Svidler recommends.   However, this is the main line and the move that makes more sense to me. Our idea is to put pressure on f3 and d4. We want to take on f3 and make White recapture with pawn. If he takes with the queen, he does not defend on d4 anymore !  That's the whole point. We also enable the idea of ... Nh5 !? once again as Be5 will not be as good now with the knight pinned. }
8. Bxc4
{ The chosen option in almost every game. e5 ?! is premature, we can follow up with ...Nh5 and ...c5 !, breaking Whites center and with a great game ahead. }
8... Nh5
{ The most accurate move. We have pinned the knight and are effectively applying pressure on d4. We want to force White to recapture on f3 with the g-pawn. }
9. Be3 { White holds onto the d4 pawn and will recapture with pawn on f3. }
9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 { Whites main option is not to give away the d-pawn ! }
10... e5
{ We challenge Whites centre immediately and fix the weakness on f4 before White can play f4 himself ! }
11. dxe5
{ After 11. d5 Nf4 !, White can not achieve much due to his weakened kingside. }
11... Bxe5 12. Qxd8
{ This is Whites most challenging attempt. Trading queens is the best option for White to show a potential advantage with the bishop pair in the endgame. However, we have a structural, static advantage and the f4 outpost for our knight. The position will be balanced. }
12... Rxd8
{ Our plan will be to change one of Whites bishops. If we manage to do so, he will not have anything to compensate the damaged pawn structure. }
13. O-O { White's main option at this point. } 13... Nd7
{ The main move is more flexible than ...Nc6 and scores better. } 14. Ne2
{ White's main attempt by far, trying to push with f4. } 14... Bxb2 15. Rb1 Ne5
{ The key move that allows us to equalise comfortably. We have transposed to 13. Ne2 Nc6 14. O-O Bxb2 !?. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bf4 Variations - 4.Bf4 Bg7"]
[Black "Bf4 Variations: 4.Bf4 20"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4
{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. e3
{ White's absolute main line, used far more than other alternatives. } 5... c5
6. Bxb8
{ Is not good for White. This move has not been played much but it is important to know why we get an advantage in this line. }
6... Rxb8 7. Qa4+ Bd7 8. Qxa7
{ White grabs a pawn, but this is too risky and we can easily obtain a big initiative. }
8... cxd4 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. cxd5
{ We quickly obtain a demolishing initiative after } 10... Qa5 11. Qd2
{ Prophylactically against ...Ne4 } 11... b5
{ With the threat of ...b4, winning space and creating problems to White's coordination. }
12. Bd3 b4 13. Nce2 Qxd5 14. Nf3 Rfd8 15. O-O e5
{ A great move! We gain space and control the important squares d4 and f4 so White can't use them. We also have good control over the d5 square. But the key aspect of this position is the bishop pair, which gives us a very comfortable game. }
16. e4 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Qxe4 18. Ng3 Qf4 19. Rfd1 Qxd2 20. Rxd2 Be6
{ See Donner-Gheorghiu, Amsterdam  (1969)  , in which ...Bc6 was played. However, ... Be6 is a better move ! We provoke Ng5 and we will win tempi on the kingside while restricting White's knights. Black has a decisive advantage, White can not hold the position for much longer. The bishop pair is too strong in this endgame. }
21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Ng5 Bc8
{ Note how advancing our pawns will be beneficial for us in two ways: 1  We will restrict the movement of White's knights; and 2  we will also open lines for our bishop pair. Black is clearly better here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bf4 Variations - 4.Bf4 Bg7"]
[Black "Bf4 Variations: 4.Bf4 21"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4
{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. e3
{ Whites absolute main line, used far more than other alternatives. } 5... c5
6. Nf3
{ White's secondary option, more respectable than Bxb8, but still worse than dxc5, the main line. }
6... cxd4
{ As White does not take on c5, we take on d4 and try to get an initiative. }
7. exd4
{ has also been tried in many games, but it is not as serious as the main variation. }
7... O-O 8. Be2 Nc6
{ Black has a very comfortable position in which White's dark-squared bishop does not sit comfortably on f4 and would be better on g5, as in the Taimanov lines. }
9. O-O Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 dxc4
{ the resulting complications will resolve in a better position for Black. }
12. d5 Nb4 13. d6 e6
{ The best reaction, delaying ...Nd3. In the Grunfeld, the passed d-pawn for White is a thematic feature of the positions. We should not be afraid of playing against it, but we always need to keep an eye on it. }
14. d7 { The pawn advances too much and too fast. } 14... Nd3 15. Bd6 Qxd7 16.
Bxf8 Rxf8
{ was played in Materniak-Slawinski, corr.  1999  . Black has two pawns for the exchange and a great knight on d3. The conclusion is that Black was clearly better. }
