1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4
{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. e3
{ Whites absolute main line, used far more than other alternatives. } 5... c5
6. Nf3
{ Whites secondary option, more respectable than Bxb8, but still worse than dxc5, the main line. }
