[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Bf4 Variations - 4.Bf4 Bg7"]
[Black "Bf4 Variations: 4.Bf4 29"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4
{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. e3
{ Whites absolute main line, used far more than other alternatives. } 5... c5
6. dxc5
{ The absolute main line of this variation. The alternatives are clearly worse than this. If White allows us to take on d4, we will get a very comfortable game and the initiative in many variations. }
6... Qa5 7. Qa4+
{ White's second most played option. Probably Whites best choice after the main line: 7. Rc1. }
7... Qxa4 8. Nxa4 Bd7 { The best move according to current theory. } 9. Nc3 Ne4
{ Black's whole idea is to increase the activity of his pieces by means of temporarily sacrificing a second pawn. }
10. Nxd5
{ The only move that can question Black's approach. Any other ideas are logically refuted. }
10... Na6
{ Preventing Nc7. White scores really bad in these lines  (around 35%)  . This position has been reached in many high-level games, like for example in Wang-Topalov in 2010. }
11. f3
{ The only move that makes sense in this position as our knight is strong on e4. }
11... Nexc5 12. O-O-O { Whites most logical and most attempted option. } 12...
e6 13. Nc7+ { The challenging attempt. Nc3 does not cause us any trouble. }
13... Nxc7 14. Bxc7 Rc8 15. Bd6 b5
{ Generating counterplay on the queenside, key to fully equalise and even get the advantage in some lines. }
16. e4
{ White tries to block our dark-squared bishop, but this is simply bad. } 16...
bxc4 17. e5 Ba4 18. Rd4 Bb5
{ A very powerful novelty. We will win the bishop pair temporarily to enter a favorable endgame. 18... Nd3+ has been tried before and Black got an advantageous position, but the recommendation is stronger. }
19. f4 Nb3+ 20. axb3 cxb3+ 21. Kd1 Bxf1 22. Ne2 Bxg2 23. Rg1
{ White does not have sufficient compensation for the pawns and Black is clearly better. }
*

