6. dxc5
{ The absolute main line of this variation. The alternatives are clearly worse than this. If White allows us to take on d4, we will get a very comfortable game and the initiative in many variations. }
6... Qa5 7. Rc1 { Whites absolute main line in the 4. Bf4 variation. } 7...
dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O
{ If there are some general tips that I extracted after studying 4. Bf4 in Rowson's book these would be the following:  1  Rc1 from White usually means that we should capture on c4.  2  We should not take on c5 before castling.  3  Castling and taking on c5 are priorities and should, generally, go before ...Nc6 }
9. Ne2
{ Should be taken seriously. It is White's second option and has scored slightly better than Nf3, the main line. White has some ideas in mind: 1  A common maneuver once the queen takes on c5 is Ng3-e4, threatening the queen. 2  We will have to find a role for our light-squared bishop, as it will be chased with f3 and g4/e4, or even with Ng3. 3  It can recapture on f4 after a potential ...Nh5. However, a knight on e2 has less influence on the centre and can not jump to e5, aiming at f7, one of the two vulnerable squares in our position along with c7. Something else to notice is that our dark-squared bishop will be really strong in these lines. }
9... Qxc5 10. Nb5
{ Looks very logical and human, but it is easily refuted after } 10... Qb4+ 11.
Kf1 Ne4
{ Other sources recommend ...a6, which is interesting, but I believe the following sequence gives Black the advantage. }
12. a3 Qxb2 13. Nc7
{ This is a mistake. However, it is not that easy to see the following tactical variation: }
13... Nc6 14. Nxa8 Rd8 15. Qe1 Nd2+ 16. Kg1 Nxc4 17. Rxc4 Be6 18. Rc1 Rxa8
{ Black's compensation and initiative are really clear. The a3 pawn will fall and our queenside passed pawns will prove decisive. }
*

