1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4
{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. e3
{ Whites absolute main line, used far more than other alternatives. } 5... c5
6. dxc5
{ The absolute main line of this variation. The alternatives are clearly worse than this. If White allows us to take on d4, we will get a very comfortable game and the initiative in many variations. }
6... Qa5 7. Rc1 { Whites absolute main line in the 4. Bf4 variation. } 7...
dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O
{ If there are some general tips that I extracted after studying 4. Bf4 in Rowson's book these would be the following:  1  Rc1 from White usually means that we should capture on c4.  2  We should not take on c5 before castling.  3  Castling and taking on c5 are priorities and should, generally, go before ...Nc6 }
9. Ne2
{ Should be taken seriously. It is Whites second option and has scored slightly better than Nf3, the main line. White has some ideas in mind: 1  A common maneuver once the queen takes on c5 is Ng3-e4, threatening the queen. 2  We will have to find a role for our light-squared bishop, as it will be chased with f3 and g4/e4, or even with Ng3. 3  It can recapture on f4 after a potential ...Nh5. However, a knight on e2 has less influence on the centre and can not jump to e5, aiming at f7, one of the two vulnerable squares in our position along with c7. Something else to notice is that our dark-squared bishop will be really strong in these lines. }
9... Qxc5 10. Qb3
{ the main move at this point. We have to play well in this position knowing what is the main issue for us in this position: We have to develop while keeping an eye on threats like Nd5, aiming at the most vulnerable square in our position: c7. }
10... Qa5
{ 10... Nc6 is the main move. However, this secondary option scores as well as the main line and I like the ideas behind this move. }
11. O-O Nbd7
{ Keeping flexibility. In my opinion it is better than ...Nc6 for our purposes. }
12. Rfd1 { Has been tried a couple of times more than a3 at this point. } 12...
Nc5 13. Qb5
{ White does not really have another option if he wants to keep some initiative and get any advantage. Qc2 would allow us to develop winning tempo with ...Bf5, followed by ...Rfd8 and the position will be equal. }
13... Qxb5 14. Nxb5 Be6 15. Ned4 Bxc4 16. Rxc4 Ncd7 17. Bg3 a6 18. Na3 Rac8 19.
Rdc1 Rxc4 20. Rxc4 Nd5 21. Kf1 Rd8 22. Rc1
{ We are following Kalashian-Sarenac, Wch U20  (2008)  . However, Black had a better move here than ...Kf8. }
22... N7b6
{ Black has good control of the position and is better. Note how Black will decide when to open the position for his pieces, while improving them and keeping Whites options restricted. }
