dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O
{ If there are some general tips that I extracted after studying 4. Bf4 in Rowson's book these would be the following:  1  Rc1 from White usually means that we should capture on c4.  2  We should not take on c5 before castling.  3  Castling and taking on c5 are priorities and should, generally, go before ...Nc6 }
9. Nf3 { Is the most played move from White. } 9... Qxc5 10. Bb3
{ White's main line by far. It is also the most natural move in this position. }
10... Nc6
{ 10... Qa5 and then ...Nc6 is also possible. However, White does not have any dangerous discovered attacks as we can check with Qb4 or Qa5. }
11. O-O Qa5 12. Qe2
{ In this line we can see some of the problems White has without including h3. }
12... Nh5 13. Bg5 Bg4 14. Bh4 { White's most played option at this point. }
14... g5
{ 14... Qb4 gives Black a fully equal game, as mentioned by Rowson and Avrukh. }
15. Bg3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 { White's main capture at this point. } 16... Ne5
{ We follow a similar approach to the fxg3 variation. However, I believe it is more accurate to start with ...Ne5 now before playing ...e6. The reason being the pin can not be broken with h3 ! We make White's life difficult and pose some questions. }
17. Bc2 e6 { Restricting White's minor pieces. } 18. Bb1 Rac8 19. Qc2 Bf5
{ White's queen is not pinned anymore. It is a good time to trade the bishops now, making White's rook occupy a worse square. }
20. Qe2 Bxb1 21. Rxb1 h6
{ Stabilizing the kingside. Black has a slight advantage. } *

