1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4
{ In the Bf4 variations, White can play e3, Nf3 and Rc1 in different orders, and we should not answer in the same way against them. It is important to understand the ideas in this chapter as they will help you find the right approach ! One thing that is common to all variations is that we should always keep an eye on c7. }
4... Bg7 5. e3
{ Whites absolute main line, used far more than other alternatives. } 5... c5
6. dxc5
{ The absolute main line of this variation. The alternatives are clearly worse than this. If White allows us to take on d4, we will get a very comfortable game and the initiative in many variations. }
6... Qa5 7. Rc1 { Whites absolute main line in the 4. Bf4 variation. } 7...
dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O
{ If there are some general tips that I extracted after studying 4. Bf4 in Rowson's book these would be the following:  1  Rc1 from White usually means that we should capture on c4.  2  We should not take on c5 before castling.  3  Castling and taking on c5 are priorities and should, generally, go before ...Nc6 }
9. Nf3 { Is the most played move from White. } 9... Qxc5 10. Bb3
{ Whites main line by far. It is also the most natural move in this position. }
10... Nc6
{ 10... Qa5 and then ...Nc6 is also possible. However, White does not have any dangerous discovered attacks as we can check with Qb4 or Qa5. }
11. O-O Qa5 12. h3
{ The main line by far. It prevents ...Bg4 and gives a escape to the dark-squared bishop. }
12... Bf5 { The main line and a logical developing move. } 13. Qe2
{ Whites absolute main option, preparing to battle but only after calling in his last soldiers ! }
13... Ne4
{ After the last two moves, we can see that Blacks position look harmonious and coordinated. White has to play accurately to avoid falling in a worse position already ! Also, note how with this knight exchange, we will open the diagonal for our bishop. }
14. Nd5 { The main option by a decent number of games. } 14... e5
{ Our two bishops are restricted at the moment, but it will be up to us when to free them again ! }
15. Rxc6
{ An aggressive approach. A move revealed by Karpov in his 11th game of the third Wch match against Kasparov in London/Leningrad, 1986. }
15... bxc6
{ It is best to take the rook before it causes more damage ! Kasparov preferred .. .exf4, and despite the fact that the game ended in a draw, modern theory shows that White has good chances to get the advantage. }
16. Ne7+ Kh8 17. Nxe5 { Whites idea to transpose is wrong due to } 17... Bxe5
18. Nxc6 Qd2 19. Qxd2
{ 19. Bxe5+ f6 ! transposes to the main line in this variation. } 19... Nxd2
20. Bxe5+ f6 21. Bc3 Nxf1
{ Black is completely winning. See Sokolov-Shirov, Wijk aan Zee  (1999)  . } *

