4... Bg7 5. e3
{ Whites absolute main line, used far more than other alternatives. } 5... c5
6. dxc5
{ The absolute main line of this variation. The alternatives are clearly worse than this. If White allows us to take on d4, we will get a very comfortable game and the initiative in many variations. }
6... Qa5 7. Rc1 { Whites absolute main line in the 4. Bf4 variation. } 7...
dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O
{ If there are some general tips that I extracted after studying 4. Bf4 in Rowson's book these would be the following:  1  Rc1 from White usually means that we should capture on c4.  2  We should not take on c5 before castling.  3  Castling and taking on c5 are priorities and should, generally, go before ...Nc6 }
9. Nf3 { Is the most played move from White. } 9... Qxc5 10. Bb3
{ Whites main line by far. It is also the most natural move in this position. }
10... Nc6
{ 10... Qa5 and then ...Nc6 is also possible. However, White does not have any dangerous discovered attacks as we can check with Qb4 or Qa5. }
11. O-O Qa5 12. h3
{ The main line by far. It prevents ...Bg4 and gives a escape to the dark-squared bishop. }
12... Bf5 { The main line and a logical developing move. } 13. Qe2
{ Whites absolute main option, preparing to battle but only after calling in his last soldiers ! }
13... Ne4
{ After the last two moves, we can see that Blacks position look harmonious and coordinated. White has to play accurately to avoid falling in a worse position already ! Also, note how with this knight exchange, we will open the diagonal for our bishop. }
14. Nd5 { The main option by a decent number of games. } 14... e5
{ Our two bishops are restricted at the moment, but it will be up to us when to free them again ! }
15. Rxc6
{ An aggressive approach. A move revealed by Karpov in his 11th game of the third Wch match against Kasparov in London/Leningrad, 1986. }
15... bxc6
{ It is best to take the rook before it causes more damage ! Kasparov preferred .. .exf4, and despite the fact that the game ended in a draw, modern theory shows that White has good chances to get the advantage. }
16. Ne7+ Kh8 17. Nxc6 Qb6 18. Ncxe5 { 18. Nfxe5 ? loses material to f6 ! }
18... Be6
{ Now I really like how Rowson considers it is critical to evaluate this position properly. In general, he considers Black to have an unclear advantage, but I would be humbler here and highlight an unclear position. It is true that his book was published many years ago and the theory in the Grunfeld has evolved.  However, I believe he had some reasons back then to believe that, but I would probably rephrase that to an unclear position with a favourable trend for Black:  1  With pawns on both sides of the board, the rooks can target them and swap from one side to the other quickly. 2  The queenside pawns can be targeted without much difficulty it seems.  3  Our biggest winning strategy would be to have an endgame with 3 pawns and the Rook against 4 pawns and the bishop.  However, White has a great compensation with some active minor pieces and a big presence on the kingside, where our King is only guarded by 3 pawns. Rowson also pointed out that with an extra pawn on e7 for Black, the advantage would be clear. }
19. Bxe6 Qxe6 20. Qc2
{ Whites main and practically only attempt to fight for the advantage. } 20...
f5 { Modern analysis has shown that ... f5 ! is stronger than ...Nf6. } 21. Qa4
{ White defends on a2. } 21... g5
{ The complications seem to favor Black and this is the preferred move. } 22.
Bh2
{ This position has been reached in around 15 good-level games. Black has tried mainly ...g4, as in Riasantzev-Eljanov, Biel  (2004)  , and ... Qe8. However, here I would like to propose the strong }
22... Rad8
{ A great novelty. Blacks idea is to play ...Rd5 if White allows so, countering Whites initiative. }
23. Nd4 Qe8 24. Qxe8 Rdxe8 25. Nec6 f4
{ A great move. Holding Whites initiative while we get to improve our position to get some serious counterplay. }
26. exf4 gxf4
{ Black is better in this position. The advantage is almost clear despite the fact that White has two pawns for the exchange. Our position is more active and our plan is clearer. }
