[White "Qa4+ Variation - 4.Qa4+ Bd7"]
[Black "Qa4+ Variation: 4.Qa4+ 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qa4+
{ This move often transposes to the line starting with Qb3. Indeed with Qa4+, White's idea is to enter the Russian System  (with Qb3)  , but first he disrupts Black's development. The reason why this is a separate chapter from Qb3 is the fact that I am proposing an approach that has not been played much yet, but that I believe is quite interesting and sound. }
4... Bd7 { We win a tempo in exchange though. } 5. Qb3 Nc6
{ This is the approach I would like to recommend against an early Qa4. ...Nc6 is an interesting move that exploits the fact that the White's king knight is still on g1. We attack the center and at the same time pose a threat with ...Na5. }
6. cxd5 { is clearly worse than other alternatives. } 6... Nxd4 7. Qd1 Nb5
{ We exploit our better development to get a slight, comfortable advantage. }
8. Bd2 Nxc3 9. Bxc3 c6 10. e4 Bg7 11. dxc6 Bxc6 12. Bd3 O-O 13. Qe2 Nh5 14. Bd2
Bxb2 15. Rb1 Bc3 { See Kan,I-Dubinin,P/Leningrad 1947/URS-ch  (48)  . } *

