1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qa4+
{ This move often transposes to the line starting with Qb3. Indeed with Qa4+, White's idea is to enter the Russian System  (with Qb3)  , but first he disrupts Black's development. The reason why this is a separate chapter from Qb3 is the fact that I am proposing an approach that has not been played much yet, but that I believe is quite interesting and sound. }
4... Bd7 { We win a tempo in exchange though. } 5. Qb3 Nc6
{ This is the approach I would like to recommend against an early Qa4. ...Nc6 is an interesting move that explots the fact that the White's king knight is still on g1. We attack the center and at the same time pose a threat with ...Na5. }
6. Nf3
{ Moves like e3 instead of Nf3 allow us to play ...Na5, targeting c4 and winning another tempo on the queen. White can not really afford to fall behind in development even more, that would give us a very comfortable position. }
6... Na5 7. Qb4 Nxc4 8. Qxb7
{ is not good for White. It leads to a somewhat forced variation where we will have a great advantage. }
8... Rb8 9. Qa6 Rb6
{ This is the idea, we will have a huge lead in development and pose problems to White's king. }
10. Qxa7 Qc8 11. e3
{ White's Queen is trapped, and this shows why 11. Bf4 is the only 'good' option for White. }
11... Ra6 12. Qc5 e5 13. Bxc4 Bxc5 14. Bxa6 Qxa6 15. dxc5 O-O *

