[White "Qa4+ Variation - 4.Qa4+ Bd7"]
[Black "Qa4+ Variation: 4.Qa4+ 6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qa4+
{ This move often transposes to the line starting with Qb3. Indeed with Qa4+, White's idea is to enter the Russian System  (with Qb3)  , but first he disrupts Black's development. The reason why this is a separate chapter from Qb3 is the fact that I am proposing an approach that has not been played much yet, but that I believe is quite interesting and sound. }
4... Bd7 { We win a tempo in exchange though. } 5. Qb3 Nc6
{ This is the approach I would like to recommend against an early Qa4...Nc6 is an interesting move that explots the fact that the White's king knight is still on g1. We attack the center and at the same time pose a threat with ...Na5. }
6. Nf3
{ Moves like e3 instead of Nf3 allow us to play ...Na5, targeting c4 and winning another tempo on the queen. White can not really afford to fall behind in development even more, that would give us a very comfortable position. }
6... Na5 7. Qb4 Nxc4 8. Nxd5
{ The only move that makes sense for White at this point. } 8... Nd6
{ This is a novelty. ...Nxd5 was played in Dolezal, J-Filip,M/Prague 1954/MCD  (46)  , but I believe ...Nd6 is a stronger move. }
9. Nc3 a5
{ We keep winning tempi and space on the queenside due to the White queen's compromised position. }
10. Qb3 a4 11. Qc2 Bf5 12. Qd1 c5
{ A great move. We will control the e4 square, forcing White to play with e3, weakening the d3 square, which will be the base of our plans to keep White's position tied down. }
13. dxc5 Nde4 14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 15. Nxa4 Ng4
{ White's position is really compromised. } 16. e3 Ngxf2
{ White's lack of development and odd pawn structure, apart from the coordination of his pieces, should reassure you. }
17. Bb5+ Bd7 18. Bxd7+ Rxd7 19. Rf1 Nd3+ 20. Ke2 Bg7
{ Black has more than sufficient compensation. White has a few problems to solve. }
*

