1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qa4+
{ This move often transposes to the line starting with Qb3. Indeed with Qa4+, White's idea is to enter the Russian System  (with Qb3)  , but first he disrupts Black's development. The reason why this is a separate chapter from Qb3 is the fact that I am proposing an approach that has not been played much yet, but that I believe is quite interesting and sound. }
4... Bd7 { We win a tempo in exchange though. } 5. Qb3 Nc6
{ This is the approach I would like to recommend against an early Qa4...Nc6 is an interesting move that explots the fact that the White's king knight is still on g1. We attack the center and at the same time pose a threat with ...Na5. }
6. Nf3
{ Moves like e3 instead of Nf3 allow us to play ...Na5, targeting c4 and winning another tempo on the queen. White can not really afford to fall behind in development even more, that would give us a very comfortable position. }
6... Na5 7. Qc2 { White's best and most challenging move. } 7... c6
{ A novelty. Until now, ... dxc4 has been the move that has been tried but White gets a slight advantage with accurate play. }
8. cxd5 cxd5
{ Our plan is simple: we keep developing while keeping an eye on the e4-square and pinning the knight on c3 with our rook. }
9. e3
{ White will have a problem developing and finding a role for his dark-square bishop, so we get a comfortable advantage in these lines. }
9... Rc8 10. Bd3 Bg7 11. h3 O-O 12. O-O Re8 13. Qd1 Bf5
{ An interesting idea. We exchange White's best minor piece to the detriment of our pawn structure. However, we get more control of key squares and prevent pawn breaks from White to break through the center and give him some space and a better role for his dark-squared bishop. }
14. Bxf5 gxf5
{ The position is unclear. Even though our pawn structure looks strange on the kingside, we prevent counterplay from White and the g7-bishop can become quite strong if White opens files to try to force some kind of play on the kingside. }
*

