6... c6 7. Qb3 { The second most played option. } 7... dxc4
{ We will counterattack on the queenside by winning tempo on the light-squared bishop. }
8. Bxc4 b5 9. Be2 a5
{ It makes perfect sense to start with this move. ...Be6 was played in Kohlweyer-Epishin, Frankfurt  (1990)  . It is an alternative which I believe can be postponed and could indeed benefit us if White plays Ba3 ? }
10. O-O
{ Of course not 10. Ba3 ? due to ...Be6 11. Qb2 c5 ! With a clear advantage for Black. }
10... Be6 11. Qb2 axb4 12. Qxb4 Qd6
{ Trading queens will be clearly in our favor due to our advantage on the queenside and better roles and squares for our pieces. The pawn structure transformation is key and something to pay attention in these variations of the Grunfeld. }
13. Qxd6 exd6 14. a3 Nbd7 15. Ng5 Bf5 16. Bd2
{ After Ng5, 16. e4 seems to be the logical continuation. However, we have a strong reply with 16...b4! And after White takes the bishop on f5 and we take the knight on c3, we will have two advantages: 1- A strong pawn on c3; and 2- White's d4-pawn will be weak. We are indeed happy to provoke e4 from White! }
16... Rfe8 17. Rfc1 Nb6
{ Now that we have improved our pieces, it is clear that White is struggling to find a plan, it seems like any pawn move would commit his position and activate some key diagonal or enable an outpost for our pieces. Black is clearly better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Closed Grunfeld - 4.e3 Bg7"]
[Black "The Closed Grunfeld: 4.e3 Bg7 3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ A quiet move leading to a closed kind of game in which White can decide among different follow-ups on the following move. }
4... Bg7 5. b4
{ White's idea is to take the game to a positional ground where he will try to show the advantage by playing on the queenside. }
5... O-O 6. Nf3
{ Other moves from White  (for instance Bb2 or Qb3)  will end up transposing to variations we will cover soon after White plays Nf3. }
6... c6 7. Bb2
{ Whites most tried option at this point, making total sense of the b4 move. }
7... Be6 8. Ng5
{ may look like an active option, questioning the position of our light-squared bishop. Nothing further from the truth, as our bishop was never meant to be on e6, but on... }
8... Bf5 9. h3 h6 { And the knight will have to retreat. } 10. Nf3 Nbd7 11. c5
{ was played in Kveinys-Bartel, Bundesliga  (2008)  , but this allows us to counterattack on the center with a recurrent idea in the Grunfeld. }
11... e5
{ A very strong novelty. ...a5 !? was played by Bartel in the mentioned game, but the recommended idea is simply better. As White commits his pawn chain, we counterattack with ...e5 ! We have a clear plan and a good initiative on the kingside. We will play ...e4, recycle the knight via h7-g5, prepare ...f5 with ...Be6. Also we will slow down White's option on the queenside with ...a6 and place our queen on b8. Something important to keep in mind is that this position requires positional understanding and good play taking into account the opponent's plans. However, our play is faster and more dangerous on the kingside than White's on the queenside. Black is better. }
*

