[Black "The Closed Grunfeld: 4.e3 Bg7 4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ A quiet move leading to a closed kind of game in which White can decide among different follow-ups in the following move. }
4... Bg7 5. b4
{ White's idea is to take the game to a positional ground where he will try to show the advantage by playing on the queenside. }
5... O-O 6. Nf3
{ Other moves from White  (for instance Bb2 or Qb3)  will end up transposing to variations we will cover soon after White plays Nf3. }
6... c6 7. Bb2
{ Whites most tried option at this point, making total sense of the b4 move. }
7... Be6 8. c5 { This gives us a straight plan involving ...e5 ! } 8... Nbd7
{ The knight on d7 will support our pawn break   e5  . } 9. h3
{ this is necessary, otherwise ...Bg4, ...Re8 and ...e5 makes our life really easy. }
9... Re8
{ An interesting novelty. Our idea is to play ...Bf5 and ...e5 ! We force White to play Bd3 to stop our idea, which will generate another interesting plan ! }
10. Bd3 Bf5 11. Bxf5 gxf5
{ Opening the g-file is good for us in this case. The f-pawn is not really weak as it bolsters the e4-outpost, which is indeed very nice for a knight. }
12. O-O e6 13. Qc2 Ne4 14. a4 Kh8
{ The position is complex and unbalanced, but I believe Black keeps an edge thanks to the initiative on the kingside. }
