[Black "The Closed Grunfeld: 4.e3 Bg7 5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ A quiet move leading to a closed kind of game in which White can decide among different follow-ups in the following move. }
4... Bg7 5. cxd5
{ Has been increasingly played lately, but to be honest this line is unlikely to cause us many problems. }
5... Nxd5 6. Bc4 { makes it even easier for us. } 6... Nb6 7. Bb3 O-O
{ 7... c5 is similar and will most likely transpose. } 8. Nge2
{ Not very ambitious, we do not have any problems fully equalising  (and probably even getting a slight edge)  in this variation. 8. Nf3 will transpose to one of the variations that will be studied in 5. Nf3. }
8... c5 9. dxc5 N6d7 { The c5 pawn will fall. } 10. Ne4 Na6 11. Qc2 Nb4 12. Qd2
Qa5 13. O-O Nxc5 14. Nxc5 Rd8
{ A novelty and a strong in-between move which leaves Whites position really compromised. 14... Dxc5 was played in Sinprayoon-Ogaard, Haifa  (1976)  . I have included the game as a reference. }
15. Nd4 Qxc5 16. Qe2 Nc6 17. Re1 Bxd4 18. exd4 Nxd4 19. Qe4 Be6
{ Whites best option will be to take on b7, regaining the pawn, but leaving Black with a great initiative and activity. Black is clearly better. }
