1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ A quiet move leading to a closed kind of game in which White can decide among different follow-ups in the following move. }
4... Bg7 5. cxd5
{ Has been increasingly played lately, but to be honest this line is unlikely to cause us many problems. }
5... Nxd5 6. Nxd5 { White's main response. } 6... Qxd5 7. Ne2
{ The absolute main line in this variation. White wants to gain a tempo with Nc3. }
7... O-O 8. Nc3 Qd6
{ A very solid option that has been played by super GMs like Caruana or Li. The other main option is ...Qd8...Qd7 followed by ...b6 is another interesting option which I was seriously considering, but I finally decided to opt for ...Qd6. }
9. Be2 c6 10. O-O Nd7 { Black will not have any problems after ...e5. } 11. Qc2
{ A natural option. White releases the d1 square for the rook. } 11... e5 12.
dxe5 Qxe5 13. e4 Nf6 14. Be3 Ng4 15. Bxg4 Bxg4 16. h3 Bc8
{ A novelty and the strongest move. The position of the bishop is key in this line ! Check the informational line   16...Bd7  for more information.  Note how 16...Be6 directly would leave our queen exposed and White can react with a quick sequence starting with f4! Gaining space, and then either continuing with f5 or, most likely e5, gaining the d6 square for the bishop, that would give White a very comfortable advantage. }
17. Rad1 Qe7 18. Qd2
{ now, contrary to the line after 16... Bd7, if White plays 18. Bf4 with the idea of playing Bd6, ...Rd8 ! prevents that plan thanks to the fact that the bishop is on c8 and not on d7. Such an important detail ! }
18... Be6 19. Bf4 Rfe8 { The position is about equal. } *

