[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Closed Grunfeld - 4.e3 Bg7"]
[Black "The Closed Grunfeld: 4.e3 Bg7 9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ A quiet move leading to a closed kind of game in which White can decide among different follow-ups in the following move. }
4... Bg7 5. Qb3
{ By far White's second option, with more than 750 games where this move has been played. }
5... e6
{ Our choice and the best move, which happens to achieve the best score for Black  (around 49%)  . It is better to keep flexibility with the c-pawn as we may want to play ...c5 at some point later in the game. }
6. Qa3
{ This is the whole point behind Qb3. White tries to prevent Black from castling. Fortunately, we have a concrete idea in this line. }
6... a5
{ We will drive our knight to b4, where it will block the a3-f8 diagonal, allowing us to castle. }
7. Nf3 c6
{ A very important in-between move that has been played in a number of games. Black defends the a5 pawn and prevents Whites maneuver Qa4+ and Qb3, followed by a3, driving our future knight on b4 away and leading to unnecessary complications. }
8. cxd5
{ The capture cxd5 from White does not change our plan of blocking the diagonal and castling. }
8... exd5 9. Bd3 Na6
{ Black is completely fine. Many times, this line leads to a position where White has hanging pawns on e3 and d4, but remember that we can control them efficiently. }
