1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ A quiet move leading to a closed kind of game in which White can decide among different follow-ups in the following move. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ The absolute main line, which leads to a flexible system for both sides. }
5... O-O 6. Bd2
{ A flexible move that has become popular recently. This move has been used by elite GMs such as Mamedyarov, Anand, Ivanchuk... }
6... c5
{ Other moves are possible, but this is a straightforward and known way of striking the center in the Grunfeld that we should always consider. }
7. dxc5 { By far Whites main option. } 7... Na6 8. cxd5 Nxc5 9. Bc4 a6 10. a4
{ White prevents ...b5, which is our immediate threat. } 10... Bf5 11. O-O Rc8
12. Qe2 Nfe4 13. Rfd1
{ other moves do not worry us as we get a comfortable position. } 13... Nxc3
14. Bxc3 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Ne4 16. Rd4 Qa5 17. Qb2 Qxc3 18. Qxc3 Nxc3
{ Black has a comfortable endgame, as you can see in Ogaard-Barle, World U20  (1971)  . }
