1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ A quiet move leading to a closed kind of game in which White can decide among different follow-ups in the following move. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ The absolute main line, which leads to a flexible system for both sides. }
5... O-O 6. Bd3
{ has been played in many games. It is a logical move that does not give Black many problems to reach a comfortable position. }
6... c5 7. O-O
{ Solving the tension in the center with a pawn capture does not help White in any way, as we have seen in other lines. This is a most challenging approach. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 { We can easily grab space in the center. } 8... e5 9. Nb3 e4
10. Be2 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Qc7 12. Be2 Nc6 13. Nb5 Qe5
{ ...Qb8 was played in T. Fischer-Steinmacher, Baunatal  (1996)  . With this recommendation, the queen plays a more active role than on b8. }
14. Qd6
{ White is better off trading to relieve some the pressure and the lack of space. }
14... Qxd6 15. Nxd6 Rd8 16. Rd1 b6 17. Nxc8 Rxd1+ 18. Bxd1 Rxc8
{ Black has the advantage in this position. The position is better coordinated for us and we have a great outpost on d3. }
