1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ A quiet move leading to a closed kind of game in which White can decide among different follow-ups in the following move. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ The absolute main line, which leads to a flexible system for both sides. }
5... O-O 6. Be2
{ The most played option by far. It was made popular by Mamedyarov in 2012, where he used this line in multiple games with positive results. }
6... c5 { The most direct answer. } 7. dxc5 Qa5
{ You may want to keep queens on the board depending on the specific situation of your game! This is a perfectly valid option, as I would like to show you in the following example line: }
8. O-O
{ White's main option. You could also take a look at 8.cxd5 if you decide to play the lines with 7...Qa5. }
8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Qxc5 10. Qd4
{ White wants to exchange queens and develop normally. We could exchange and the position would be about equal. However, I recommend this approach: }
10... Qh5 { We are looking for a better exchange for our purposes! } 11. Qe5
Qxe5 12. Nxe5
{ Note the difference between exchanging on e5 and d4. Now we will win a tempo on the knight to maneuver with our knight on f6 and recycle it to d6 via e8. }
12... Ne8 13. Nf3 Nd6 14. Bb3 Nc6
{ Black does not have any problems in this position and I would say White needs to be careful. Note how it is not trivial for White to develop and coordinate his position. }
