1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ A quiet move leading to a closed kind of game in which White can decide among different follow-ups in the following move. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ The absolute main line, which leads to a flexible system for both sides. }
5... O-O 6. Be2
{ The most played option by far. It was made popular by Mamedyarov in 2012, where he used this line in multiple games with positive results. }
6... c5 { The most direct answer. } 7. O-O
{ The absolute main line in this variation. } 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ has been tried in a number of games as well. It will be enough for our purposes to see the general plan we should follow in this secondary variation. }
8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6
{ We threaten ...b5, giving us a very comfortable position. } 10. a4
{ Whites best move. } 10... Qc7 { Now we threaten the common ...e5. } 11. Qe2
e5 12. Nc2 e4
{ We grab more space and create more chances. The pawn on e4 is really annoying for White. }
13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Re8 15. Nd4 Nd7
{ Our knight embarks on a long, but pleasant journey! } 16. Qc4
{ Whites best and most active way to stop our straightforward plan. } 16...
Qxc4 17. Bxc4 Ne5
{ A very interesting novelty. ...Nb6 was played in Golombek-Smyslov, Bucharest  (1953)  . Smyslov ended up winning the game, but White could have done better to hold the position. }
18. Bd5 Nd3 19. h3 Bxd4
{ The resulting pawn structure favors Black in the endgame. } 20. exd4 Nb4 21.
Bb3 Be6 22. Bd2 Bxb3 23. Bxb4
{ Black has the better chances and a nice plan. The idea is to bring the King to d5 after playing ...f5 and challenge White on the c-file. We have a slight edge in the endgame. }
