{ We could apply a well-known saying in this case. 'To take is a mistake', referring to the capture on f3, which is not as good as ...Rc8 ! }
15. Bd5 Bxd5 16. Bxd4 e5 17. Be3 Bc4 18. Qxd8 Rfxd8 19. Rfd1 f5
{ Black has the advantage. See Adly-Ponomariov, Khanty-Mansiysk,  (2005)  . } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Closed Grunfeld - 4.e3 Bg7"]
[Black "The Closed Grunfeld: 4.e3 Bg7 36"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. e3
{ A quiet move leading to a closed kind of game in which White can decide among different follow-ups in the following move. }
4... Bg7 5. Nf3
{ The absolute main line, which leads to a flexible system for both sides. }
5... O-O 6. Be2
{ The most played option by far. It was made popular by Mamedyarov in 2012, where he used this line in multiple games with positive results. }
6... c5 { The most direct answer. } 7. O-O
{ The absolute main line in this variation. } 7... cxd4 8. exd4
{ White's most often played capture. } 8... Nc6
{ Blacks main response and the most logical one, generating more pressure on Whites center and developing. }
9. h3
{ Whites main option, which has been played in around 700 games. The idea is to avoid ...Bg4, a thematic move in the Grunfeld when generating pressure on d4. From here, Black has tried around 5 successful ideas, which highlights White's passive setup. }
9... Be6
{ This is a my recommendation. It is indeed a good way to proceed that fits well in our repertoire. I was extremely tempted to choose ...b6 !? over this move, especially after White decides to play h3. However, for the purpose of our repertoire and to have a more standard way of facing these lines, I decided to recommend ...Be6 !?, which is as good as ...b6 or even the main line   ...dxc4  . Let's explore our ideas. }
10. c5
{ Whites main move. White solves the central tension by leaving our bishop 'blocked' on e6. }
10... Ne4 11. Bf4
{ This variation allows a very nice idea from Black of a different nature. }
11... h6
{ An interesting move. With ...g5, we will win space and White may have some problems in coordinating his position if we take him out of his known lines. }
12. Qa4
{ A logical alternative, used a couple of times less than Bb5, the main move. }
12... g5 13. Bh2 { after Be3, ...f5 ! Will give us a very good position. }
13... Qc8
{ An interesting novelty. Our idea is to play ...f5 and ...g4, generating some pressure and counterplay on the kingside. }
14. Bb5 { White counterattacks on the queenside. } 14... f5
{ A complicated and interesting position with lots of play and questions to solve for both sides. }
*

