[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Russian System"]
[Black "The Russian System: 4.Nf3 Bg7 - 5.Qb3 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qb3
{ White employs a tricky move order which most likely will end up in the main variation of the Russian System after Nf3 is played. Sometimes White delays the development of the king's knight, but we should not be distracted and confused into another line. }
4... dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bg7 6. e4 { 6. Nf3 O-O transposes to the main line. } 6...
O-O 7. Be2 { 7. Nf3 Nc6 transposes to the main line once again. } 7... Nc6 8.
Be3
{ After 8. Nf3 we are, once again, in the main line, which will be covered under the main move order: 4. Nf3 Bg7, 5. Qb3. Be3 is an independent, secondary line. This idea is not White's best option. We can get a comfortable game after }
8... e5 { Black gets great counterplay. } 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Qa4 Bd7
{ See Shabalov-Mikhalevski, World op, Philadelphia  (2009)  , where ... Bg4 was played. However, I believe this idea is much stronger. We will make it difficult for White to coordinate his position in the following sequence. }
11. Qc2 Re8 12. Nf3 Neg4 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 g5 15. Bg3 Nh5 16. Rd1 Nxg3 17.
hxg3 Qe7
{ Black does not have any problems in this position. In fact, there is a noticeable slight advantage. White's pawn structure is compromised, our pieces are well-placed and we have the bishop pair. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Russian System"]
[Black "The Russian System: 4.Nf3 Bg7 - 5.Qa4+ 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qa4+
{ With this check White wants to disrupt our natural development. Ivan Sokolov has played this line in several games against the Grunfeld guru Peter Svidler. }
5... Bd7 { But we also gain a tempo here ! } 6. Qb3
{ 6... Nc6 loses a pawn for nothing in this position. Do not confuse the idea here: There is a huge difference between 4. Qa4+ and 5. Qa4+ as the d4 pawn is now defended by the developed knight on f3. }
6... dxc4 7. Qxb7 { This is not a good idea for White in this line due to }
7... Nc6
{ The threat ...Rb8 followed by ...Nb4 is too strong for White to handle. } 8.
Bf4 Rb8 9. Qxc7 Qxc7 10. Bxc7 Rxb2
{ And Black was clearly better in Trmal-Hollis, Leningrad  (1960)  . } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Russian System"]
[Black "The Russian System: 4.Nf3 Bg7 - 5.Qa4+ 3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qa4+
{ With this check White wants to disrupt our natural development. Ivan Sokolov has played this line in several games against the Grunfeld guru Peter Svidler. }
5... Bd7 { But we also gain a tempo here ! } 6. Qb3
{ 6... Nc6 loses a pawn for nothing in this position. Do not confuse the idea here: There is a huge difference between 4. Qa4+ and 5. Qa4+ as the d4 pawn is now defended by the developed knight on f3. }
6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 { The best and most logical response from White. } 7... O-O
8. e4
{ This used to be the main line a few years ago, but it has been relegated to the main alternative at White's disposal. And this is not a surprise, as Svidler highlights as well: 'this is worse than in the normal Qb3 lines, as Black has the very important additional option of...' }
8... b5
{ There has been a lot of analysis in these lines and this is currently known as the clearest way to equalize for Black. }
9. Qb3
{ White may refrain from taking on b5. This is the other option that has been played at this point. }
9... c5 10. dxc5 Na6
{ This gives us great counterplay for the pawn. White also needs to be accurate in these lines as he can end up in danger if he does not tread carefully. }
11. Be3
{ The following line is an example of how badly things can turn out for White after }
11... Ng4 12. Bf4 Nxc5 13. Qc2 Rc8
{ Black is clearly much better in this position. See Jezidzic-Rogulj, Hum na Sutly  (2012)  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Russian System"]
[Black "The Russian System: 4.Nf3 Bg7 - 5.Qa4+ 4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qa4+
{ With this check White wants to disrupt our natural development. Ivan Sokolov has played this line in several games against the Grunfeld guru Peter Svidler. }
5... Bd7 { But we also gain a tempo here ! } 6. Qb3
{ 6... Nc6 loses a pawn for nothing in this position. Do not confuse the idea here: There is a huge difference between 4. Qa4+ and 5. Qa4+ as the d4 pawn is now defended by the developed knight on f3. }
6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 { The best and most logical response from White. } 7... O-O
8. e4
{ This used to be the main line a few years ago, but it has been relegated to the main alternative at White's disposal. And this is not a surprise, as Svidler highlights as well: 'this is worse than in the normal Qb3 lines, as Black has the very important additional option of...' }
8... b5
{ There has been a lot of analysis in these lines and this is currently known as the clearest way to equalize for Black. }
9. Qb3
{ White may refrain from taking on b5. This is the other option that has been played at this point. }
9... c5 10. dxc5 Na6
{ This gives us great counterplay for the pawn. White also needs to be accurate in these lines as he can end up in danger if he does not tread carefully. }
11. e5 Ng4 12. Bxb5
{ This is White's best option. He should focus on completing development, otherwise we do not have any problems. }
12... Nxc5 13. Qc4 Bxb5 14. Qxc5 Ba6
{ Black has the advantage in this position. The bishop pair is really powerful and we also get an initiative. White has some serious coordination problems. See Lubczynski-Schmidt, Poznan op.  2004  . }
*

