[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qa4+
{ With this check White wants to disrupt our natural development. Ivan Sokolov has played this line in several games against the Grunfeld guru Peter Svidler. }
5... Bd7 { But we also gain a tempo here ! } 6. Qb3
{ 6... Nc6 loses a pawn for nothing in this position. Do not confuse the idea here: There is a huge difference between 4. Qa4+ and 5. Qa4+ as the d4 pawn is now defended by the developed knight on f3. }
6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 { The best and most logical response from White. } 7... O-O
8. e4
{ This used to be the main line a few years ago, but it has been relegated to the main alternative at White's disposal. And this is not a surprise, as Svidler highlights as well: 'this is worse than in the normal Qb3 lines, as Black has the very important additional option of...' }
8... b5
{ There has been a lot of analysis in these lines and this is currently known as the clearest way to equalize for Black. }
9. Nxb5 { This is the main line } 9... Nxe4 10. Qxc7
{ This is the main and most logical reply. } 10... Nc6 11. Bd3
{ White's main option. } 11... Nb4
{ The old line is my recommendation in this position. This is considered to be absolutely fine for Black, as Svidler points out. }
12. Bxe4 { What follows is a well-known, forced line. } 12... Bxb5 13. Qxd8
Raxd8 14. Bd2 f5
{ There are some debates going on about this move, which is considered dubious by theory. But here I agree with Avrukh, who proposes this move as a good one. }
15. Bb1
{ I want to show you what happens if White does not take on f5. This is something I have not seen covered in other books I have checked. }
15... Nc6 { Now we target the pawn on d4 after gaining space with ...f5. } 16.
a4 Ba6 17. Ba2+ Kh8 18. Bc3 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Bxd4 20. O-O-O Bxc3 21. bxc3 e5
{ Black is slightly better in this same-colored bishop and rooks endgame. The key is the pawn structure on both sides. White could potentially hold the endgame, but he is going to have to play very accurately. }
*

