{ This is my recommendation. We ignore the hanging pawn on c7, but we will get something in return: A lead in development, the pawn on d4 will become a target and we will also have some dangerous threats with ...Nc6-b4. }
9. Qxc7 Nc6 10. e3 { This is White's main line and the best-scoring move. }
10... Nb4 { We force White to take a decision now. } 11. Qxd8
{ As we are threatening ...Nbd5 in this position, it is logical for White to exchange queens as soon as possible as there is no better option ! }
11... Rfxd8
{ And in the following sequence  (rather forced)  , Black manages to keep good compensation. }
12. Kd2 Nbd5 13. Nxd5 Ne4+
{ This is an important in-between move. We prevent White from playing Bd3 after ...Bxd5. If that happens, we will not be able to play ...Ne4 later on. }
14. Ke1 Bxd5 15. Rc1
{ This may be a very human move, with the idea of occupying the open file, but is clearly a mistake. }
15... Rac8 { And now Black is clearly better. } 16. Rb1
{ Rd1 allows ...Rc2, whereas exchanging rooks leaves us with the file and no opposition. }
16... Bxa2 17. Ra1 Bc4
{ We want to exchange the light-squared bishops and then get our rook onto the second rank. We will double up on the c file and enjoy a clear advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Russian System"]
[Black "The Russian System: 4.Nf3 Bg7 - 5.Qa4+ 19"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qa4+
{ With this check White wants to disrupt our natural development. Ivan Sokolov has played this line in several games against the Grunfeld guru Peter Svidler. }
5... Bd7 { But we also gain a tempo here ! } 6. Qb3
{ 6... Nc6 loses a pawn for nothing in this position. Do not confuse the idea here: There is a huge difference between 4. Qa4+ and 5. Qa4+ as the d4 pawn is now defended by the developed knight on f3. }
6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 { The best and most logical response from White. } 7... O-O
8. Bf4
{ The main line from White. This option has grown in popularity over the last couple of years. }
8... Be6
{ This is my recommendation. We ignore the hanging pawn on c7, but we will get something in return: A lead in development, the pawn on d4 will become a target and we will also have some dangerous threats with ...Nc6-b4. }
9. Qxc7 Nc6 10. e3 { This is White's main line and the best-scoring move. }
10... Nb4 { We force White to take a decision now. } 11. Qxd8
{ As we are threatening ...Nbd5 in this position, it is logical for White to exchange queens as soon as possible as there is no better option ! }
11... Rfxd8
{ And in the following sequence  (rather forced)  , Black manages to keep good compensation. }
12. Kd2 Nbd5 13. Nxd5 Ne4+
{ This is an important in-between move. We prevent White from playing Bd3 after ...Bxd5. If that happens, we will not be able to play ...Ne4 later on. }
14. Ke1 Bxd5 15. Bd3 Nc5
{ A great tactical resource that is possible thanks to the bishop hanging on d3. }
16. dxc5
{ Is also a possibility, I want to show you one example line of how the game may continue: }
16... Bxf3 17. gxf3 Rxd3 18. Ke2 Rd5 19. Rac1 Bxb2 20. Rc2 Bf6
{ The endgame is about equal. } *

