{ A respectable variation that we should know how to meet. However, I believe 7. e4 is the most challenging move. }
7... Na6
{ Remember this key idea. At the same time as we defend the c7-pawn, we get ready to challenge the centre. We can not simply let White get the whole centre !  We would also like to point out that, instead of ...Na6, you can transpose to one of the lines in the 5. Qa4+ Bd7 variation where Black plays 8...Be6. It is a good idea in terms of simplicity. However, 7...Na6 is a really dynamic move that we liked a lot in this position! }
8. e4 c5 9. d5 { White's main alternative. } 9... e6 10. d6
{ The main alternative. } 10... e5
{ A move that was played by Garry Kasparov. Black sacrifices a pawn to get the initiative ! }
11. Bxe5
{ 11. Nxe5 is simply bad due to ...Nh5 ! with a better game for Black. } 11...
Nb4 12. Rd1 { An interesting idea, provoking ...Nc2+. } 12... Be6 13. Qxc5 Nc2+
14. Kd2 Nd7 { A key move at a key moment. } 15. Qc7 Nxe5 16. Qxd8 Raxd8 17.
Kxc2 Ng4 18. Rd2 Bh6
{ With this resource, we force White to return one of the extra pawns. } 19.
Re2 Rxd6 20. h3 Nf6 21. g4
{ A key move. Otherwise, Black could get an advantage. } 21... Nd7
{ See Piket-Kasparov, Wijk aan Zee  (2000)  . Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn. }
