[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Russian System"]
[Black "The Russian System: 4.Nf3 Bg7 - 5.Qb3 24"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3
{ This move characterises the Russian System. White exerts a lot of pressure on d5. There are two ways to fight against this pressure:  1  Play passive, solid moves like ...e6 or ...c6; and  2  Take on c4 and give White more control of the centre while gaining a lead in development in return.  The first approach is not in the spirit of the Grunfeld at all, so there is no doubt we should choose the second approach ! }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. Bf4
{ A respectable variation that we should know how to meet. However, I believe 7. e4 is the most challenging move. }
7... Na6
{ Remember this key idea. At the same time as we defend the c7-pawn, we get ready to challenge the centre. We can not simply let White get the whole centre !  We would also like to point out that, instead of ...Na6, you can transpose to one of the lines in the 5. Qa4+ Bd7 variation where Black plays 8...Be6. It is a good idea in terms of simplicity. However, 7...Na6 is a really dynamic move that we liked a lot in this position! }
8. e4 c5 9. d5 { White's main alternative. } 9... e6 10. Be2
{ White's most tried option, although I believe d6 is more challenging if we do not know the position ! }
10... exd5 11. exd5
{ This positions reminds of the ...Na6 variation in the Russian System, but with the big difference that White has not castled yet ! Instead, the dark-squared bishop is developed and we can benefit from that. }
11... Nb4
{ 11... b5 !?N is a very interesting novelty. The idea is to follow with ...Re8 and ...Bb7 ! Playing really actively for the sacrifice and bringing all our pieces to play quickly, while also targeting the d5 pawn. I encourage you to take a look at it at it could really surprise your opponent. However, this move is the main recommendation and the safest option while maintaining a very good game. }
12. O-O { Has also been tried, but it is clearly weaker than Rd1. } 12... Nfxd5
{ better than ...Nbxd5. } 13. Rad1 Be6 14. Ng5 Qxg5 15. Bxg5 Nxc3 16. Qxc5
{ White tries to prove that our 14th move was the wrong idea, nothing could be further from the truth ! }
16... Nxe2+ 17. Kh1 Nc6
{ Black's three pieces are stronger than White's queen and Black is clearly better. }
*

