[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3
{ This move characterises the Russian System. White exerts a lot of pressure on d5. There are two ways to fight against this pressure:  1  Play passive, solid moves like ...e6 or ...c6; and  2  Take on c4 and give White more control of the centre while gaining a lead in development in return.  The first approach is not in the spirit of the Grunfeld at all, so there is no doubt we should choose the second approach ! }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. Bf4
{ A respectable variation that we should know how to meet. However, I believe 7. e4 is the most challenging move. }
7... Na6
{ Remember this key idea. At the same time as we defend the c7-pawn, we get ready to challenge the centre. We can not simply let White get the whole centre !  We would also like to point out that, instead of ...Na6, you can transpose to one of the lines in the 5. Qa4+ Bd7 variation where Black plays 8...Be6. It is a good idea in terms of simplicity. However, 7...Na6 is a really dynamic move that we liked a lot in this position! }
8. e4 c5 9. dxc5 { By far White's main choice. } 9... Be6
{ ...Qa5 is also possible. However, I like the recommended move more. } 10. Qb5
{ The only move that makes sense for White in this position. } 10... Bd7 11.
Qxb7 { 11. Qc4 would lead to a repetition. } 11... Nxc5 12. Qb4 Ne6
{ Normally in these lines, the lead in development we enjoy will give us enough compensation for the pawn, and sometimes even more if White does not play carefully ! }
13. Be5 a5
{ The perfect moment to chase White's queen away from the b4 square. In some variations this is key in order to target the e4 pawn. }
14. Qa3 Qb6 15. Nd5
{ This lead to a forcing line in which only Black can be better. } 15... Nxd5
16. exd5 Nd4 17. Bxd4 Bxd4 18. Nxd4 Qxd4
{ Black is in no danger at all and actually White should be very careful in these lines to avoid falling into a worse position immediately. }
