1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3
{ This move characterises the Russian System. White exerts a lot of pressure on d5. There are two ways to fight against this pressure:  1  Play passive, solid moves like ...e6 or ...c6; and  2  Take on c4 and give White more control of the centre while gaining a lead in development in return.  The first approach is not in the spirit of the Grunfeld at all, so there is no doubt we should choose the second approach ! }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4
{ We reach the starting point of the classical Qb3 variation, and we also reach a crossroad. We have a variety of options here: ...a6, ...Na6, ...Nc6, ...Bg4, ...Nfd7, ... Be6, etc. }
7... Nc6
{ Even though this is not the most popular choice at the top level, I decided to opt for ...Nc6 as it is more consistent with our repertoire and also rich in play and ideas. GM Avrukh defines ...Nc6 at this point as a 'viable alternative to the more common lines.' }
8. Bf4 Bg4
{ ...Nh5 and ...Nd7 are more common moves. But I like this idea, which so far has been played in less than 10 games according to my database. It has however caught the attention of players such as Khalifman, Ganguly and Inarkiev. }
9. d5 Bxf3 10. dxc6 b5
{ A great tactical resource worth keeping in mind as it is typical in these positions of the Russian System. }
11. Nxb5
{ The main and only serious move for White. 11. Qxb5 ?! does not work due to ...Nxe4 ! }
11... Bxe4 12. Rd1
{ White does well not taking on c7, as the pawn is full of poison ! } 12... Qc8
13. Nxc7 { White's best move by far. } 13... Rb8
{ A novelty. ...e5 was played before, but this idea is simply much stronger at this point. }
14. Nb5 Rb6 15. c7
{ This brave pawn looks indeed scare, but we have enough resources to compensate the annoyance. }
15... Qa8
{ The key move ! We get very active chances and have a slight edge in this position. }
16. Be2 Bxg2 17. Rg1 Bb7
{ This move is necessary to play ...Nd5, targeting both the bishop on f4 and the pawn on c7. }
18. Rd8 Rxd8 19. cxd8=Q+ Qxd8 20. Bc7 Qa8 21. Bxb6 axb6
{ We have enough compensation, even maybe a slight edge if White does not play accurately, but objectively it should be about equal. This is probably the only line in the 8. Bf4 variation where I was not able to find any advantage or clear edge for Black, but I would still play Black here, to be honest. }
