1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3
{ This move characterises the Russian System. White exerts a lot of pressure on d5. There are two ways to fight against this pressure:  1  Play passive, solid moves like ...e6 or ...c6; and  2  Take on c4 and give White more control of the centre while gaining a lead in development in return.  The first approach is not in the spirit of the Grunfeld at all, so there is no doubt we should choose the second approach ! }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4
{ We reach the starting point of the classical Qb3 variation, and we also reach a crossroad. We have a variety of options here: ...a6, ...Na6, ...Nc6, ...Bg4, ...Nfd7, ... Be6, etc. }
7... Nc6
{ Even though this is not the most popular choice at the top level, I decided to opt for ...Nc6 as it is more consistent with our repertoire and also rich in play and ideas. GM Avrukh defines ...Nc6 at this point as a 'viable alternative to the more common lines.' }
8. Bg5
{ Has not been played in many games, but has brought White some good results so far. }
8... Bg4 9. O-O-O Nd7 10. e5
{ Pretty much the only move that has been played by the elite at this point. White prevents us from playing typical ideas such as ...e5. }
10... Nb6 11. Qc5 f6 12. Be3 fxe5 13. dxe5 Qe8
{ is a better move than ...Qc8. The queen exerts more control from e8 and also is not exposed to White ideas like h4-Bh3 after we exchange or sacrifice the exchange on f3, which could be a possibility. }
14. Be2 Rf5
{ Black's best move at this point, with a very interesting idea. The rook stands very well on f5 for now ! }
15. Bd3 Rh5 { It also stands well on h5 ! } 16. Bb5 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Bxe5 18. Rhg1
a6 19. Bxc6 Qxc6 20. Qxc6 bxc6 21. Rg5 Rxg5 22. Bxg5 Bxh2 23. Bxe7 h5
{ The extra pawn is significant here. It is unusual for Black to end up with a passed pawn on the kingside in the Grunfeld, but I guess this is the exception that proves the rule ! }
