[Black "The Russian System: 4.Nf3 Bg7 - 5.Qb3 43"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3
{ This move characterises the Russian System. White exerts a lot of pressure on d5. There are two ways to fight against this pressure:  1  Play passive, solid moves like ...e6 or ...c6; and  2  Take on c4 and give White more control of the centre while gaining a lead in development in return.  The first approach is not in the spirit of the Grunfeld at all, so there is no doubt we should choose the second approach ! }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4
{ We reach the starting point of the classical Qb3 variation, and we also reach a crossroad. We have a variety of options here: ...a6, ...Na6, ...Nc6, ...Bg4, ...Nfd7, ... Be6, etc. }
7... Nc6
{ Even though this is not the most popular choice at the top level, I decided to opt for ...Nc6 as it is more consistent with our repertoire and also rich in play and ideas. GM Avrukh defines ...Nc6 at this point as a 'viable alternative to the more common lines.' }
8. e5
{ The right pawn to advance if White really feels compelled to advance one of them. }
8... Be6
{ An interesting move that will leave us with queen and two pawns for three minor pieces for White. }
9. exf6 Bxc4 10. fxg7 Kxg7 11. Bxc4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Be2 Qb6
{ A highly unclear position. We have the queen and two pawns for three pieces, but White has no weaknesses. It is interesting and I believe the right plan, apart from grabbing the d-file, is to use our pawns cleverly in order to try and limit White minor pieces. Also, we should aim at creating some weaknesses that we can target at some point in White's position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Russian System"]
[Black "The Russian System: 4.Nf3 Bg7 - 5.Qb3 44"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3
{ This move characterises the Russian System. White exerts a lot of pressure on d5. There are two ways to fight against this pressure:  1  Play passive, solid moves like ...e6 or ...c6; and  2  Take on c4 and give White more control of the centre while gaining a lead in development in return.  The first approach is not in the spirit of the Grunfeld at all, so there is no doubt we should choose the second approach ! }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4
{ We reach the starting point of the classical Qb3 variation, and we also reach a crossroad. We have a variety of options here: ...a6, ...Na6, ...Nc6, ...Bg4, ...Nfd7, ... Be6, etc. }
7... Nc6
{ Even though this is not the most popular choice at the top level, I decided to opt for ...Nc6 as it is more consistent with our repertoire and also rich in play and ideas. GM Avrukh defines ...Nc6 at this point as a 'viable alternative to the more common lines.' }
8. Be2
{ The absolute main line, but White has some other options too that have been played at top level. }
8... e5
{ A very interesting move completely in the spirit of the Grunfeld. Vachier-Lagrave has played this a couple of times recently. Other ideas are ...Bg4 or ...Nd7. }
9. dxe5
{ Another option where we usually will not have many problems equalising and White should be careful in some risky lines. }
9... Ng4 10. O-O
{ We will not have problems with equalising if White plays normal development moves. }
10... Ngxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Qa4
{ The best move for White at this point. 12. Qb3 was played in Iotov-Sarkar, Dallas  (2014)  . Sarkar continued with 12... c6, however, ...Nc6 !, aiming for the d4 square, would have given him better chances. }
12... c6 13. Be3 Qe7 14. f4 Ng4 15. Bxg4 Bxg4 16. e5
{ White's maneuver Ne4-d6 is annoying, and therefore we need to be prepared to meet it by creating complications for White. }
16... Bf5 17. Ne4 b5 18. Qd4 Rfd8 19. Nd6 Be6 20. a4 f6
{ The game is unclear. We have a small edge as White will struggle to keep the material balance and will have to look for ways to get some activity in return for the pawn that will most likely fall. I would choose to play Black in this position if you'd ask me. }
*

