[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Russian System"]
[Black "The Russian System: 4.Nf3 Bg7 - 5.Qb3 57"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3
{ This move characterises the Russian System. White exerts a lot of pressure on d5. There are two ways to fight against this pressure:  1  Play passive, solid moves like ...e6 or ...c6; and  2  Take on c4 and give White more control of the centre while gaining a lead in development in return.  The first approach is not in the spirit of the Grunfeld at all, so there is no doubt we should choose the second approach ! }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4
{ We reach the starting point of the classical Qb3 variation, and we also reach a crossroad. We have a variety of options here: ...a6, ...Na6, ...Nc6, ...Bg4, ...Nfd7, ... Be6, etc. }
7... Nc6
{ Even though this is not the most popular choice at the top level, I decided to opt for ...Nc6 as it is more consistent with our repertoire and also rich in play and ideas. GM Avrukh defines ...Nc6 at this point as a 'viable alternative to the more common lines.' }
8. Be2
{ The absolute main line, but White has some other options too that have been played at top level. }
8... e5
{ A very interesting move completely in the spirit of the Grunfeld. Vachier-Lagrave has played this a couple of times recently. Other ideas are ...Bg4 or ...Nd7. }
9. d5
{ White's main option by far. Now that we counterattack in the centre, White fixes it gaining space and hoping that we can not find a good plan or squares for our pieces. }
9... Nd4 10. Nxd4 { White's main move by far. } 10... exd4 11. Qxd4 c6 12. Qc4
{ White's main option at this point. } 12... b5
{ Introduced by Vachier-Lagrave a few years ago. The old line is 12... cxd5. }
13. Qb3 cxd5 14. exd5 a5
{ An interesting novelty I would recommend in this position. ...b4 and ...Re8 have been tried before, but there are not many games. The idea of ...a5 is to keep the b4 pawn defended once we advance it and gain space on the queenside. We keep our options open and have a flexible position. }
15. Bxb5 Qe7+
{ We want to play ...a4, a move that will create complications and give us great initiative. }
16. Kf1 a4 17. Nxa4
{ This moves leads to complications and I believe it is easier to go wrong as White. 17. Bxa4 is met by ...Ba6+ !, and Black is practically winning. 17. Qc4 is met by ...Bb7 ! 18. Bd2 Qd8 !, with a clear advantage. We can pressure and open more files and diagonals for example with ...a3 if White does not play it. }
17... Rb8 18. Be3 Ba6 19. Nb6 Qa7
{ With a complicated position. We have multiple threats and it is indeed much easier for White to go wrong ! }
