[White "Taimanov Variation - 4.Bg5"]
[Black "Taimanov Variation: 4.Bg5 Bg7 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5
{ The Taimanov variation. White puts pressure on the d5 defender, the f6-knight. Once again, White develops the queenside before the kingside. 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 transposes to the 5. Nf3 line. }
4... Bg7
{ 4... Ne4 is the main move, but it requires knowing a great deal of difficult theory and tricky transpositions. The alternative recommendation is solid and will be backed up by a recommendation of Svidler in the only line which was thought to create problems for Black. }
5. e3
{ As other authors point out, it is a surprise that this is the second most played option. It feels like it does not mix very well with Bg5. We have a straightforward way to respond: }
5... c5
{ A well-known resource in the Grunfeld, attacking White's center at the first chance we get. }
6. dxc5 Qa5 { And we are fine in all lines of this variation. } 7. Qa4+ Qxa4 8.
Nxa4 Ne4 9. Bh4 Bd7
{ 'A knight on the rim is dim', isn't this what they say ? } *

