1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5
{ The Taimanov variation. White puts pressure on the d5 defender, the f6-knight. Once again, White develops the queenside before the kingside. 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 transposes to the 5. Nf3 line. }
4... Bg7
{ 4... Ne4 is the main move, but it requires knowing a great deal of difficult theory and tricky transpositions. The alternative recommendation is solid and we will be backed by a recommendation by Svidler in the sole line was thought to create problems for Black. }
5. e3
{ As other authors point out, it is a surprise that this is the second most played option. It feels like it does not mix very well with Bg5. We have a straightforward way to respond }
5... c5
{ A well-known resource in the Grunfeld, attacking White's center at the first chance we get. }
6. dxc5 Qa5 { And we are fine in all lines of this variation. } 7. Qd2 dxc4 8.
Bxc4 Qxc5 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Nd5 Qxc4
{ A novelty and the strongest move in the position, which happens to work well tactically after a sequence of moves. 10... Qd6 was played in Sharif-Rowson, Liechtenstein  (1996)  . }
11. Rc1 Qg4 12. f3 Qd7 13. Nc7+ Kd8 14. Nxa8 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Be5
{ Preventing the knight from coming to c7 and escaping. } 16. Ne2 b6 17. Ke1
Bb7 18. Nxb6 axb6 { Black is clearly better. } *

