[White "Taimanov Variation - 4.Bg5"]
[Black "Taimanov Variation: 4.Bg5 Bg7 9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5
{ The Taimanov variation. White puts pressure on the d5 defender, the f6-knight. Once again, White develops the queenside before the kingside. 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 transposes to the 5. Nf3 line. }
4... Bg7
{ 4... Ne4 is the main move, but it requires knowing a great deal of difficult theory and tricky transpositions. The alternative recommendation is solid and we will be backed by a recommendation by Svidler in the sole line was thought to create problems for Black. }
5. Nf3 Ne4
{ The absolute main line in this position is what I recommend. Other options are ...dxc4, which could lead to extremely sharp positions, and ...c5, which is interesting, but Black struggles to generate enough compensation in all the lines if White knows the theory. White has three main options at this point: cxd5, Bh4 and Bf4. }
6. Bh4
{ is second most tried option for White, and it makes more sense than Bf4 because of the knight on f3. }
6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 dxc4 8. Qa4+ Qd7
{ 8... Nd7 !? is a challenging option, but objectively it is probably worse than the recommendation. }
9. Qxc4 b6
{ We want to use the white's queen compromised position to win a tempo while developing our light-square bishop. }
10. e3
{ The most tried move. 10. Qb3 is possible, transposing as usually 11. e3 will come after 10... Ba6. }
10... Ba6 11. Qb3 Bxf1 12. Kxf1
{ Taking with the rook is also possible, but it will most likely transpose. }
12... O-O 13. Ke2 c5 14. dxc5 Na6
{ As a rule of thumb, Black usually enjoys great compensation when White takes on c5 and the pawn structure on the queenside is broken, like in this case with c3-a2, which make these pawns really easy to target along the a1-h8 diagonal and the c-file. }
15. Rhd1 Qc7
{ 15... Qb7 ?! allows 16. c6 !, and the Queen does not defend the e7 pawn anymore. Carlsen won a game from this variation against Eljanov in Wijk aan Zee  (2008)  . }
16. cxb6 axb6
{ Black enjoys fantastic compensation for the pawn in this well-known position. See Lautier-Ivanchuk, Terrassa  (1991)  . }
*

