[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5
{ The Taimanov variation. White puts pressure on the d5 defender, the f6-knight. Once again, White develops the queenside before the kingside. 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 transposes to the 5. Nf3 line. }
4... Bg7
{ 4... Ne4 is the main move, but it requires knowing a great deal of difficult theory and tricky transpositions. The alternative recommendation is solid and we will be backed by a recommendation by Svidler in the sole line was thought to create problems for Black. }
5. Nf3 Ne4
{ The absolute main line in this position is what I recommend. Other options are ...dxc4, which could lead to extremely sharp positions, and ...c5, which is interesting, but Black struggles to generate enough compensation in all the lines if White knows the theory. White has three main options at this point: cxd5, Bh4 and Bf4. }
6. cxd5
{ is the most famous reply to ...Ne4. Note how both 6. Nxe4 ?? and 6. Nxd5 ?? lose material. }
6... Nxg5 7. Nxg5 e6 8. Qd2 { The second most tried option after Nf3. } 8... h6
{ I want to avoid getting into the theoretical tree of ...exd5 here, which is fine for Black but requires a lot of studying. I believe it is easier to grasp the ideas and lines of ...h6, which actually, and to my surprise, score better at this point than ...exd5. }
9. Nh3 { Played more than 9. Nf3, but maybe more artificial. } 9... exd5 10.
Nf4 { The main move, ahead of Qe3+. } 10... O-O
{ Black does not spend time defending the pawn on d5. } 11. e3
{ 11. g3 seems more intimidating than it actually is. It allows ...Re8 ! and ...Nc6. Black is slightly better as both d-pawns will fall and we have the bishop pair in an open position. }
11... c5 12. dxc5 d4
{ We open the position for our g7-bishop. The sacrifice is justified and is a recurring concept in these lines. }
13. exd4 Qxd4 14. Qxd4 Bxd4 15. O-O-O Nc6 16. Nfd5 Bxc5 17. Ne4 Bd4 18. Bb5 Be5
19. f4 Bb8
{ The game is about equal, but we get to keep the bishop pair and can generate still some problems for White. }
