[White "Taimanov Variation - 4.Bg5"]
[Black "Taimanov Variation: 4.Bg5 Bg7 16"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5
{ The Taimanov variation. White puts pressure on the d5 defender, the f6-knight. Once again, White develops the queenside before the kingside. 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 transposes to the 5. Nf3 line. }
4... Bg7
{ 4... Ne4 is the main move, but it requires knowing a great deal of difficult theory and tricky transpositions. The alternative recommendation is solid and we will be backed by a recommendation by Svidler in the sole line was thought to create problems for Black. }
5. Nf3 Ne4
{ The absolute main line in this position is what I recommend. Other options are ...dxc4, which could lead to extremely sharp positions, and ...c5, which is interesting, but Black struggles to generate enough compensation in all the lines if White knows the theory. White has three main options at this point: cxd5, Bh4 and Bf4. }
6. cxd5
{ is the most famous reply to ...Ne4. Note how both 6. Nxe4 ?? and 6. Nxd5 ?? lose material. }
6... Nxg5 7. Nxg5 e6 8. Qd2 { The second most tried option after Nf3. } 8... h6
{ I want to avoid getting into the theoretical tree of ...exd5 here, which is fine for Black but requires a lot of studying. I believe it is easier to grasp the ideas and lines of ...h6, which actually, and to my surprise, score better at this point than ...exd5. }
9. Nf3
{ Objectively the move that most club players and not theoreticians/experts would play. }
9... exd5 10. e3 O-O 11. Be2
{ We reach a position with the Carlsbad pawn structure. Some ideas that you should know about this structure: 1  We will most likely stop White's minority attack on the queenside with ...a5 2  Black usually plays ...c6, but take into account that ...b6-...c5 is also possible, ending in a pawn structure with hanging pawns that could benefit us should we get a good initiative. Also, if White plays b4, we have the idea of ...c6-... b5  (with ...a5 played)  , gaining control over the c4 square. 3  Another idea is to play with ...f5-...f4, opening the position usually will benefit our dark-square bishop, which has no opposition. But, be careful with overextending when it is not a good time, White has extra cover for his king once castled, we just have 3 pawns and exchanging the f-pawn may mean that we can create weaknesses, you have to evaluate if it's safe to do so. 4  Black often plays with ...Re8 and recycles the dark-square bishop via f8-d6, where it has influence over both sides, supporting the kingside initiative we will want to generate later on and, also, helping stop White's minority attack idea. }
*

