1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5
{ The Taimanov variation. White puts pressure on the d5 defender, the f6-knight. Once again, White develops the queenside before the kingside. 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 transposes to the 5. Nf3 line. }
4... Bg7
{ 4... Ne4 is the main move, but it requires knowing a great deal of difficult theory and tricky transpositions. The alternative recommendation is solid and we will be backed by a recommendation by Svidler in the sole line was thought to create problems for Black. }
5. Bxf6
{ The absolute main line. White will try to prove that Black has no compensation for the pawn sacrifice. }
5... Bxf6 6. cxd5 { The only way for White to fight for an advantage. } 6... c6
{ Generating counterplay at the first chance we get. We enter a kingdom of unbalanced positions that every Grunfeld player should enjoy. }
7. Rc1
{ White's main alternative, which has been used just a few times less than the main move: e4. }
7... O-O 8. dxc6 { 8. e4 Bg7 ! transposes to 7. e4. } 8... Qxd4
{ This is the recommendation by Svidler I mentioned at the beginning of the line, which solves Black's problems in this line. }
9. Qxd4 Bxd4 10. cxb7
{ White's most serious continuation, grabbing the pawn and trying to show he has the advantage. }
10... Bxb7
{ This pawn sacrifice is a recurring concept in these lines. Observe how far in development Black is compared to White, also the bishop pair factor is important. Black has more than enough compensation. }
11. Nf3 Bf6 12. e3 Na6
{ I believe this is an interesting move and I am a bit surprised this has not been tried but once at master level. }
13. Be2
{ A better continuation than 13. Bc4, which was played in Li-Garcia, HD Bank op  (2017)  . I have included the game for you to see more about the ... Na6 !? idea. }
13... Rac8 14. O-O Rfd8 15. a3 Nc5
{ Black has enough compensation for the pawn. } *

