[Black "Taimanov Variation: 4.Bg5 Bg7 31"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5
{ The Taimanov variation. White puts pressure on the d5 defender, the f6-knight. Once again, White develops the queenside before the kingside. 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 transposes to the 5. Nf3 line. }
4... Bg7
{ 4... Ne4 is the main move, but it requires knowing a great deal of difficult theory and tricky transpositions. The alternative recommendation is solid and we will be backed by a recommendation by Svidler in the sole line was thought to create problems for Black. }
5. Bxf6
{ The absolute main line. White will try to prove that Black has no compensation for the pawn sacrifice. }
5... Bxf6 6. cxd5 { The only way for White to fight for an advantage. } 6... c6
{ Generating counterplay at the first chance we get. We enter a kingdom of unbalanced positions that every Grunfeld player should enjoy. }
7. e4
{ White's absolute main line. An ambitious move which poses Black some problems to solve. }
7... O-O
{ The main line is my recommendation here. However, I would like to bring 7... Bg7 !? to your attention. The idea is to play prophilactically against a possible e5. Black will enter positions with a great positional compensation thanks to two very strong bishops, Black's main aim is not to get the pawn back though. I would suggest keeping an eye on such lines. Unfortunately, there are not many high-level games yet, but it is likely to be used in the future. }
8. e5
{ The main and most ambitious move for White. The absolute test for Black in this variation. }
8... Bg7 9. Bc4 b5 { Needed if we want to win material back. } 10. Be2
{ An interesting attempt. White prefers to develop his knight via f3, rather than e2, where the knight sits strangely. With Be2, White minimises the effect of ...Bg4 as well, as recapturing on f3 with bishop is possible. }
10... b4 11. Na4 cxd5 12. Nf3 Bg4
{ Black sets a bind on the White squares and will recycle his bishop to the a3-f8 diagonal, playing on the queenside first and if White tries to release the tension there, the b-pawn will become a potential target. }
13. O-O Qa5 14. b3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 e6 16. Qd2 Nd7 17. a3 Rfb8 18. Rfc1 Bf8 19.
Bd1 Rc8
{ Black fully equalises. See Xiong-Durarbayli, A Saint Louis  (2018)  . } *

