[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation Sidelines - 5th Moves"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: Sidelines 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Na4
{ An old, interesting idea. White wants to take on the whole center without allowing ...Nxc3. Also, it prevents our thematic pawn break: ...c5. }
5... Nf6
{ The main move by far is 5... Bg7. With the suggested odd-looking move, we are breaking the rule ! We are moving the knight back to f6, but, why ? We simply take advantage of the fact that White will have a very difficult time proving any advantage without e4. Several well-known GMs have used this move before, such as: Sasikiran, Wang, Yermolinsky, Belov, McShane...  White has the option to repeat moves here after: 6.Nc3 Nd5 7.Na4 Nf6... If this is not something that you have in mind for any reason, I recommend taking a look at 5... e5 !?, an option which leads to rich positions in which Black is by no means worse after 6. dxe5 Nc6. }
6. g3 { Does not work now due to } 6... Nc6 7. Nf3 e5
{ ...Bg7 was played in Rogule-Zaksaite, Oropesa del Mar  (1999)  . However, the recommended novelty is much stronger. }
8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Ng4 11. Ke1 Bd7 12. Nc3 Bc6 13. f3 Nxe5
{ Black has almost a clear advantage. Our pieces are much better, White has a strange pawn structure and is behind in development. }
*

