1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Na4
{ An old, interesting idea. White wants to take on the whole center without allowing ...Nxc3. Also, it prevents our thematic pawn break: ...c5. }
5... Nf6
{ The main move by far is 5... Bg7. With the suggested odd-looking move, we are breaking the rule ! We are moving the knight back to f6, but, why ? We simply take advantage of the fact that White will have a very difficult time proving any advantage without e4. Several well-known GMs have used this move before, such as: Sasikiran, Wang, Yermolinsky, Belov, McShane... If repeating moves is not something that you have in mind for any reason, I recommend taking a look at 5... e5 !?, an option which leads to rich positions in which Black is by no means worse after 6. dxe5 Nc6. }
6. Nf3 { The main option and the most logical one for White. } 6... Bg7 7. Bf4
O-O 8. e3 Nbd7 9. Be2 { is just slightly less popular than Rc1. } 9... c5
{ our thematic pawn break ! } 10. Nxc5 Nxc5 11. dxc5 Ne4 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Be5
Nxc5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. O-O Be6 16. Nd4 Bd5
{ The position is about equal. However, Black is slightly more active and Van de Mortel can show us an example of how to play the endgame. See Friedrichs-Van de Mortel, BEL chT  (2000)  . }
*

