[Black "Exchange Variation: Sidelines 4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Na4
{ An old, interesting idea. White wants to take on the whole center without allowing ...Nxc3. Also, it prevents our thematic pawn break: ...c5. }
5... Nf6
{ The main move by far is 5... Bg7. With the suggested odd-looking move, we are breaking the rule ! We are moving the knight back to f6, but, why ? We simply take advantage of the fact that White will have a very difficult time proving any advantage without e4. Several well-known GMs have used this move before, such as: Sasikiran, Wang, Yermolinsky, Belov, McShane... If repeating moves is not something that you have in mind for any reason, I recommend taking a look at 5... e5 !?, an option which leads to rich positions in which Black is by no means worse after 6. dxe5 Nc6. }
6. Nf3 { The main option and the most logical one for White. } 6... Bg7 7. Bf4
O-O 8. e3 Nbd7 9. Rc1
{ White tries to avoid ...c5. GM Narciso Dublan used this move in a blitz match against McShane. }
9... c6
{ After Rc1, with ...c5 not being an option, we will choose to play with the other thematic pawn break: ...e5 ! }
10. Be2 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 Nd5
{ Black's position is very rich with ideas, notably the ...e5 pawn break. White will have to sacrifice the pawn on a2 if he wants to maintain the pawn structure, and then accept some unclear consequences after }
12. Bg3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Qxa2 { White's compensation is not obvious at all. } 14.
O-O e5
{ Indeed we play the pawn break, which now takes the form of a brilliant positional sacrifice. Apart from breaking White's center, we gain an important square for our knight on c5 ! This, together with the strong a-pawn, gives Black a game that is more than acceptable. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation Sidelines - 5th Moves"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: Sidelines 5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bd2
{ This line has become increasingly popular over the last few years. White's idea is to take on c3 with bishop. This way, our dark-squared bishop will have opposition along the a1-h8 diagonal. }
5... Nb6
{ 5... Bg7 is the main line. However, this move scores better nowadays and is regaining popularity. I recommend this move as taking on c3, which is also viable, will mean that the bishop on c3 will make the pawn breaks on c5 and e5 less effective, or the game will take a different direction. I believe this variation fits better in our repertoire. Now White has four different options which are similar in terms of popularity. }
6. e3
{ A secondary line which may look very sober and not really ambitious, but it hides a line that could be really problematic if we underestimate it ! }
6... Bg7 7. f4
{ The main line, which has been played by many top GMs. 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Rc1 transposes to a line that will be covered under the 6. Nf3 move order. }
7... O-O 8. Nf3 c5
{ And again, the thematic pawn break. By means of this pawn sacrifice, we activate our position and get interesting play. }
9. dxc5 N6d7 10. b4 a5 11. a3 e5
{ The following analysis was provided by Svidler, who commented in his analysis that this was pointed out as the best option by Houdini. }
12. Bc4 exf4 13. exf4 Nc6 14. Rb1
{ 14. O-O is not ambitious for White and we equalise easily by taking the b4-pawn with the knight after the exchanges. }
14... axb4 15. axb4 Re8+ 16. Ne2 { Any other option is worse for White. } 16...
Nf6 17. O-O Bf5 18. Ng5 Nd5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation Sidelines - 5th Moves"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: Sidelines 6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bd2
{ This line has become increasingly popular over the last few years. Whites idea is to take on c3 with bishop. This way, our dark-squared bishop will have opposition along the a1-h8 diagonal. }
5... Nb6
{ 5... Bg7 is the main line. However, this move scores better nowadays and is regaining popularity. I recommend this move as taking on c3, which is also viable, will mean that the bishop on c3 will make the pawn breaks on c5 and e5 less effective, or the game will take a different direction. I believe this variation fits better in our repertoire. Now White has four different options which are similar in terms of popularity. }
6. e3
{ A secondary line which may look very sober and not really ambitious, but it hides a line that could be really problematic if we underestimate it ! }
6... Bg7 7. f4
{ The main line, which has been played by many top GMs. 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Rc1 transposes to a line that will be covered under the 6. Nf3 move order. }
7... O-O 8. Nf3 c5
{ And again, the thematic pawn break. By means of this pawn sacrifice, we activate our position and get interesting play. }
9. dxc5 N6d7 10. Ne4
{ The main move and the one that makes most sense in my opinion in this position. }
10... Bxb2 11. Rb1 Bg7 12. Bc4
{ Whites only way to try to fight for an advantage. } 12... Na6
{ The problem with the most obvious move, ... Nf6, is, as Svidler highlighted, that White has serious chances to checkmate us. And I add to this, in case it helps you remember, that it leaves as with less pieces to defend on the kingside and with lots of space to launch an attack against our king. Also, our whole queenside will need to be developed. Not a very attractive option in my opinion. }
13. Bxa6 bxa6 14. Rc1
{ Whites best move, it prevents an immediate attack on the c5 pawn. } 14... Nb8
{ We recycle our knight to block White's passer. } 15. O-O Qd5 16. Nf2
{ Until now, we are following Riazantsev-Svidler, RUS-ch  (2017)  . And now Svidler missed a good chance to play a strong move, he rather chose 16... Bb7. White could have obtained an advantage in a game that ended up in a draw. }
16... Nc6
{ A great move that keeps Black on track with an initiative and full compensation. }
17. Qa4 Rb8 { With counterplay. As mentioned, Black enjoys full compensation. }
*

