{ This line has become increasingly popular over the last few years. Whites idea is to take on c3 with bishop. This way, our dark-squared bishop will have opposition along the a1-h8 diagonal. }
5... Nb6
{ 5... Bg7 is the main line. However, this move scores better nowadays and is regaining popularity. I recommend this move as taking on c3, which is also viable, will mean that the bishop on c3 will make the pawn breaks on c5 and e5 less effective, or the game will take a different direction. I believe this variation fits better in our repertoire. Now White has four different options which are similar in terms of popularity. }
6. Nf3 { Also a popular option. White will try to prevent ...c5. } 6... Bg7 7.
Rc1 { 7. Bg5 transposes to a line seen under 6. Bg5. } 7... Nc6 8. e3
{ White has to play this move. The alternatives are clearly worse. } 8... O-O
9. Bb5
{ The critical attempt. Other choices are worse and we have a comfortable game after }
9... e5
{ 9... Bd7 is the main move, but I believe is worse than the recommended option, which has been defended by players such as: Sasikiran, Nielsen or Krasenkow. }
10. Bxc6 { The main and logical move. } 10... exd4
{ The key of playing ...e5 ! } 11. Nxd4 bxc6
{ Our bishop pair, especially our light-squared one, will give us enough counterplay to make up for our damaged pawn structure. }
12. Nxc6
{ This move has never been tried before, and it makes sense as it looks really suspicious. }
12... Qd7
{ Black has a good position. Now White will have to give some material back not to fall in a seriously worse position. }
*

