1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bd2
{ This line has become increasingly popular over the last few years. Whites idea is to take on c3 with bishop. This way, our dark-squared bishop will have opposition along the a1-h8 diagonal. }
5... Nb6
{ 5... Bg7 is the main line. However, this move scores better nowadays and is regaining popularity. I recommend this move as taking on c3, which is also viable, will mean that the bishop on c3 will make the pawn breaks on c5 and e5 less effective, or the game will take a different direction. I believe this variation fits better in our repertoire. Now White has four different options which are similar in terms of popularity. }
6. Bf4
{ Is also a secondary line which enjoys a similar reputation that 6. e3. } 6...
Bg7 7. e3 { this is the main continuation. Nf3 most often transposes. } 7...
O-O { Our choice also happens to be the main continuation. } 8. Nf3 Be6
{ I firmly believe this move gives us good play. We prepare .. .Nc6, put an eye on the thematic c4-square and keep our ...c5 pawn break option open. The main move here is 8... c5. 8... Bg4 is also interesting, but a rather passive choice, as highlighted by Svidler in his analysis. }
9. Rc1
{ This seems to be a logical move, which can be met with a common idea: } 9...
c5
{ With a complicated position. This has been played by GMs like Ricardi and Kozul. }
