[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation Sidelines - 5th Moves"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: Sidelines 14"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bd2
{ This line has become increasingly popular over the last few years. White's idea is to take on c3 with bishop. This way, our dark-squared bishop will have opposition along the a1-h8 diagonal. }
5... Nb6
{ 5... Bg7 is the main line. However, this move scores better nowadays and is regaining popularity. I recommend this move as taking on c3, which is also viable, will mean that the bishop on c3 will make the pawn breaks on c5 and e5 less effective, or the game will take a different direction. I believe this variation fits better in our repertoire. Now White has four different options which are similar in terms of popularity. }
6. Bg5
{ Here we should remember the idea of an early ...c5 ! As The dark-squared bishop from White will be out of the pawn chain and won't be able to defend on c3, we can destroy Whites pawn structure. }
6... Bg7 7. e3 c5
{ This is the second most used move, notably after the main option: O-O. However, this variation scores much better than the main move and is therefore our choice. }
8. dxc5 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3
{ This concept is quite typical in the Grunfeld, we exchange our dark-squared bishop in order to ruin White's structure. }
9... Qxd1+ 10. Rxd1 N6d7 { We will be more than fine if we capture on c5. } 11.
Bb5 { White's main and most logical line. } 11... Nc6 12. Nf3
{ looks like a natural move, but it gives Black the better chances due to }
12... f6 { White's bishop will be out of the game for a while. } 13. Bh4 Nxc5
14. Nd4
{ This is, in my opinion, the most challenging idea from White. 14. O-O is also an option, see Medina Plasencia-Fernandez Garcia, Tenerife  (2014)  . }
14... Bd7 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Bc4
{ We are following Sandhoefner-Ragger, AUT-chT  (2017)  . Now I found a great improvement which happens to be a novelty as well: }
16... Rb8
{ A strong novelty. We are quickly getting a very active and annoying position for White to handle. }
17. f3 Be6 18. Bg3 Rb2 19. Bxe6 Nxe6
{ The endgame is slightly in Black's favor. } *

