1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. Qa4+
{ An independent line often used as a surprise. The rest of the options are covered in other chapters, where Nf3 from White happens later on in the game. For example, 6. e4 transposes to the Exchange Variation, 6. e3 transposes to the Closed Grunfeld, 6. g3 transposes to the Fianchetto Variation, etc. }
6... Bd7
{ Here Black has played three options which are reasonable and similar in terms of popularity. Probably ...Nc6 !? is the most recent approach; however, finally I decided to suggest ...Bd7 as I believe it fits better in our repertoire. }
7. Qb3 { The main move and probably the most logical one as well. } 7... Nxc3
{ The main move here is ...Nb6. However, I found a new idea in this alternative variation  (almost virgin soil)  that I recommend. }
8. bxc3 { White's main capture and the logical move. } 8... c5
{ And again, the thematic pawn break in the Grunfeld seen in action. We activate the long dark-squared diagonal and get a really comfortable game with great chances. }
9. e3 O-O
{ This pawn structure, as highlighted by Grunfeld experts such as Avrukh, is virtually always good for Black. }
10. Be2 Qc7 11. O-O Nc6 12. Rd1 Na5
{ 12... Rac8 was played in Turner-Seidman, New York  (1957)  . I have included the game as a reference. I think it is best not to commit the rook to c8 yet, as we can see in the given line. }
13. Qa3 b6 14. dxc5 Be6
{ Remember this maneuver, it is a really good way for Black to end up with the two best minor pieces. }
15. cxb6 { White is better off not taking on b6 as, after } 15... axb6
{ Black is already better and with multiple immediate threats. } *

