[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation Sidelines - 7th Moves"]
[Black "Exchange Variation Sidelines: 7th Moves - 7.Qa4+ 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Qa4+
{ White disrupts our normal development before continuing developing naturally. Now we have to choose between covering the check with the queen or with the knight. This move has gotten quite a bit of attention recently, with strong players like Nakamura using it a lot. Svidler himself mentions in his book that he had to face this line against Ruslan Ponomariov in 2011. It happened during the semi-final of the World Cup. }
7... Nd7
{ This is the strongest move and the option Mikel and I believe fits in the spirit of this repertoire. We decided to give this line as 7. Qa4+ is a trendy variation that has been used more and more, especially in rapid and blitz games. 7... Qd7 is also a playable option. }
8. Bg5
{ An alternative that has been used notably by strong players such as Volkov and Krasenkow. }
8... O-O 9. Rd1
{ This is the independent line I want to show you in this variation. Note how White develops his whole queenside before even moving a piece of the kingside. Note how 9. Nf3 would transpose to one of the lines covered after 8. Nf3. }
9... Nb6
{ The most common move here for Black is 9... c5, which is recommended by both Avrukh and Svidler in their analysis. However, this is a very interesting novelty I was really happy to find. }
10. Qa3 { White exerts pressure on the e7-pawn. } 10... Qd7
{ This is the key of our plan. This move is two-fold: 1- We threaten ...Qg4, which is indeed a very strong idea. 2- We want to transfer the queen to c6, from where it will have a great influence over the pawn on c3, but also, and more importantly, over the c4 square, a common outpost and key square in the Grunfeld, as I have mentioned in other variations. }
11. Nf3 { White ignores our most immediate threat. } 11... Qg4
{ This move is really annoying for White to face. We target the pawn on e4 and White has no easy way to develop his position and stop our ideas or counter our initiative. }
12. e5
{ White's best attempt in my opinion. Now I want to show you an example line of how the game may continue: }
12... Be6
{ The same idea we have seen over and over again in the Grunfeld. We want to use the outpost on c4 for our minor pieces. }
13. Be2 Qe4 { We make it difficult for White to develop naturally. } 14. Be3
{ White cannot castle as the bishop on e2 would be en prise. } 14... Nc4
{ Our knight lands on the c4-outpost. } 15. Qc1 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Bh6
{ White's pawn structure is dubious to say the least. Now our idea is to challenge the center. }
17. Kf2 c5
{ Black is slightly better in this position. White should tread carefully or the advantage could be more significant. }
*

