[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Qa4+
{ White disrupts our normal development before continuing developing naturally. Now we have to choose between covering the check with the queen or with the knight. This move has gotten quite a bit of attention recently, with strong players like Nakamura using it a lot. Svidler himself mentions in his book that he had to face this line against Ruslan Ponomariov in 2011. It happened during the semi-final of the World Cup. }
7... Nd7
{ This is the strongest move and the option Mikel and I believe fits in the spirit of this repertoire. We decided to give this line as 7. Qa4+ is a trendy variation that has been used more and more, especially in rapid and blitz games. 7... Qd7 is also a playable option. }
8. Be3
{ This move, intended at bolstering the center, has been notably played by GM Milov, although Nakamura and Sokolov have used it as well. }
8... O-O 9. Rd1 Nb6
{ Similar to the variation with 8. Bg5, here the main move is 9... c5. However, I do not see any reason not to stick to this novelty again ! }
10. Qb3 { This move is not really accurate due to } 10... Bd7
{ We threaten ...Ba4 and then probably the following move is the only one that slightly justifies Qb3 for White: }
11. Bb5 Bxb5 12. Qxb5 Qe8
{ It is important to understand than trading queens benefit us. The queen is White's most active piece. }
13. Qxe8 Rfxe8
{ We are ready to challenge the center, gaining some space to use the third rank and transfer our rook on e8 to the queenside, from where it can target White's structural weaknesses. }
14. Ne2 e5 15. f3 Nc4 { A great outpost for our knight. } 16. Bf2
{ Black has a comfortable advantage in this position. We can keep White tied down for a while here while we improve our pieces and try to create more weaknesses in our opponent's position. }
