1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Qa4+
{ White disrupts our normal development before continuing developing naturally. Now we have to choose between covering the check with the queen or with the knight. This move has gotten quite a bit of attention recently, with strong players like Nakamura using it a lot. Svidler himself mentions in his book that he had to face this line against Ruslan Ponomariov in 2011. It happened during the semi-final of the World Cup. }
7... Nd7
{ This is the strongest move and the option Mikel and I believe fits in the spirit of this repertoire. We decided to give this line as 7. Qa4+ is a trendy variation that has been used more and more, especially in rapid and blitz games. 7... Qd7 is also a playable option. }
8. Nf3
{ This is White's usual choice. The alternatives frequently transpose if White follows up with Nf3 in the next few moves. }
8... O-O 9. Be2 { White's most frequent try. } 9... c5 10. O-O
{ White's universal response. Moiseenko has played this line in multiple occasions with White. }
10... Nb6
{ Here I agree with Svidler that it is not necessary to get into really complicated positions arising from 10... cxd4, as shown in an Informational line. }
11. Qa3 cxd4 12. cxd4 Bg4 13. Bg5 { White's main try at this point. } 13...
Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Qxd4 15. Qxe7
{ Taking with the queen makes more sense than doing so with the bishop. } 15...
Rab8 16. Rad1 Qa4
{ Now I will quote Svidler: 'I looked at this position quite carefully and I believe it should be very holdable for Black. Strategically speaking, if White could somehow transfer his bishop from f3 to b3 in one move, then Black's position would be very difficult and maybe even lost. So I believe this is a more prudent and practical solution than the whole mess starting with 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc5.' }
