[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation - 7.Nf3"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Nf3 3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3
{ 7. Bc4 is the main line and the classical option. Nf3 is considered the modern approach  (compared to Bc4)  of the Exchange Variation. In these lines, White intends to develop his pieces to natural squares: Nf3, Be3, Be2 and O-O.  In the long term, White's idea is to consolidate his centre with d5 and eventually c4. We must keep in mind that the best approach will still be the same and we should play in the Grunfeld's spirit ! The main idea to keep in mind is that, contrary to what happens in the 7. Bc4 lines, we have the annoying thematic pin: ...Bg4. }
7... c5 { Challenging the center immediately. The best move order. } 8. Be2
{ A secondary line and also a dubious move. You probably know what I mean if you have seen the informational line with 7...O-O. }
8... Nc6 { We keep challenging the center. } 9. d5
{ Does not work for White due to the fact that he has not castled yet ! You can tell the difference compared to the move order with 7...O-O. However, this is considered to be somewhat challenging, do not believe you will have a free point ! }
9... Bxc3+ 10. Bd2 Bxa1 11. Qxa1 Nd4 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Qxd4 O-O 14. Bh6
{ White gets back the exchange, but the initiative will be gone for him and it is not very coherent with the exchange sacrifice player earlier on. }
14... Qa5+ 15. Kf1 f6 16. Bxf8 Kxf8
{ Black has a more comfortable game here and has a slight advantage. See Hernandez Onna-Sisniega, Matanzas  (1992)  . }
*

