{ Black has more options, but this is the main line and the most logical move. In the Grunfeld, we should always pressure and challenge the center ! }
11. O-O Rd8 12. d5
{ This is a thematic sacrifice in some lines of the Grunfeld. White has scored well in this variation, which has been used by strong GMs like Korchnoi. However, I believe I have found an effective antidote, so we should not be scared ! }
12... Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Qxc3 14. Rc1 Qa3
{ ...Qa5 has been suggested by Avrukh. However, this seems to be the best square for the queen for now. In some variations it may be key to keep an eye on the e3 square to prevent White from playing f4, which leaves the e4 pawn weak, as ...Qe3+ may be a strong move. }
15. Ne5
{ This move allows us to develop by offering the knight exchange, which undoubtedly benefits us. }
15... Bxe2 16. Qxe2 Nd7 17. Nxd7 Rxd7
{ White's only chance to play actively in this position is to advance the kingside pawns. Otherwise we will be better if we advance our queenside and White just moves around the board with his major pieces. Black has a comfortable advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation - 7.Nf3"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Nf3 13"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3
{ 7. Bc4 is the main line and the classical option. Nf3 is considered the modern approach  (compared to Bc4)  of the Exchange Variation. In these lines, White intends to develop his pieces to natural squares: Nf3, Be3, Be2 and O-O.  In the long term, White's idea is to consolidate his centre with d5 and eventually c4. We must keep in mind that the best approach will still be the same and we should play in the Grunfeld's spirit ! The main idea to keep in mind is that, contrary to what happens in the 7. Bc4 lines, we have the annoying thematic pin: ...Bg4. }
7... c5 { Challenging the center immediately. The best move order. } 8. Be3
{ White's second option at this point, but this is also a big main line of the Nf3 variation. White overprotects the pawn on d4. White will develop his queenside entirely before even worrying about his kingside. After Be3, White usually plays Qd2 and Rb1/Rc1. With Rc1, White's idea is to quickly protect c3, following up with the d5 strategic threat. }
8... Qa5 9. Bd2
{ An odd-looking move. White will try to exploit the position of our queen. }
9... O-O 10. Be2 Bg4
{ Black has more options, but this is the main line and the most logical move. In the Grunfeld, we should always pressure and challenge the center ! }
11. O-O Rd8 12. Rb1
{ The main variation as the alternative is not very promising for White in this particular position. The ideas from White will remind you of 8. Rb1 !? }
12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Qxa2 { The most logical and strongest response. } 14. d5
{ 14. Ra1 Qb2 would lead to a repetition, and that may indeed be the best option at White's disposal ! }
14... b6
{ 14... Nd7 !? is another idea, giving back the pawn to activate the pieces. However, I do not think we should give back the pawn, we have also the option of developing without giving back the pawn thanks to favourable tactics ! }
15. Bg5 Nc6 { Taking advantage of the pinned queen to develop ! } 16. Rc1 h6
17. Bh4 g5 18. Bg3 Rac8 19. h3 Bxf3 20. Bxf3 Ne5
{ Black has a slight advantage. We have free hands on the queenside and better minor pieces, while White finds some problems to coordinate his position. }
*

