[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation - 7.Nf3"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Nf3 20"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3
{ 7. Bc4 is the main line and the classical option. Nf3 is considered the modern approach  (compared to Bc4)  of the Exchange Variation. In these lines, White intends to develop his pieces to natural squares: Nf3, Be3, Be2 and O-O.  In the long term, White's idea is to consolidate his centre with d5 and eventually c4. We must keep in mind that the best approach will still be the same and we should play in the Grunfeld's spirit ! The main idea to keep in mind is that, contrary to what happens in the 7. Bc4 lines, we have the annoying thematic pin: ...Bg4. }
7... c5 { Challenging the center immediately. The best move order. } 8. Be3
{ White's second option at this point, but this is also a big main line of the Nf3 variation. White overprotects the pawn on d4. White will develop his queenside entirely before even worrying about his kingside. After Be3, White usually plays Qd2 and Rb1/Rc1. With Rc1, White's idea is to quickly protect c3, following up with the d5 strategic threat. }
8... Qa5 9. Qd2 { The main line by far. } 9... O-O
{ ...Nc6 is the main line. However, this scores slightly better lately and I believe is a tricky more order to play against if White does not know the theory ! Also, we make White move the rook before taking on d4 ! Keep this small nuance as a reminder of the line ! }
10. Rc1 { The main line by far. } 10... Nd7
{ This is a really interesting alternative which scores well for Black. White has overprotected d4 and c3 so much that our most common ideas do not work in this position. However, we also have the thematic pawnbreak ... e5 ! This is our plan in this position. Note how 10... Nc6  (intending ...e5)  does not work due to d5 from White. This is the reason why we play 10... Nd7 !? This option has been used by many elite GMs, for example: Vachier-Lagrave, Svidler, Morozevich... The main line is ...Rd8, and also interesting is ... cxd4, which is the second option used by Black in this position. }
11. d5
{ The main alternative and in my opinion a more challenging option than the most played line. We should know how to play this position not to end up in a poor position. }
11... Nf6 12. e5 Nd7
{ Black has a really difficult time after ...Ng4 Bf4 !. White has won every game following that line so far. }
13. Bh6 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxf8 Kxf8
{ Black has a great compensation in the resulting position. } 16. g3 b5
{ See Sarkar-Gledura, Gibraltar  (2017)  , where ... Kg8 was played. Black ended up winning a very convincing game thanks to the big initiative generated on the queenside. After the recommended move, Black's plan is to prevent White's counterplay and slowly improve his position on the queenside. }
