{ This is a really interesting alternative which scores well for Black. White has overprotected d4 and c3 so much that our most common ideas do not work in this position. However, we also have the thematic pawnbreak ... e5 ! This is our plan in this position. Note how 10... Nc6  (intending ...e5)  does not work due to d5 from White. This is the reason why we play 10... Nd7 !? This option has been used by many elite GMs, for example: Vachier-Lagrave, Svidler, Morozevich... The main line is ...Rd8, and also interesting is ... cxd4, which is the second option used by Black in this position. }
11. Bd3 { is the main move. } 11... e5 12. d5
{ Whites main option at this point. 12. dxe5 is not a problem for Black. We can just take on e5, exchange and play ...Be6 ! eventually, with some new lines open for our pieces after the bishop exchange on e6, with counterplay and more options to create passed pawn than White in a potential endgame. See Gledura-Vidit, Malmo  (2018)  . }
12... b5
{ We are playing in both sides of the board ! Keeping flexibility and with a rich position. }
13. O-O c4 14. Bc2 Qa3
{ We improve the scope of our queen. We are not in a hurry as White does not have any active options at the moment that we should worry about. }
15. Rb1 a6
{ An interesting novelty. Here I want to depart from the analysis in 'A Practical White Repertoire with 1.d4 and 2.c4. Volume 2: The King's Fianchetto Defences' by Alexei Kornev, who analyses 15...Rb8 as Black's response.  So, what is the idea behind this novelty? We do not define yet our structure and intentions with the b4 pawn break, keeping our options open while we improve our position.   ...Rb8 and ...a5 happened in Pashikian-Nepomniachtchi, Aeroflot op.  2010  . I have included the game as a reference. Black played a really good game and ended up winning. }
16. Qc1 Qd6 17. a4 Rb8 18. axb5 axb5 19. Ra1 f5 20. Ra5 Nf6 21. Nd2 Qd8 22. Qa3
Rf7
{ Making room for the bishop on f8 and controlling the 2nd rank. The position is objectively about equal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation - 7.Nf3"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Nf3 23"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3
{ 7. Bc4 is the main line and the classical option. Nf3 is considered the modern approach  (compared to Bc4)  of the Exchange Variation. In these lines, White intends to develop his pieces to natural squares: Nf3, Be3, Be2 and O-O.  In the long term, White's idea is to consolidate his centre with d5 and eventually c4. We must keep in mind that the best approach will still be the same and we should play in the Grunfeld's spirit ! The main idea to keep in mind is that, contrary to what happens in the 7. Bc4 lines, we have the annoying thematic pin: ...Bg4. }
7... c5 { Challenging the center immediately. The best move order. } 8. h3
{ This move became briefly popular after the match Kramnik-Kasparov, Wijk aan Zee  (2000)  . Then, it was not seen much in the elite for a while, but now it seems to have experienced another burst of popularity at the top level. }
8... O-O 9. Be2
{ Is the main move, and now that White prevents ...Bg4, I recommend playing }
9... b6
{ Here I like this logical idea. We try to underline the fact that 8. h3 could just have been a loss of time, as mentioned by Krasenkow in his analysis. }
10. Be3 { I want to show you an example line of how to play this variation. }
10... Bb7
{ We also fianchetto our light-squared bishop, that is the idea of ...b6 now that ...Bg4 is not an option because of h3. }
11. Qd3 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nc6 13. O-O e6 14. Rad1 Qd6
{ Black is doing fine. See Baldauf-Michalik, AUT-chT  (2018)  . There is still a lot to discover in this variation, and the theory is likely to evolve in the next few years. The good news is, as this variation evolves, our course will do so as well in order to be up to date with the current theory. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation - 7.Nf3"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Nf3 24"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3
{ 7. Bc4 is the main line and the classical option. Nf3 is considered the modern approach  (compared to Bc4)  of the Exchange Variation. In these lines, White intends to develop his pieces to natural squares: Nf3, Be3, Be2 and O-O.  In the long term, White's idea is to consolidate his centre with d5 and eventually c4. We must keep in mind that the best approach will still be the same and we should play in the Grunfeld's spirit ! The main idea to keep in mind is that, contrary to what happens in the 7. Bc4 lines, we have the annoying thematic pin: ...Bg4. }
7... c5 { Challenging the center immediately. The best move order. } 8. Rb1
{ The absolute main line in this variation and with an interesting idea which is not really obvious. This is also the pet line of Boris Gelfand. Rb1 is a consolidatory move, as Rowson first defined it in his book on the Grunfeld.  White prophylactically takes the rook off the long diagonal, where it is vulnerable to the attack of our dark-squared bishop once he decides to advance his center with d5. Now it will be possible to play d5 in many lines, sacrificing on c3, but without leaving the rook en prise. This move also plays against our ...Bg4 ideas, putting indirect pressure on d4, as our b7-pawn would not be defended anymore. }
8... O-O 9. Be2 { By far the most important of White's options at this point. }
9... cxd4
{ We are not obliged to take on d4, solving White's problem with the pawn structure and releasing the pressure against the center. However, it is tactically justified and we will play a game in which we will have a static advantage  (the extra material as we grab a pawn)  and White will enjoy a dynamic advantage.  It used to be common knowledge that Black needed to memorise a lot in this variation. Now that is not exactly true and it has been proved that Black is fine and comfortable in the main lines if we play reasonably. 9... Nc6 and 9... b6 are other options which are perfectly playable. }
10. cxd4 Qa5+ { The beginning of the trip to the queenside for our queen ! }
11. Qd2
{ Far less popular than Bd2, the main line. However, it is not bad and we should not lower our guard. }
11... Qxd2+ 12. Bxd2 b6
{ The main move and the most logical one. As White is ahead in development, playing both ...e6 and ...b6 will mean that he will be even more ahead ! We will connect our rooks and undermine White's centre whenever he advances his pawns ! }
13. d5
{ A respectable alternative. However, Black is fine in this variation. As soon as White advances his d-pawn, there is one thing we should remember: the control over c5 has been released ! }
13... Na6 14. Be3 { Preventing ... Nc5. } 14... f5
{ Black here plays a good move. Apart from attacking White's centre, ...f4 is also a threat. The bishop would have to leave the diagonal that he defends and then ...Nc5 would come next ! }
15. Bc4 { A better try than e5. } 15... Kh8 16. e5 f4 *

