13. d5
{ A respectable alternative. However, Black is fine in this variation. As soon as White advances his d-pawn, there is one thing we should remember: the control over c5 has been released ! }
13... Na6 14. Be3 { Preventing ... Nc5. } 14... f5
{ Black here plays a good move. Apart from attacking White's centre, ...f4 is also a threat. The bishop would have to leave the diagonal that he defends and then ...Nc5 would come next ! }
15. e5 { The most popular option at this point. } 15... f4 16. Bd4 Bf5 17. Rc1
Nb4 { This is really good for Black. } 18. Bc4
{ White's best option here would be to sacrifice the d5-pawn with O-O, but Black would just be better. }
18... Nd3+ 19. Kd2 Nxc1 20. Rxc1 Rfc8
{ See Hertneck-Kasparov, Munich  (1994)  . White could have played better, true, but it is easier said than done when you play against Kasparov ! }
