[White "Exchange Variation - 7.Nf3"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Nf3 26"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3
{ 7. Bc4 is the main line and the classical option. Nf3 is considered the modern approach  (compared to Bc4)  of the Exchange Variation. In these lines, White intends to develop his pieces to natural squares: Nf3, Be3, Be2 and O-O.  In the long term, White's idea is to consolidate his centre with d5 and eventually c4. We must keep in mind that the best approach will still be the same and we should play in the Grunfeld's spirit ! The main idea to keep in mind is that, contrary to what happens in the 7. Bc4 lines, we have the annoying thematic pin: ...Bg4. }
7... c5 { Challenging the center immediately. The best move order. } 8. Rb1
{ The absolute main line in this variation and with an interesting idea which is not really obvious. This is also the pet line of Boris Gelfand. Rb1 is a consolidatory move, as Rowson first defined it in his book on the Grunfeld.  White prophylactically takes the rook off the long diagonal, where it is vulnerable to the attack of our dark-squared bishop once he decides to advance his center with d5. Now it will be possible to play d5 in many lines, sacrificing on c3, but without leaving the rook en prise. This move also plays against our ...Bg4 ideas, putting indirect pressure on d4, as our b7-pawn would not be defended anymore. }
8... O-O 9. Be2 { By far the most important of White's options at this point. }
9... cxd4
{ We are not obliged to take on d4, solving Whites problem with the pawn structure and releasing the pressure against the center. However, it is tactically justified and we will play a game in which we will have static advantage  (the extra material as we grab a pawn)  and White will enjoy the dynamic advantage. It used to be common knowledge that Black needed to memorise a lot in this variation. Now that is not exactly true and it has been proved that Black is fine and comfortable in the main lines if we play reasonably. 9... Nc6 and 9... b6 are other options which are perfectly playable. }
10. cxd4 Qa5+ { The beginning of the trip to the queenside for our queen ! }
11. Qd2
{ Far less popular than Bd2, the main line. However, it is not bad and we should not lower our guard. }
11... Qxd2+ 12. Bxd2 b6
{ The main move and the most logical one. As White is ahead in development, playing both ...e6 and ...b6 will mean that he will be even more ahead ! We will connect our rooks and undermine White's centre whenever he advances his pawns ! }
13. O-O { The main line. } 13... Bb7
{ This move is key. We want to provoke d5 from White in order to release his control over some dark squares, especially c5. }
14. d5 Ba6
{ Now, after d5 has been played, we want to exchange the bishops and develop with tempo. }
15. Bxa6 Nxa6
{ Now a forced sequence follows as White will feel really uncomfortable by allowing ...Nc5. }
16. Be3 f5
{ Again ! With queens exchanged and given White's center arrangement, this is thematic ! }
17. e5 f4 18. Bc1
{ White needs to keep the d-file clear to defend on d5, otherwise we play Rad8 !, winning the pawn ! This is one of the lines where you can see the problem of advancing White's mobile center too quickly and too far ! }
18... Rad8 19. Rd1 Nc7 20. d6 exd6 21. exd6 Ne6
{ And Black has a very comfortable endgame which is safe. Here Svidler made a good point about the passed d-pawn in the Grunfeld: 'In the Grunfeld in general the passer on d6 either wins pretty much straight away, especially when White has the bishop pair against bishop and knight, or it's safely blockaded and not a major concern for Black.' }
22. Bb2 Nc5 { Recycling our knight to block White's passer on the d-file. } 23.
Bxg7 Kxg7 24. Rb4 Rf5 { Black activates his rook and has an equal endgame. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation - 7.Nf3"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Nf3 27"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3
{ 7. Bc4 is the main line and the classical option. Nf3 is considered the modern approach  (compared to Bc4)  of the Exchange Variation. In these lines, White intends to develop his pieces to natural squares: Nf3, Be3, Be2 and O-O.  In the long term, White's idea is to consolidate his centre with d5 and eventually c4. We must keep in mind that the best approach will still be the same and we should play in the Grunfeld's spirit ! The main idea to keep in mind is that, contrary to what happens in the 7. Bc4 lines, we have the annoying thematic pin: ...Bg4. }
7... c5 { Challenging the center immediately. The best move order. } 8. Rb1
{ The absolute main line in this variation and with an interesting idea which is not really obvious. This is also the pet line of Boris Gelfand. Rb1 is a consolidatory move, as Rowson first defined it in his book on the Grunfeld.  White prophylactically takes the rook off the long diagonal, where it is vulnerable to the attack of our dark-squared bishop once he decides to advance his center with d5. Now it will be possible to play d5 in many lines, sacrificing on c3, but without leaving the rook en prise. This move also plays against our ...Bg4 ideas, putting indirect pressure on d4, as our b7-pawn would not be defended anymore. }
8... O-O 9. Be2 { By far the most important of White's options at this point. }
9... cxd4
{ We are not obliged to take on d4, solving White's problem with the pawn structure and releasing the pressure against the center. However, it is tactically justified and we will play a game in which we will have a static advantage  (the extra material as we grab a pawn)  and White will enjoy a dynamic advantage.  It used to be common knowledge that Black needed to memorise a lot in this variation. Now that is not exactly true and it has been proved that Black is fine and comfortable in the main lines if we play reasonably. 9... Nc6 and 9... b6 are other options which are perfectly playable. }
10. cxd4 Qa5+ { The beginning of the trip to the queenside for our queen ! }
11. Bd2 { The main move by far. } 11... Qxa2
{ Our queenside pawns become a long-term asset. However, White has reasons to believe his position is solid and promising too. }
12. O-O
{ So. Why would White want to play such a position with a pawn less, granting Black with two passed connected pawns on the queenside ?  1  White has a large lead in development. However, his bishops will have to move again as they occupy passive squares.  2  f7 and e7 are weak against White's bishop, and also the kingside is not very well protected with the knight gone.  3  White can try to establish domination with the central control, changing the play from one side to the other of the board. Luckily, we can prevent this from happening with }
12... Bg4
{ Trying to consolidate the material gain, developing and annoying White. } 13.
d5
{ An independent sideline worth taking a look at. White's rook can no longer annoy the queen as our bishop controls the whole diagonal. Also, we have an easier task undermining White's centre with either ...e6 or ...f5. }
13... Nd7 14. Rxb7 Nc5 15. Rxe7 Bf6 16. d6 Bxe7 17. dxe7 Rfe8 18. Bc3 Nxe4
{ ...Rxe7 loses on the spot due to Qd4 ! } 19. Ba1 f6 20. h3 Bf5 21. Bb5
{ White is clearly better. } *

