7... c5 { Challenging the center immediately. The best move order. } 8. Rb1
{ The absolute main line in this variation and with an interesting idea which is not really obvious. This is also the pet line of Boris Gelfand. Rb1 is a consolidatory move, as Rowson first defined it in his book on the Grunfeld.  White prophylactically takes the rook off the long diagonal, where it is vulnerable to the attack of our dark-squared bishop once he decides to advance his center with d5. Now it will be possible to play d5 in many lines, sacrificing on c3, but without leaving the rook en prise. This move also plays against our ...Bg4 ideas, putting indirect pressure on d4, as our b7-pawn would not be defended anymore. }
8... O-O 9. Be2 { By far the most important of White's options at this point. }
9... cxd4
{ We are not obliged to take on d4, solving White's problem with the pawn structure and releasing the pressure against the center. However, it is tactically justified and we will play a game in which we will have a static advantage  (the extra material as we grab a pawn)  and White will enjoy a dynamic advantage.  It used to be common knowledge that Black needed to memorise a lot in this variation. Now that is not exactly true and it has been proved that Black is fine and comfortable in the main lines if we play reasonably. 9... Nc6 and 9... b6 are other options which are perfectly playable. }
10. cxd4 Qa5+ { The beginning of the trip to the queenside for our queen ! }
11. Bd2 { The main move by far. } 11... Qxa2
{ Our queenside pawns become a long-term asset. However, White has reasons to believe his position is solid and promising too. }
12. O-O
{ So. Why would White want to play such a position with a pawn less, granting Black with two passed connected pawns on the queenside ?  1  White has a large lead in development. However, his bishops will have to move again as they occupy passive squares.  2  f7 and e7 are weak against White's bishop, and also the kingside is not very well protected with the knight gone.  3  White can try to establish domination with the central control, changing the play from one side to the other of the board. Luckily, we can prevent this from happening with }
12... Bg4
{ Trying to consolidate the material gain, developing and annoying White. } 13.
Bg5
{ A theory giant and the main line of the 8. Rb1 variation. The active way of defending d4 is considered the best attempt for White. We give back the material gained in order to catch up in development and complicate the position. }
13... h6
{ We want to limit the dark-squared bishops scope by making it go somewhere else. It is key to understand the idea behind this great move. White has to make up his mind now about the future of the bishop: 1  If he decides to take on e7, we will get a quick counterplay. 2  If White decides to play Bh4, it will lose its influence over the c1-h6 diagonal. 3  If White decides to play Be3, our e7-pawn is not targeted anymore. }
14. Be3
{ The main move by far. Compare this position to 13. Be3. The difference is, indeed, the pawn on h6. Black weakens his kingside slightly, however, we also prevent White from using the g5 square for his minor pieces. White will try to keep our dark-squared bishop attached to defending h6. Also, White will have ideas linked with Bc4, targeting the g6-pawn, as the f7-pawn would be pinned. }
14... Nc6 15. Rxb7
{ Again we see this idea in a different position. It is important to understand the nuances. However, our play will be similar to the line without including h6. }
15... Rab8
{ Offering the exchange. Whites rook is more active, and when the exchange happens, our rook on b8 will be more active than the opponents rook on f1. }
16. Rxb8 Rxb8 17. h3
{ White threatens Qc1, a strong move. Fortunately, we have a strong reply. }
17... Bd7
{ The small nuance I mentioned. When we have played h6, the bishop should go to d7 instead of exchanging on f3 ! Now we defend our knight against Whites threat: Qc1. }
18. d5 Ne5 { A pawn sacrifice at a good moment ! } 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Bxh6 a5
{ Black has a slight advantage. White missed the point and went off on a tangent by capturing on h6. Our a-pawn runs very fast. }
