[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation - 7.Bc4 - 10...Bd7 - 11...b6N"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Bc4 - 10...Bd7 11...b6!?N 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4
{ And we reach the second-to-last chapter of the book. This is the classical choice of the Exchange Variation and it is also the most played option in the Grunfeld. White's idea is to continue the development with Ne2, avoiding the annoying pin with ...Bg4 after Nf3. In order to execute his plan, c4 is pretty much the only square the bishop can go to. The position of the bishop has been widely discussed among theoreticians. On the one hand, it could be vulnerable to future attacks  (...Rc8 or ...Na5)  . This means that, potentially, we may gain some tempi. }
7... c5
{ We challenge White's centre straight away. The 'd4 battle' will be a tough one ! }
8. Ne2
{ The main move by far and what makes sense after 7. Bc4. An alternative which transposes to the main line is 8. Be3 O-O 9. Ne2 Nc6. White also has the chance to transpose the 8. Nf3 variation after 9. Nf3. }
8... Nc6 { Note that against 8... Bg4, White can reply with f3 ! } 9. Be3 O-O
10. O-O
{ Is the main move which leads to the well-known tabiya of the 7. Bc4 variation. }
10... Bd7 11. Rb1
{ The absolute main move of this variation. This move also happens to be the only one that scores above 50% at this point. }
11... b6
{ An interesting novelty in which we sacrifice a pawn for great compensation and initiative in the endgame. Bear in mind that this novelty leads to somewhat drawish positions, so depending on the situation, you may prefer to choose 11... Qc7, which is the main theoretical option and is covered in a separate chapter. }
12. Qd2 { White decides not to take the pawn. } 12... Qc7
{ We are threatening ...cxd4 and ...Nxd4, then the bishop on c4 would be hanging. }
13. Bd3 Rad8 { We want to continue with ...Na5 now. } 14. Rbc1 Na5
{ This will be our standard plan if White does not accept the sacrifice. Eventually, we will challenge the center with ...e5. Black is doing fine in this position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exchange Variation - 7.Bc4 - 10...Bd7 - 11...b6N"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Bc4 - 10...Bd7 11...b6!?N 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4
{ And we reach the second-to-last chapter of the book. This is the classical choice of the Exchange Variation and it is also the most played option in the Grunfeld. White's idea is to continue the development with Ne2, avoiding the annoying pin with ...Bg4 after Nf3. In order to execute his plan, c4 is pretty much the only square the bishop can go to. The position of the bishop has been widely discussed among theoreticians. On the one hand, it could be vulnerable to future attacks  (...Rc8 or ...Na5)  . This means that, potentially, we may gain some tempi. }
7... c5
{ We challenge White's centre straight away. The 'd4 battle' will be a tough one ! }
8. Ne2
{ The main move by far and what makes sense after 7. Bc4. An alternative which transposes to the main line is 8. Be3 O-O 9. Ne2 Nc6. White also has the chance to transpose the 8. Nf3 variation after 9. Nf3. }
8... Nc6 { Note that against 8... Bg4, White can reply with f3 ! } 9. Be3 O-O
10. O-O
{ Is the main move which leads to the well-known tabiya of the 7. Bc4 variation. }
10... Bd7 11. Rb1
{ The absolute main move of this variation. This move also happens to be the only one that scores above 50% at this point. }
11... b6
{ An interesting novelty in which we sacrifice a pawn for great compensation and initiative in the endgame. Bear in mind that this novelty leads to somewhat drawish positions, so depending on the situation, you may prefer to choose 11... Qc7, which is the main theoretical option and is covered in a separate chapter. }
12. dxc5
{ In my opinion, the main move of this novelty variation should be accepting the pawn ! }
12... bxc5 13. Bxc5
{ White can also accept the pawn on this move. However, this gives us a comfortable follow up with }
13... Qc7
{ We are threatening ...Ne5, as both of the bishops are hanging. Now for example the game could continue with }
14. Be3 Ne5 15. Bb3 Rad8 { We are threatening ...Bb5 now. } 16. Qc2 Bc8
{ A very interesting idea ! We want to recycle our bishop to a better diagonal, from where it will exert some pressure, apart from controlling the thematic c4 outpost. }
17. Bf4 Ba6 18. Rfd1 Qa5
{ Black does not have any problems and has sufficient compensation for the pawn. }
*

