[White "Exchange Variation - 7.Bc4 - 10...Bd7 - 11...Qc7"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Bc4 - 10...Bd7 11...Qc7 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4
{ And we reach the last chapter of the book. This is the classical choice of the Exchange Variation and it is also the most played option in the Grunfeld. White's idea is to continue the development with Ne2, avoiding the annoying pin with ...Bg4 after Nf3. In order to execute his plan, c4 is pretty much the only square the bishop can go to. The position of the bishop has been widely discussed among theoreticians. The main drawback for White is that the bishop could be vulnerable to future attacks  (...Rc8 or ...Na5)  . This means that, potentially, we may gain some tempi. }
7... c5
{ We challenge White's centre straight away. The 'd4 battle' will be a tough one ! }
8. Nf3
{ Generally speaking, the bishop on c4 and the knight on f3 do not work well together against the Grunfeld. }
8... O-O { We are ready now to keep challenging the centre. } 9. Be3 Nc6 10. h3
{ A different approach from White, avoiding ...Bg4. We should know that we have no problems, but I would like to give you an example line for you to feel confident when facing it: O-O transposes to 9. O-O eventually. }
10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qa3 { The queen can be very useful on a3 ! }
13. Rb1
{ White's best continuation at this point. It is well-known that 13. d5 ?! does not work in this position. See Salinnikov-Kovalev, Alushta  (2000)  to see how useful the queen ended up being on a3 ! }
13... Rd8 14. d5 Na5 15. Be2
{ This happened in Ahlander-Eriksson, Malmo  (2000)  . And now Black should have taken the a2 pawn instead of playing ...e6. }
15... Qxa2 16. O-O Bd7
{ With a double-edged position, as highlighted by Avrukh in his analysis. } *

