1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4
{ And we reach the last chapter of the book. This is the classical choice of the Exchange Variation and it is also the most played option in the Grunfeld. White's idea is to continue the development with Ne2, avoiding the annoying pin with ...Bg4 after Nf3. In order to execute his plan, c4 is pretty much the only square the bishop can go to. The position of the bishop has been widely discussed among theoreticians. The main drawback for White is that the bishop could be vulnerable to future attacks  (...Rc8 or ...Na5)  . This means that, potentially, we may gain some tempi. }
7... c5
{ We challenge White's centre straight away. The 'd4 battle' will be a tough one ! }
8. Ne2
{ The main move by far and what makes sense after 7. Bc4. An alternative which transposes to the main line is 8. Be3 O-O 9. Ne2 Nc6. White also has the chance to transpose the 8. Nf3 variation after 9. Nf3. }
8... Nc6 { Note that against 8... Bg4, White can reply with f3 ! } 9. Be3 O-O
10. Rc1
{ This move is a serious alternative to O-O. White is provoking ...cxd4, followed by ...Qa5+, but, why ? What is the idea behind this mysterious move ? Well, White wants to continue with h4, therefore he does not want to castle. At the same time, the rook on c1 defends c3 and the bishop on c4, which is a weakness at the moment. }
10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Qa5+ { Black's main and most logical continuation. } 12.
Kf1
{ By far White's main move in this position. White will try to launch an attack against our King. Also, note how White prefers to play Kf1 over Bd2. What do you think is the reason ? Well, losing the right to castle is better than affecting the central coordination and control, which is the biggest treasure White has in these positions. }
12... Qa3
{ A great move, it deserves at least one '!', but I think it should have one and a half at least ! This move has been played by Svidler and Anand, among other elite grandmasters. This movement's idea is two-fold: 1  We want to play ...Na5, attacking White's light-squared bishop. 2  We prevent h4, as . ..Bg4 would be really annoying as f3 is not possible because the dark-squared bishop would be hanging ! }
13. Rc3 { By far White's most used move. } 13... Qd6 14. h4
{ White's logical follow up after Kf1. If White delays this with, for example, f3. Then we can replay by attacking the centre with Rd8 ! }
14... h5
{ We are better off by preventing that pawn from advancing more at this point. }
15. f3 Rd8 { Exerting pressure on White's centre. } 16. Kf2
{ This allows a tactical solution with } 16... Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Bxd4 18. Bxd4
Qxd4+ 19. Qxd4 Rxd4
{ And White had decent compensation for the pawn in Grego-Kolodziejski, e-mail  (2009)  . A draw was agreed, however Black does not risk anything by continuing the game. }
