[White "Exchange Variation - 7.Bc4 - 10...Bd7 - 11...Qc7"]
[Black "Exchange Variation: 7.Bc4 - 10...Bd7 11...Qc7 13"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Bc4
{ And we reach the last chapter of the book. This is the classical choice of the Exchange Variation and it is also the most played option in the Grunfeld. White's idea is to continue the development with Ne2, avoiding the annoying pin with ...Bg4 after Nf3. In order to execute his plan, c4 is pretty much the only square the bishop can go to. The position of the bishop has been widely discussed among theoreticians. The main drawback for White is that the bishop could be vulnerable to future attacks  (...Rc8 or ...Na5)  . This means that, potentially, we may gain some tempi. }
7... c5
{ We challenge White's centre straight away. The 'd4 battle' will be a tough one ! }
8. Ne2
{ The main move by far and what makes sense after 7. Bc4. An alternative which transposes to the main line is 8. Be3 O-O 9. Ne2 Nc6. White also has the chance to transpose the 8. Nf3 variation after 9. Nf3. }
8... Nc6 { Note that against 8... Bg4, White can reply with f3 ! } 9. Be3 O-O
10. O-O
{ Is the main move which leads to the well-known tabiya of the 7. Bc4 variation. }
10... Bd7
{ This positional approach is my recommendation. There are many other alternatives here for Black, and many of them interesting. However, apart from the fact that this variation scores well for Black, I believe it fits well in our repertoire and I have found some interesting ideas. Some elite GMs have played this move many times, like for example Vachier-Lagrave and, notably, Svidler. }
11. Rc1
{ A logical alternative. White indirectly defends the bishop on c4 in case there is a pawn exchange on d4. Note that White sometimes starts with 11. Qd2, but it transposes after ...Rc8 12. Rac1. }
11... Rc8 { Responding in kind. } 12. Qd2 { The main move in this variation. }
12... Qa5 { We are threatening ...cxd4, entering a very good endgame for us. }
13. d5
{ An important alternative that we should know, as it is one of the main motifs to understand about the Exchange Variation in the Grunfeld. White has achieved one of the strategic aims of this variation: playing d5. So, what do we get in exchange for allowing this ? We will never allow White to play a comfortable c4 ! Our plan now is to prevent White from consolidating his position, we will gather our efforts around the c4-square. Another idea is to play the pawn break ...e6 in the right time. }
13... Ne5 14. Bb3 Qa6
{ In order to understand this move, you should be aware of the fact that we almost never want to play ...c4 in this position. That would make it easier for White to find squares and an active role for his pieces. Instead, our plan is to place our knight on c4 ! Then, we have the plan of playing ...e6. If White plays c4 himself, then we have a very tempting pawn break with ...b5 !, generating great counterplay on the queenside. }
15. Bg5
{ An alternative that makes sense but that was never embraced. White is better off playing c4 in the end it seems. }
15... e6 16. dxe6 Bxe6 17. Bd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 Rfe8
{ And now yes ! It makes sense to follow up with ...Nd3 and ...c4. See Georgiev-Ftacnik, Bled  (2002)  . }
*

