13... Bc8
{ A move that has been used before by Vachier-Lagrave and Mikhalevski, among others GMs. }
14. Rd1 { This is the universal reply to ...Bc8. } 14... Na5
{ I think this novelty becomes a really strong asset for this variation ! I have to confess that it was not easy to make up my mind between this move and ...e6 !?, which is also interesting. And now, let me show you an example of how this game may look like: }
15. Qa3
{ The queen exerts some pressure on the queenside, which is one of White's ideas. }
15... c4
{ And this is the key of ...Na5. We will play the pawn break ...e5, but in a slightly different order, which I believe gives us better chances than starting with 14... e5. }
16. Bc2 b6
{ We secure the a7 pawn and the knight on a5 before continuing with ...e5 ! }
17. f3 e5
{ We will probably play ...f6 first, giving space for our rooks to double-up on the f-file. We may recycle our knight via b7-d6 and then, once we are ready, we will break with ...f5 !? It is a complicated position which may require lots of maneuvering and prophylaxis, but in my opinion the position is in fact really rich with ideas and interesting to play ! Isn't that what we are looking for in the Grunfeld ? }
