{ If you have been studying the previous chapters, you may have the right feeling that this move should not give us many problems, it is actually what we want to happen ! }
12... Ne5
{ This move has only been tried once in high-level games by Shishkin. In my opinion, ...Ne5 is a slightly better move than ...Na5 in this position. Apart from keeping an eye on c4, we have other moves in mind like ...Ng4. It is the flexibility what made me choose this one over ...Na5. In a5, the knight is too restricted in this case without having full control over c4 unlike in other variations. }
13. Bd5 Rab8 { White's light-squared bishop will have to move soon! } 14. a4
Rfd8 15. Qc2 e6 16. Bb3 Ng4
{ They key of the variation in my opinion, this is why I prefer ...Ne5 on move 12. }
17. Bf4 Be5 { much better than 17... Ne5 } 18. Bxe5
{ Is positionally bad for White. } 18... Qxe5 19. Ng3 Qxc5
{ Black is clearly better. White still needs to find roles for his pieces and we have an easy game against White's uncoordinated position. }
