{ This is the main move at this point in the 10... Bd7 !? variation. It has been played regularly by elite GMs like Vachier-Lagrave or Svidler. 11... b6 !?N is analyzed in a separate chapter. }
12. Bf4
{ This is the main move. However, it does not score very well for White  (around 47%)  . }
12... e5
{ 12... Qc8 is the main line. However, I believe I have found an idea to bring this variation back to life ! }
13. Bg3
{ This is the main option. A move that has been analysed before and that is thought to give White the advantage, but I cannot agree with that evaluation. }
13... Rad8
{ I believe this is the strongest continuation for Black. We are threatening ...cxd4 now. }
14. Bh4
{ This move is highlighted by Svidler as a good move for White in his analysis. The super GM gives ...Rc8 now for Black, but then White gets a really beautiful position and Black suffers. However, I recommend this interesting idea: }
14... exd4
{ A great positional exchange sacrifice ! Black will get a great compensation with a strong dark-squared bishop. }
15. Bxd8 Rxd8 16. cxd4
{ This is the only move that has been played in the only game in this variation, according to my database. }
16... Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Bxd4
{ This happened in Fitiak-Vokarev, Izmailov Memorial  (2011)  . Black has sufficient compensation for the exchange and has no problems in this position. Note how strong is the dark-squared bishop, who has no counterpart, by the way ! }
